cslb_other_changes: During the past several weeks he has displayed a reluctance to go up or down any stairs. I assist him with patience and compassion in managing the stairs in order to work through this new issue.

"We lost our chocolate lab in mid-April, which has affected how much time Abby is active. She also appears ""sad"" by her sprawling on floor and looking up dejected. Might be anthropomorphic but still it best describes what I see. "

When Sherlock is being walked on leash and we come upon either a stranger or a familiar person, I am able to retain his attention upon me or have him settle quietly while the person and I talk. If, however, he is off-leash in our yard for a potty break and someone is walking on the street, whether known or unknown, he races towards them barking, and it is sometimes difficult getting him to break off and return home, especially if the person continues to walk away.  There is nothing wrong with his eyesight, as he is able quite easily to spot people walking dogs, jogging, deer in the yard, the black cat on the driveway, or squirrels in the tree.
He was a rescue and had trust issues. He is trusting other people more, but is still aggressive with other dogs which we are working on.

Mandy has developed a needy type of attitude in the last 6 months.  If I am at my computer, she will take her nose and put it under my knee telling me to get up.  She will either lead me to the kitchen - look at her bowl then the fridge OR take me to the door to go out.  She is also getting up in the wee hours and will put her nose close to your head (while sleeping) and either snort or cry until you get up.  She also has become super attached and does not like me leaving her alone.  She gets depressed and mopey if I leave for too long.  I try to have someone at home with her at all times.
There was a period of about two months after neutering last year that Drake was a little less friendly to unknown dogs, but he returned to his dominant but cheery attitude.
She is getting smarter chasing squirrels and rabbits.  A lot more using her nose to track them down.

Zoe is refusing to go in the back yard with me if I request it. She will go on her own or following our other dog but is nervous out there with me. I believe this is related to recent baths and her fear of water.
Odie used to be a rapid eater, now he eats about half the volume at meal time and will eat the remainder through out the day.

No, she is on nutrients to help prevent that.  She has lost a lot of her sight, but she knows her home and yard and does not have a problem navigating.  Also, the contractor who rebuilt my home loved my pups so there is a wooden walkway from the House to the barn.  I think Mia uses that and the deck to gauge her location in the yard.  There is also a wooden walk along the back chainlink fence that helps her navigate, these have been here since she has been here.    She is not my first vision-impaired pup.  My Niki was almost blind for the last 3 years of her 16 years.  She loved cats and always adopted one or two.  Her last cat is still with me and provided her with assistance, vision and aggitation.  Never left her side until I can home each day.
Slightly less time spent playing, and more time spent napping
No, his thinking does not seem to have changed.
We think he might be loosing his hearing.
He seeks out more human attention (COVID)
Difficulty seeing last step in a flight of stairs.
He is minding better.  Will come now more consistently when in situations where he doesn't want to come and he wants to do what he wants, but then makes the decision to do what I am asking him to do.
She doesn't eat well at all compared to 6 months ago, but her inflammatory bowel disease has been under poor control, so probably that.
Jaxson is still very reactive to the sight of other dogs

"Lucy has never been a dog that likes being picked up or hugged. She gives ""kisses"" usually when asked, but doesn't want lots of hugs. That said, when my husband or I am not feeling well, she'll come up on bed or sofa when called. "
Lily is becoming much smarter as she gets a little older.  She is currently going through a phase of trying to get her way when I want her to do one thing and she wants to do something else.

"We have been working on his ""Pomeranian"" shyness about being pet.  He likes people but he is slightly apprehensive about being pet.  He is better about being pet now but it remains a struggle.  (He likes it when I pet him but he doesn't want to be pet too long -- even by me.)"

Not sure if this is what you're looking for but he sometimes spends much more time during walks sniffing everything in sight. I have to really work to get him moving. It's not every walk, so it could just be something as simple as a female was walking the same path just before we got there, but when he was younger he was alway motivated to keep moving as far and fast as he could.

She is more likely to try to wander the neighborhood. She has made a friend of the neighbor's dog behind us and will sit at his fence with him for long periods of time, refusing to come when called until we get close to her.
none that i can think of
He was diagnosed with a tumor in his chest and is on gabapentin for pain control. At night he stands and stares blankly and pants. In the day he is fine, but at night he seems confused.

About 12 months ago it became more apparent that Wilson was experiencing increased loss of vision especially at night. If he doesn't orient himself using physical cues in our bedroom (such as walking to a rug in the hallway and turning himself around) he has attempted to jump on our bed in the dark and been completely parallel to it/lands on the floor. He generally does use the physical cues but probably once a month he appears to forget and doesn't make it onto the bed. This does not happen when lights are on so it's unclear if it's vision or cognitive or both.
She seems more inquisitive and interested in what others are doing.
Been using cbd drops for couple of months and actually seeing improvements in eyesight and movement.
Luna went blind about 18 months ago. I believe her struggles or behaviors are not based on cognitive issues but are due to her lack of eyesight.
Less barking at or even noticing people coming to the house (mailman, delivery drivers, familiar visitors).
She quit using the stairs to get up on the couch and the bed.   I think she can't see them well when getting down.
Not yet - she's still sharp as a tack and the most intellectual dog I've ever known!
Has become less active - tests show might have very early Addison's but still learning more.
none. i think changes in Mira's behavior are due to her mobility and digestive issues
She is just as intelligent and quick as ever
She doesn't always want to go on a walk which is completely out of character for her.  She gets tired more easily.

she wants to please very badly and if she thinks her agility performance at a trial was not good she gets very depressed,   If she thinks she did well she struts back to her kennel wagging her tail dancing.  The key is to not show signs that she made mistake .
Olive seems to have developed some apprehension to participate in training.
Much less activity due to hip injury.
Slight change in her eating habits.  No longer goes for food immediately as it is put down, sometimes she will only eat if she is hungry.  she is self regulating when it comes to food
Lately, she is reluctant to go for a walk in the morning (dark) hours. Some walks are interrupted because Zinni wants to return quickly.

When ther eis another dog on the street (one we don't know) he sometimes doesn't realize there is another dog near him till they sniff him or he sees it. He used to sense another dog was near sooner. My dog still likes his toys but doesn't play with them much anymore
No. Oscar is very mentally sharp and although he is a bit older, he still has energy like he did when he was a puppy.
We got a puppy, so that has made Ruby much more active. She has also lost some weight (after putting on puppy weight) and I think that is helping her too
None. Cooper has always been a 'thinker' who will stare at the wall.

She seems a bit more calm, now that she's less of a puppy.  For the first year at least she had two modes: frenetic and somnolent.  Now that she's an adult she tends to be just active and alert when she's not snoozing.  She only gets over excited now when a new person enters the house, which isn't happening much these days.  She still wants to insist on playing sometimes, but if I ignore her, she calms down.

"Although the pacing is seldom, there was an entire week recently when she paced the room every evening.  It stopped as suddenly as it started.  Her startle reaction is heightened, but it's not often because her hearing is now impaired a bit.  I startle her at times if she doesn't hear or see me coming.  She is much less apt to come to me for her eye drops (not painful) or anything else.  It's as though she's saying, ""Hey, I'm old.  I'll do what I want.""  (I don't blame her a bit.)"

Charlie is a certified service dog but over the past year has made the adjustment to staying home more like a pet based on my own change of circumstance and a move. He has adjusted well to staying home with a six year old female Haveshon and is happy. But, he can step up to his service training in an instant as required which never ceases to amaze me given that there is not a continual reinforcement of his commands nor practice. He has overcome his early separation anxiety behaviors in the past two years. However, given the choice he remains close to a human, myself or my wife when we are at home or when he is out with us. He is well-adjusted and a delight for everyone who meets him. He exhibits natural propensity to be a therapy dog too. (Hope this helps)
This is hard to gauge since we have been home full time with Meribel due to the Pandemic. She still loves her walks and is very playful but is also sleeping more than she used to
He has learned to whine more for human food.
He seems a bit more depressed- he lays around more and makes noises like he's bored.  I think it's pandemic-related b/c we don't get him out as much.

He had a TPLO surgery in April 2020, so 6 months he was still recovering physically (hence why his activity is slightly more now than it was 6 months ago). This isn't related to his thinking or processing ability, instead physical recovery.
He seems to vocalize during dreaming more now.
Not really.  I think she's just as bored/stir crazy as the rest of us due to COVID.  And she only walks into doors or walls occasionally when walking before looking!
Our older dog died six months ago, and Penny showed signs of grieving.  We now have a new puppy, who is keeping her on her toes.  She is getting lots more play exercise.

She has always been especially  fearful of loud or strange noises, fireworks being the worst and this last 4th of July her fearfulness lasted much longer than in previous years  (it took her a few weeks to be comfortable going outside as nightfall approached.    We live in an area where almost unlimited fireworks are allowed, so it pretty intense.
Sirius occasionally barks (once) in the middle of the night.  there doesn't seem to be a reason.  it isn't often, perhaps once every couple weeks.

He is very aggressive with his father, who, in turn is aggressive with him. But this is due to an intact female coming into heat at the same time his dad had major surgery and due to hormones and pack standing, we are pretty sure
Cecelia is maturing and becoming calmer as she grows Ito adult hood
Sadie has always loved food/treats, but she seems more obsessed with food now. She grabs for offered treats rather than taking them gently.
Ernie is an old soul that loves to lounge around. He is constantly thinking though and is very responsive. He also hates getting out of his bed in the morning.
flinching - as if seeing something in front of his eyes - shadows of hair or floaters?

The only change has been that he stopped urinating and defecating in the house in the last 6 months. He was neutered and we put up a privacy fence which both helped with his indoor elimination issues.

Due to covid my shift at work has changed. I was working straight days m-f but over 4 months I have been working 4 shifts varying 8-14 hours, then off 3 days in a row. Marnie had a difficult time adjusting.  She became much more needy as in attention and snuggling. She appeared confused as each shift differs in time leaving and returning. After about 4 weeks Marnie appeared to understand her new schedule. She currently eats breakfast and supper at different times each day but she remembers the meal hours before covid and still attempts to alert me at the pre covid time. Some days she can still hold her urine a long shift and other days she will urinate on the concrete basement floor. She has done this a few times while I am home and able to let her out.
chewing things up more if left alone
Not really. He hates us leaving, barks crazily but settles down after car is gone. Also barks and jumps to window at outside people/noises- this hasn't changed
Sleeps more and deeper sleep.  Takes louder or more motion to wake him up.
In order to get attention, Buster will whine at the alpha person for petting time or to sit in his lap.  I can call him over and that does stop the whining.
No changes.. still has mind of her own, i.e. stubborn at times.
His intelligence has grown as he has aged

Miles will sometimes just decide to ignore me if I'm asking him to do something he doesn't want to do that he didn't used to (like if I'm letting the other dog outside, he had been jumping up too but now he sometimes just wants to stay on the couch).

Irene was a rescue and has been with us just over one year.  She exhibited some fairly serious separation anxiety manifested by chewing household items to destruction when left for more than about thirty minutes.  Over the last year, with time and understanding this problem has been resolved.
Exhibiting some signs of separation anxiety when left with the same person he's always been left with.
I have not observed any changes in this area yet.

"Parker barks more at people/dogs/cars since we stopped socializing with other dogs and their owners (due to COVID.). Parker has always been very friendly with strange dogs and people so I had to leash him on our off-leash walks when social distancing was recommended.  I can now usually keep him from greeting everyone and from chasing bicycles by giving him the ""Stay Close"" command.  But I have noticed that he barks more when he sees people, dogs, cars, bicycles - even if they are far away.  It's actually been helpful on walks because he warns me that someone is coming so I can put on my mask.  "

Since we've all be quarantined and are home all day, my dog will sometimes go into another room to sleep in the evenings.  This happens multiple times per week and I think it's because we are around her much more and she wants her alone time.
none she is as spry as she has always been
He is a little slower, 10-1/2 years old.  Just slower because of age
I believe she is losing her hearing.
Barking more at noises outdoors and when doorbell rings.

We call Watson our scaredy cat. He's afraid of thunder, the wind, fireworks, and other dogs. It seems to be getting worse as he ages. Houston recently had 2 days of rain and wind; Watson whimpered the whole time. When we walk Watson (and Holmes, our pit bull mix) and we see someone else walking their dog, Holmes ignores the other dog but Watson gets scared, barks at the other dog, and refuses to walk until the other dog is out of sight. The next door neighbor has a pit bull and 2 large mixed breeds. When Watson is in our back yard he will often start wailing as if he's afraid those 3 dogs are going to come though the fence (it's a sturdy wooden fence).
She is not 6 months old yet. She is 5 months and 9 days.

A dog that Gypsy was obsessed with passed away and she showed anxiety and depression in not ever seeing that dog anymore on walks and she tended to act more aimless on walks.  She has recently found a new pair of dogs to obsessively track down on walks.  When Gypsy saw/smelled the deceased dog's owner on a walk (without the deceased dog), Gypsy got very excited and ran to her and then sniffed her, but was clearly disappointed not to find the dog.  Gypsy was obsessed with this dog ever since it barked meanly at her while on a walk and she clearly held a grudge.

Dewey is sleeping much more than six months or a year ago. He also is urinating inside the house once or twice a week now, something he's rarely done in all the years I've owned him.   He appears to be completely deaf now so he is very attentive about watching people's faces and he seldom wanders off, much more attached. He's never been particularly affectionate so I don't see much difference in this respect.

Sylvie is very outgoing and friendly to people and other dogs, but she is not as outwardly affectionate to some random strangers. She does not display any fear or aggression, but she seems indifferent toward some people who approach her. She is now approximately 18 months old.
Her sleeping patterns during the day, because my husband is always home, seems rather distant...like she doesn't realize I'm home. And she always slept with him during the day...
Due to covid restrictions, we have been working from home since March. As a result, we have noticed her social separation anxiety has increased slightly. She prefers the pack to stay together. ;)
Unsure if this is thinking/information processing, but after his leg was amputated he sometimes has trouble laying down, and will circle extra times or whine at me about it.
Same level of activity...same loveable pup

"Walter seems, what we like to call, ""under-served"" in the past six months. Since we are home all day, every day (due to the pandemic) he seems largely bored and unsatisfied. I am sure it is confusing because, even though we are home, we are still busy working and cannot devote significant portions of our designated workday to pet-attention.  "
She has definitely slowed down physically, but her cognitive abilities are about the same.
Her thinking and cognitive processing seem the same
No, he is just now almost 1 year old so I think any changes would be related to that.
He is an 11 month old puppy. He has developed amazing problem solving skills and sometimes seems smarter than us!  He loves to figure things out.

she likes being alone sometimes. sometimes she wants to sit with us while watching tv, sometimes she goes into another room to sleep. this has only really happened since we're home much more during covid.
Diagnosed with diabetes about 8 months ago, lost most of his vision around that time.
she is doing really well  with her training since she started classes 2 months ago: heeling, staying, walking on a leash. she is very trainable.

Rascal has always loved jumping into people's laps. In the last six months he has become more reluctant to do this, sometimes staring at the lap but not launching himself into it. However, he still jumps readily onto chairs and sofas on which he is allowed to go, so if this is a physical issue, it appears at this time to be a mild one.

If anything, she is a little bit sharper.  We joke about her aging Benjamin Button style.  We suspect she is much less anxious than she was previously, which is allowing her to attend to stimuli better.  She now looks in the direction we point and successfully retrieves treats from a puzzle board (which she does by sliding a circular shape on a track).
She has neuritis of cranial nerves 7 and 8. She has episodes where she stares multiple times a day. Over the past 6 months, the frequency of episodes has increased.

"Alex seems to be more in sync with me with regard to things she should pay attention to, e.g. inexplicable noises outside or around the house. I interpret this as a sign of maturity and a faint hope that she will improve upon her ""ranch security"" duties."

He is very keen on finding ways to communicate that he would like an extra cookie, apple slice, or whatever he is wanting.  He gives a pathetic sounding wuffle when he wants a boost onto MY bed so he can take a nap after breakfast!  Fully capable of jumping up there, but that's no fun when mom could help me and oh yeah, give me a little rub down while she's there!  I can see his eyes shifting side to side when he's thinking something up!
At 12 years of age, Tobi continues to be bright and alert. I imagine (though I didn't know her when she was younger) that she sleeps more now.
no. though I think he's getting cataracts. He's not as accurate at catching the Frisbee as he used to be.
Over the last 6 months she has become more agitated and barking at strangers especially men.
he acts more bonded to me, needing to be by my side. When we visit at our best friends (mine and his), he is anxious about being separated from me.

Gabby continues to learn more tricks and commands as she ages.  For the first two years, Gabby did not take treats.  Once I found treats she enjoys, teaching her to be calm when we walked past dogs on the sidewalk has become easier.  Gabby only within the last year has been more motivated by food (will be 5 in two weeks).  She still does not finish 2 cups of kibble per day on a regular basis. So in the last 6 months Gabby has become easier to teach and with improved thinking and processing.
Nothing. He's the same dog as always
We had to put our other dog who was 15 down about a month ago. Lila seems more attached since then and lays closer by us throughout the day.

Moose is slower to respond to his name than 6 months ago. Sometimes I have to repeat commands several times before he seems to understand, such as coming in the house. He used to quickly follow me, now he doesn't seem to grasp coming into the house
In the woods we go in everyday, if I get just out of her sight she barks an alarm. She started doing this in the last year or so.
Still goes to bed with me, but gets up more in the middle of the night to lay on the couch in the living room with my husband if he is awake watching TV or something

"Walter is more territorial about the house -- he barks more loudly and more frequently when the mail carrier arrives, or when he sees people he doesn't know outside. But he also seems to have a strong recognition capability, and only barks at *unfamiliar* strangers or dogs when he sees them outside the house (when he's sitting in the window), and has learned quickly not to bark at the gardener, the in-laws of the next-door neighbors who visit regularly, etc. He has also picked up on new words (""pupsicle"" for a frozen treat, for instance) and learned new behaviors (waiting to hear the word ""okay"" before he eats his food) *without* formally being trained on these."

I don't notice a change in the thinking or information.  I do notice that she spends a lot of time laying down on her bed, but not asleep.  I actually didn't notice that behavior until your initial questionnaire.  While she lays around alot on her bed, she doesn't appear to be sleeping.  This is not a new behavior, but one that has been  going on for years.
some real good days, some slow days...she's pushing 18 that we know, still very affectionate, loves her food and treats...has good days when zooms all over the yard and goes  for long walks

(My older dog, I didnt do the study on him, it said to only do 1 pet in the household, I did the younger one assuming he'd have more time to age & collect information from, but my older dog he's about to turn 14 and he's just starting to show signs of all these questions you asked me.  He walks the back yard in circles and does the staring into space.  Like he has dementia.  Breaks my heart. )
Less active due to seasonal weather, less daylight hours and less time outside

"She is very smart. We have another dog and when they play, he runs more than she does. No apparent changes in the dog's essential cognition but an occassional tremor in the head. I am curious as to what that is.
He seems REALLY happy because we are home with him all the time.
Poppy is more engaged with attention seeking (petting) largely because more people at home during day (old parents) here all day petting dog all day long

His hearing has declined very rapidly over the past 4-6months. I think it's a little bit nice for him, though, because he sleeps more deeply and is generally less anxious. No physical causes of the change in hearing (no infection, trauma, etc), but probably related to the cognitive decline already noted in his behavior.

Just in the last couple months, he has started to dribble on the floor when I get home.  He has always greeted me at the door and jumped with excitement to see me.  But a few times when I set my things down and pet him, he dribbles on the floor.
"He has become food oriented/motivated. When he used to not even eat unless he was hungry. Now he makes sure to let you know when he ""thinks"" its meal time. "
He seems to get more excited and lungs/jumps up at person coming in to house. Also when playing with him, he gets very excited pushing at me and lunging/jumping up on me.
She has always chased squirrels, she's a First.  This summer she taught herself how to lie in wait, stalk and use concealment.  She caught 4 squirrels this summer.  None in the past.
He has been more active and playful since we stopped the prozac

She had to have surgery for a ruptured CCL in late July 2020. She has struggled to recover from this as her back got very tight and needed some muscle relaxers to help her move better.  During this time, I feel like she's become a little less active -- it's now that I notice sometimes, she'll lay on the floor and stare under the sofa for longer periods of time than usual.
She has gotten better at finding her toys in brush or wooded areas when playing fetch.
She has been harder to train new behaviors to.  It is taking longer to do.  Can't run with me as long before she needs a break due to heavier breathing and panting, increased heart rate.
He seems to remember things better.  Exactly where he spotted an iguana previously, for example.

I think Ricky will bark at me more to get my attention if he wants something: to play or go for a walk.  I think he might also mope about (not aimlessly but perhaps lying on the couch or floor) because we do not go to the dog park or doggy dare care as much due to the pandemic. But I think that's understandable.
No, he's still pretty crisp and on the ball.

We haven't noticed any changes in her thinking or information processing. She experienced an upheaval 12 months ago when her fur brother Bandit passed away. Since then, she has become more vocal: howling and wooing when she wants attention or something to do.  Now that she is the only pup, she eats more slowly than she did when Bandit was alive!

Her ability to hear well has certainly decreased causing decreased information processing.  Often she misinterprets sounds ---for instance, when she hears the ding of an incoming text on my phone, she barks and goes to the front door thinking its the doorbell.

We have struggled with her off-leash recall since we adopted her five years ago.  Recently, she seems to have finally made the connection that coming back results in good things and means she can usually return to exploring.
No. She is still a puppy
No. Violet is active and exhibits normal pointer working dog behavior.

Dexter is five years old; my wife and I are 72. We have a lot more cognitive decline than he does. I call him Dexter the Great Observer. He watches us constantly and figures out how to put that to best use. He seems to be continually learning and getting smarter.
I definitely see him trying to learn more now than he did six months ago when he'd just look at me like I was crazy or something. Now I can see him actively working to understand and get it right.

Covid deprived us of our regular activities.  She couldn't travel with us because we didn't travel. Her grandma can't stay with us like she normally does, so the child us deprived of attention.  I don't think her being sad sometimes is age related. Its more that she gets less attention and entertainment compared to what she normally gets.
I put him on a homemade food diet for the past 4 months and he is doing amazing!
He is still very active hikes and or runs up to five miles a day. More devoted to my grandchildren. Loves to sit with ever the littlest one (6 months) and let her lay on him.
Goldie should have been a DEA bomb or drug sniffing canine!  she is so smart & smell sensory is stunning.

Not sure if she just can't hear or if she is having difficulty understanding what I need her to do.    We'll be walking on the beach, I'll call her to come. She heads toward me and then stop and look at me when she is halfway to me.

"I did notice early in the pandemic, Birdie also seemed stressed or out of sorts at times. This has abated but I do see more ""neediness"" from her lately. She more frequently wants to lay directly on top of me if I am sitting on the couch where in the past, she would be next to me. "
No, but I'll be weaning him off his Prozac shortly.
A little more aggressive towards other dogs he does not know, when first meeting them.
No change does not do any of the items listed.

She is pretty much the same as the day she arrived in our home the end of March, 2017.  BTW, on her medical records, they have her age wrong.  I first met her as a nursing puppy (though mother was trying to wean), in November, 2012 in Haiti, so she would have been born in September, 2012.  The medical records say she is 9 years, 10 months today, November 24, 2020, but she is actually 8 years, 2 months.  I am absolutely sure about this.  She never barked in Haiti, or for the first perhaps two months with us, but our three other dogs taught her how it is done, and she is now the biggest barker. The other thing...our other three dogs are male.  Though she squats and empties in the backyard, she lifts her leg and marks while on a walk.  Another learned behavior.
She is more mature and stronger now. She understads and obeyis commands much better and she has more strengh to run and fetch for longer.

Swinton has a degenerative back issue, (possibly neurological) but has been on Prednisone for the past 6 month sand is doing considerably better due to that.  It has created a few other issues, ( eating and drinking more, resulting in going to the bathroom more frequently), but he is able to walk much better and no longer has the pain and sleeping issues, head shacking, etc,... that were very bad.  Swinton can no longer climb stairs or jump on furniture, and he needs support when pooping, or he will fall backwards, but, overall, he is happy and we are home to be with him during the Pandemic, and thrilled he is with us.

"Given how old he is, he still has his puppy-ish moments> attempting to ""romp"" while on walks, even though it wears him out after 10 seconds. But increasingly less often than a few months ago. He's also getting incrementally more ""stubborn"", but not overly so. "
I have noticed signs of aging like diminished eyesight in some situations and difficulty differentiating between same tone colors and things like that.  I think she is slowing down a bit.
She's the same as always.  She came from a hoarder (one of 85 dogs) and still has most of the quirks she came with.  She is starting to have a little trouble with stairs.
Since I have gone back to work he is very visibly upset and fidgety around the time I leave every day. He is only alone for approximately 4 hours a day.

Actually, Sonny seems to be able to repeat tasks asked of him better as he ages.  As a younger dog he did not like repetition, i.e., if he was asked to search for scent in scent work, once he did it he was done.  Now he will work at it again multiple times.

We purchased a puppy in the last six months.  The puppy has changed the life of Fede.  She plays with the puppy, runs in the back yard, seems to want to teach the puppy how to behave and keep the puppy out of trouble.  I wish Fede wasn't sick because they are good for each other.

I feel like over the last 6 months he is better at understanding words and non verbal cues.  Over this last 6 months my husband has worked from home, which I think has been good for Truman cognitively

He is very smart and figures problems out.  He is a jack Russell.  I have an interactive game that we played but it figured that out quickly. Funny story, when he was a puppy , I was paper training him to potty on the paper.  He was so good, I had the newspaper on my end table and he jumped up there and potties on it. I just had to laugh.
Old man is starting to lose his hearing and has a bit harder time following/finding balls during daily fetches. Also having more issues with hip mobility that make it harder to get up.
We have gotten Cabby new cognitive puzzles in the last six months and she has figured them all out.  And is training us on when she wants a treat from the puzzles.
Not really anything.  She is alert as ever and has quite a vocabulary she has learned over the years.

My dog has been diagnosed with spinal stenosis of the C-5 vertebrae.   His hind legs seem weaker now, and clumsier.  Three weeks ago fecal issues showed up.   He drops stools in his sleep. I plan to monitor his daily behaviors and stay in close contact with his Vet so that I can give him a quality of life.  Obviously, he is now fully retired from any Service Dog duties; except for little non stressful tasks within our apartment, which he self initiated. However when she meets another dog - even a stranger to her- she is animated and coquettish and instigates play.  She notices children playing and seems to look longingly at them wanting to engage with them. She clings rigidly to our routine and gets antsy/bossy if we vary it. She is much better at leash walking since having been spayed but she still usually explores off-leash. He experienced two seizures for the first time in the last 6 mo, both after being bathed and going upstairs shortly afterward. He hates baths and always as. Titan is now 10 1/2 months old.  He has definitely matured in the last six months.  He is a very smart dog, and knows where to go to get his toys, and will pass by shoes or socks, to get his his chew toys.  He loves to chew, and will spend an hour or two a day chewing.      Titan is not terribly interested in his dog food; he will eat when he is hungry and often leaves food in his bowl.  But when he is hungry, he will pick up his empty food bowl (or one of our other dogs' bowl) and knock it around.        He is nervous around new people, and even some of our friends that he has met before.  It can take three or four interactions for him to greet them without growling, barking, or ruffling the fur on his back.  Although there have been a few people he has taken to immediately.  He is also very nervous around children and low growled at our friend's three children for almost their whole 15 minute visit.  Obviously, they were not allowed to interact, and he will not be around children without extremely cautious supervision.    He is very affectionate with my husband and I, and will take naps cuddled up with us, and lay on the couch with us.  Although, he also enjoys his own space, and chooses to sleep in his crate.  He will snuggle when it is 'bedtime', but as soon as I turn off the light and settle down to sleep, he will get up and go to his crate. (Even if I try to coax him to stay.)      Finally, he has recently begun a new and strange behavior.  In the evening, when napping in the living room while we watch TV, he will suddenly wake up and jump up in my lap like he was startled and scared of something.  He will then paw at me before setting down in my lap.  (He is now about 65-70 pounds, so it is a little funny to see him scared.)
Not really. He has always had a phobia of floor surfaces. By that I mean he seems fearful of falling on hardwood and tile floors.

No changes recognized. His only poor behavior is reacting to large vehicles and other dogs when we encounter them and we are working on training for that and is gradually getting better.

Instead of runs every day, it is more like every 2-3 days and weekends especially we stay in. We do find plalces to run but our favorites are not as accessible. ( I have 3 dogs so even though all are socialized - it is harder with 3 dogs as then tend to appear as a pack to other dogs and people).
Nathan is more willing to find toys that he has left in other rooms rather than just barking in frustration.

Argus had a seizure today, a bad one.  We had been weaning him down from 125mg twice a day and for the past 2 weeks, he's only been on 25mg once a day.  We will be in touch with the vet on Monday when they open, fortunately, we still had some of his higher dose so we are already titrating him up.
no changes in the last six months

Rocco is amazing.   He's very strong for his age and food driven and lives going for his walks and I let him take his time and sniff.  He walks better in colder weather.   He loves his routine.  We are retired so home a lot so he gets lots of attention.   My vet calls me a helicopter dog mom. Lol.

Rocky knows what time we go for walks in the morning and the afternoon. My office is just above the living room (LR) where his bed is. In the last couple of months he has gotten more insistent that it is time to go on a walk--and starts to pace back and forth in the LR alternatively laying down, getting up, pacing, jumping on his ottoman laying down there, and then repeating. He seems to have gotten more impatient as he has gets older. If I come over and tell him to lay down and stay, he seems to be able to calm himself down. This has also happened sometimes in the evening before bedtime. He starts to pace, and can't seem to calm down, but when I get stern with him and tell him to go to bed he eventually calms down. We live in the foothills of the Rockies and I think that sometimes he is smelling deer, elk or bobcats outside but it has happened pretty frequently and thus I wonder if its a cognitive change.
She is a sheltie so is always on the alert. As she ages she is becoming more so and more of a guard dog to noises and strangers outside.
She sometimes becomes agitated in her crate where she sleeps at night, and we have to let her out.
He has become more comfortable with new people
changes are physical, not cognitive-at least not yet
Some difficulty in following directions due to increasing deafness, it seems, but not sure if this is cognitive.
"He has learned a few new ""tricks"" and is offering the ""new tricks"" before offering the tried and true, such as a handshake, when we is begging for food. "

6 mo ago my son, daughter in law and 1 year old grandson moved in with us.  Mishka has had to learn to deal with a 1 year old and more people living in our house.  It means more social interactions just based on the number of people and she has been super adjusting to my grandson.  One of the best dogs possible around a small child.  She has always been more interested in people than dogs or cats.  She isn't aggressive to other animals, she just ignores them.  But she will always walk up to any person on the street for a pet.

She seems to be more active, however I attribute this mostly to me working from home due to Covid, so we've taken longer and more frequent walks. I think she's just adapting to getting more exercise. We both enjoy it :)
He is getting deaf, making it hard to call him or give him directions

"-- She is slightly less active now than 6 months ago because *we* can't take her out as much.  -- Since she's 14 years old, we don't expect to see any changes in her ""thinking"" (although perhaps they're there, but we're too old to notice them!)"
Perhaps some slight cognitive decline, but Tubby is also blind so it's hard to tell if he is experiencing confusion due to him being blind or other reasons.
Fiona seems to be doing very well . She has been consistent for the last six months. Physically she has slowed down to a bit but is still very active.
Because I have been working from home so much, Sadie is much more depressed when I leave. My mom says she will stare at the road waiting for me to get home.
The same covid issues we all have, life has changed for all us including our pets.

My dog spends more time alone, sleeping in a quiet spot. She used to only sleep near where her people were. My dog also seems to prefer sleeping on a blanket on the floor, near my bed and no longer prefers sleeping in the bed with me.
he is getting better behaved every day...still scared to death of thunder and lights flickering and is an ankle nipper but only for delivery people in his yard.
None that I can think of.
"The older he gets, the better he gets at communicating his wants and needs to us. Whether it's a slight ""woo"" and a glance to the door or nudging our hands to give him pets."
No but starting to slow down and his cataracts may be  interfering with his night vision.
He's become jealous of me taking our younger dog to daycare on the days I go to the office. He's even acted out a few times and my husband watched him pee on things after I've left.
She sleeps all the time.  She wakes occasionally for pets and snuggles. She still is a voracious eater.
She has started to chew at her hind legs. At on them, in the air towards them.

I started working from home in March due to Covid-19, and just this week went back to the office full time, so his behavior this week has been a little off this week as we are re-adjusting.  Also, we just went through a Hurricane, and went 5 days without power, which seemed to throw him for a loop - wasn't eating after dark, and wasn't interested in playing after it went dark.
Not Gracie, as she is only 2.5, but our 14 year old, whom I did not register with you, as I didn't think she would live this long (!) does ALL of the 1st page.

Six months ago it was summer now with the weather colder we spend less time outdoors. She also started a pain medicine indicated by her decreasing activity. (Gabapentin) Within a month she was back to her active self. As for her thinking, she is as sharp as ever.

Jordy is six years old and has been a certified therapy dog for 4 1/2 of those years. The trainer suggested I certify him because he's calm, loves all dogs and all people, and has no issues, so I'm very careful to keep him in training, so we can someday go back to hospitals, schools, and care centers. I watch for any behavior changes.

Quigley will chase things that are not visible to me. He'll go off in the woods and come right back. He is sleeping much more throughout the day. He is now more anxious about changes in habits and then is incontinent of urine.
She appears to be a bit more stubborn and doesn't listen/obey as well as she used to when asked to do something.
She has recently developed some fence aggression where she'll bark at dogs on the other side. She never used to do this.
She has started to have occasional anxiety, which seems to be related to any change in her routine.

Has stopped coming upstairs or downstairs but I think it's more related to her confidence of doing it. One set of stairs has treads the other completely carpeted. She use to come up every night and sleep in our room. She no longer does this. And she use to go down to the basement when Jim works there or we're working out and she no longer comes down. She does stair down the basement stairs if we leave the door open.
He doesn't jump on people as much.
"No changes; ""she acts 1/2 her age."" Glenn Escherd, Lili's vet; ""she'll live forever."""

"She has continued to develop her problem solving skills.  Much of this growth we believe are extensions of her ""wild"" instinct-driven behaviors. He was very sick over the last 6 months, so now he feels so much better and is much more social.
None. He is smart, witty, happy and often mischievous as always.

"Tico has changed a great deal over the past half-year. He paces continually, has difficulty ""settling down"" to rest, seems confused, as if ""in a fog,"" and is urinating & defecating in the house. Previously, he never did these things."

No, but I did want to note for the 'avoid petting question' Kahlua goes to work with my husband several days a week. She considers being at the shop as 'work time'. Unless it is a person who she has interacted with outside of the 'work setting' she will not let them pet her. She has also never been a fan of strangers petting her in general. She just bobs, weaves, and ducks away from their hands.
She is startled more often. I believe her hearing is diminishing, so she isn't always aware that someone has come near her, so once she realizes it, she is surprised.
We don't train as often as we did prior to the pandemic and shutdowns. Jeff has gotten a bit lazier but I don't think it is cognitive related.
Covid has made it interesting that she always stays next to me and when I leave it is a little more operation anxiety than before

Freya has become more clingy in the past 6 months. When I'm sitting down reading or watching TV, 6 months ago she might sit at my feet but more often she would choose to lie down in another room. Now, she's most likely at my feet or a short distance away.

She has gotten more toy interested since her younger sister joined the pack. Same parent dogs 2 yrs difference in age. Even more high energy and excitement in having a playmate her size and energy level. Starting to actually catch and release balls and toys instead of always wanting just to play tugs.
no changes but she is young
Gnash picks up on desired behavior pretty quickly, and is also very keen to hide such behavior if he does not want to stop.
No has a seizure once (roughly once a month) in a while so kinda foggy after that ...

He has lost his sense of smell or eyesight some.  Or both.  He does pretty well, but, especially when going after a toy and excited, he sometimes runs into things.  And he begs for food, but he sometimes doesn't see it fall.
none - with a change in my work schedule - being able to work from home due to the pandemic, Ellie's level of activity has increased - for the better!
She is more focused on food - that is often the reason for the pacing.  She starts the pacing about an hour before her regular food time.
no, but he Is more active because of the quarantine and us walking him more.
He has become more intuitive on what we want or what the situation is.
decrease in activity due to increased problems with hip dysplasia, therefore no long walks or trips to dog park

Then when we relocated to our beach condo in NJ we had more strong storms with high winds and thunder. Plus when we're outside we're masked and so are any other people she sees. So, her extra anxiety, esp. when we leave the house without her, and also leave with her but go in the car, is understandable. I don't believe her thinking of info processing skills are diminished. We're all adjusting to the new normal - and missing our old lives.
seems much more interested in smelling other dogs marking areas for longer periods of time
He's a lot calmer, which I am guessing is just a part of him maturing.
"Possibly some slight hearing loss or choosing to ignore commands  (specifically ""come"" when sniffing or checking out something)"

She spends a lot more time on a leash since we moved to a more urban area. Her leash behavior has gotten much better. She's also learned she can bully our other dog. Uses this to claim the prime dog bed, or dropped food, etc.
He is a growing puppy so becoming more familiar with objects, routine of the house.
She continues to learn new things :)
Annie has shown any changes in the last 6 months.
My dog seems to be kind of superstitious, which is hilarious to me. He will only walk one way around tables.

"We moved houses, so she has had more anxiety (""velcro"" dog, peeing inside as we establish a new routine/exit). She also is now avoidant of stairs after not being allowed to go upstairs onto carpeted area in previous house."
Maybe he sleeps little more often.

This is difficult to answer as Boomer is 14 years old.  At this time the changes are more physical than cognitive.

She's more addled than she was in the late spring.  She's still happy but she's slowing down more.  She's forgetting which door she has gone in all of her life.  She won't go on the porch anymore and it's not that she can't, it's like she doesn't even think about it as an option.  Clove is also forgetting to eat so we entice her to eat and then she'll drink water like she's in a daze and just can't stop.

He used to nervously pace at bedtime, get in a dog bed that's in our bedroom, and then as soon as we rustled the sheets of the bed, he'd jump out of the dog bed and start pacing. We moved the dog bed recently and that stopped it. He's gotten more needy as work from home has stretched on.
He is 4-1/2 months old.  He seems to be catching on more to what he is supposed to do.

"Duke has always been a ""sheriff"", did rounds checking the house. Smallest noise would trigger a bark fest. He's never been a relaxed pup. In recent months, this has intensified. He's highly nervous, on watch, light sleep, less deep sleep. "
Marley will be 13 in February and doing really well. We rescued another dog a year ago and they play together which has gotten her moving more.
she still acts like a playful puppy, picking up toys to get her playmate (dog) to play with her, spinning in circles.
She has become slightly more dependent on me. She wants to be with me all the time.
Sleeping a little more during the day. No changes seen yet in cognitive behaviors
Because of advancing blindness and hearing loss his cognitive abilities are changing. It's difficult to determine if the cognitive changes are due to this or advancing age.
No. Still very much an active happy dog

Digby has always been a little terror but he seems to be mellowing out with age. For example, if he started barking at another dog (the enemy, and almost all dogs are enemies) when we were on a walk he'd keep it up for blocks, even though other dog was long gone. Now he still barks, but it's short duration or not at all.
Less interested in playing with other dogs once she meets them. She's more independent
He has grown out of most puppy behaviors (chewing objects other than his toys)

I feel like her social intelligence is finally maturing. She doesn't run up to other dogs and immediately try to stand on their heads with her front feet. It's like she has finally clued in that other dogs don't appreciate that!

His critical thinking and problem solving has become much more evident. He's quick to learn new things and very eager to do so. He's become much more capable of associating different words with different objects and tasks.

Sometimes he is less food motivated, even a few times turning away from food. Over the past 6 months, it has gone from never (e.g. always being food motivated) to a few times a week he does not care about food.

In September we noticed occasional labored breathing and some weight gain, and she became significantly less active.  Vet diagnosed Hypercalcemia (which had been noted 5 months before) and found a mass on a right parathyroid.   Parathyroidectomy was done on October 14.  Lulu has recovered from the operation and now  has normal calcium levels and appears to be as active as before the problems began.

Roughly 6 months ago he has increased aggression towards our young toddler (growling, baring teeth when he would approach despite being separated by a gate). We believe it was a combination of low grade depression (we've had our routine upended like most), and the toddler being increasingly mobile. In the 6 months since, he has calmed a bit and we're trying to come up with creative outlets for his suspected excess energy.
In the past two weeks, he has tripped going up steps in a hurry, so I wonder if his eyesight is diminishing. Looking into his eyes there is no appearance of cataracts, though.

He is more affectionate with me. He was a puppymill product and had FHO surgery early in his life. His first home was rough with him, and the last four years have been baby steps toward dealing with his fears of everything, including being touched.

She was never trained to do this She will not approach any person but me without their asking Just sits in front of them wags here tail and makes eye contact Then if invited she will get close and likes to be petted
No. He's been pretty much the same; active, alert, friendly, and intelligent.
He whines when he wants something. It almost seems like frustration because he hears us speaking, does not understand and is trying to communicate.

Henry has become increasingly intelligent and intuitive in anticipating our (his parents) activities and behaviors.  He has also continued to hone his internal clock for meal times.  No kidding --- he knows EXACTLY when it is 5:30 pm, or 8 am or 12 pm --- and starts to alert us five minutes before the precise time.  He's amazing.
Tache did get startled by a street sign and barked at it. A first???
She understands commands better (she is now 10 months old) and doesn't bite as much. She still enjoys chewing on furniture.
sudden loud beeping sounds like from fire alarm - now make her jumpy and she shivers for a little while even if the beeping sounds have stopped.
"He tilts his head while ""listening"" to me talk to him, tilting back and forth when I say different words, especially if in the form of a question. This is more frequent now than in the past."
Sleep/wake cycle disruption more prominent. Even more scent oriented on walks, stops and sniffs a small area for several minutes.
She seems to me needier than in the past. Wanting to come in and vocalizing her wants more. Always sits by door and over reacts when someone walks by.
She follows us around the house more since we are home a lot more.

"Our family adopted a 2nd dog 6 months ago. He is smaller and younger than Winston. Prior to then, Winston was an ""only dog"" and was not social with other acquaintance dogs. No, his brain seems as good as ever. He might have slowed down slightly, which indeed is a blessing as Blue has always had an enormous amount of energy.
As she reaches 2 yrs old, we are noticing less puppy like behavior.  She's still hyper, given her mixed heritage,  that's not surprising.  She slightly less hyper, all the time.
No noticeable changes over the past six months
no changes notes at this time

Princess Beyonce is still as sharp as ever. She stilk knows the sound of her daddys truck when he comes home. She still is the momma of the pack. She still has the same attitiude shes always had. She is still the same emotional bag that shes always been. She still expetcts to do what she wants to do when she wants to do it. If she potties in the right spot she still covers it up like shes hiding it. The ONLY 2 diffrences that weve noticed is that she is getting more white on her face and her voice sounds hoarce when she howls from wanting attention or being lonely. Thats the ONLY 2 things.

"He is more socially adaptable, as in when introduced with other dogs he listens to their social cues more than he did 6 months ago. We recently moved to a house with a yard, so he has more consistent but less intense exercise than when we were in an apartment (chuck-it sessions for exercise). Work from home, especially with the yard, has seemed to make him more comfortable/less defensive and much more cuddly :)

Because of COVID, we've all been stuck at home more, so needless to say our dogs are also stuck at home more and are a bit bored (especially since there's fewer dog park visits).   Pumpkin discovered that if she sits up and does a begging movement with her front paws, it gets attention, and so she now indicates she needs something that way (no matter what it is). We're still working on ways for her to indicate what she needs, although if I list off a few things at random, she usually reacts excitedly to the right one. I'm thinking of training her to ring a hanging bell on the door if she needs to go potty, because she's certainly smart enough to learn that.
Increased (unexplained) anxiety - especially in the middle of the night.
She's slightly less responsive to directions that she used to respond to really quickly.

We have a new neighbor after the apartment next to us being vacant for over a year; they also have an ill-trained dog.  Indy (my dog) is much more vigilant in the apartment now, keeping track of their noises and their dog's barking next door.
She has more learned behavior having attended two different obedience classes.
My dog Jack is probably more attached as we are working from home. So he seems a little less independent.
Nicky spends more time wanting to be with me. She moves around well and will follow wherever I go. She also has changed her day time sleeping area from her usual bed to several different closets.
We find our dog adapting more to our schedule and habits.  Less puppy-ish/headstrong.

We also have a 15 year old Shih-Tzu who is deaf and has cataracts named Scooter. Scooter barks a lot. If he wants to go out and I don't let him, because he's always barking at the door, he gets Muffy. He rarely goes out without her. If Scooter goes out with Muffy and doesn't pee right away, I send him back out. Muffy will go back outside so he will follow her and wait until he pees. She seems to have begun watching out for him, like an older sibling would but they're not related and she's 5 years younger. We got them from a rescue shelter. The previous owner got Muffy, who was a puppy to be company for Scooter.
Mocha continues to learn new words and to respond to her basic commands.  She initiates games and has a number of favorite toys that she can identify and retrieve on demand.
Calmer, although still very headstrong.  Fewer bursts of the zoomies
He's slightly more active because (I think) I retired this summer and he wants to always follow me or see what I'm doing, he gets longer walks too.

Harvey has good and bad days but I believe they are more pain related, due to his spondylosis, rather than cognitive decline. When he hurts, he refuses food and attention, sometimes for a full day, but with increased pain meds and massage, he comes around, He is overdue for chiro treatment, but because he hates it, I have been reluctant to send him into the clinic on his own. May have to.
Appears deaf. Eyes are watery and cloudy. I think shes losing her sight. We acquired a new puppy. There is one short playtime between them daily otherwise Pixie sleeps. Lost weight feels bony.
There have been changes in activity but it is likely due to extended confinement from major orthopedic surgery.
Seems to be a teensy bit slower in taking in information, which I suspect could be related more to an aging-related decrease in hearing.
She seems to be more expressive when she wants -something - when she wants me to follow her, feed her, play with her, etc.

She tells them to back off usually immediately if they start acting up, where she didn't use to.  I taught Brit to weave between my legs as I'm taking big steps, which is a new trick for her. No. Given her age, Nina does very well. Her vision is sharp and although she toddles a bit, her movement is good. She is very alert and exhibits no cognitive disorders. She is sassy as ever!

She is more stubborn and does not listen immediately - it's like she decides whether or not she wants to cooperate if she feels like it. Freckles has been receiving a dental treat every evening at the same time and she now knows when that time is and behaves in a way to let you know if you are late. No. He sleeps a lot, but he's nearly 12 years old. He plays at least twice a day (chases a tennis ball, other toy, or laser pointer) and he initiates the playtime, whining and staring at us until we play with him. After these bursts of energy, he generally lays down and takes a nap.

Ok to be petted but doesn't go up to people for attention or affection.  He does to me only.  I don't know what his previous home was like so who knows.  If I want to brush him, cut his nails, clean his ears, etc. ,he seems afraid or mom,  I just don't like that.  I give treats and lots of affection when doing those things. She approaches me in order to get petted/rubbed and wants to keep it going. New behavior, she has always been reluctant to let us pet her.

He seems to whine a lot and it feels like he wants something at that time.  It may not be evening biscuit or food time when he does this.  Petting does not quiet him. Yorkies have a habit of just stand still & staring. She is slowing down & napping more but that seems to be the only real change thus far.

Bodhi has always been easily startled.  Since doing formal obedience training over the past couple of months, he seems to be gaining confidence and isn't quite so over-reactive.

She whines every day now, but I think that has to do with a significant decrease in the days and numbers of dogs in our house, due to Covid19 (I dogsit in my home and people aren't traveling as usual for vacations and weekends). She doesn't like to fetch or chase balls, so a walk doesn't provide the higher aerobic activity and mental stimulation of wrestling or racing with other dogs. Hopefully after Covid...
She seems to be getting more agile and smart.  She just turned 2

When he's eaten all of his food, he continues to nose around the food mat, maybe looking for a hidden morsel.  He spends several minutes doing this after each meal.
Barks at horses in the neighboring field, never did that before.
Took back a three year old Shih Tzu who lost his mom to Covid in March.  Destry is now actively playing, running and jumping more with this slightly (3 months) older dog.
Based on the questions listed my dog does not exhibit any of those behaviors.

He has learned how to get under a blanket by his dog bed in the living room which he was not doing before although the blanket has been there for more than a year. Tentative to jumping out of the car.

This has made for a much calmer dog, particularly in terms of his leash reactivity towards other people and dogs. So many people are out walking (in this quite rural setting) that we have been able to work on behavior modification much more reliably.
Dog seems the same.  Still very food motivated. She was just diagnosed with a bladder infection which we are treating with antibiotics.

"Due to the pandemic, we are home all the time.  She has adjusted her ""schedule"" to match ours.  For example, she will sleep until 11 am if we do, without asking to go out or for breakfast.  She seems more unhappy if we leave the house without her, which has always bothered her.  She clearly likes having our son home from college."

She now has a marked tendency to come and stand in front of me, and won't move.  I have to go around her.  I don't think she wants anything other than to me with me, but she's lost the ability to recognize that she needs to move over when I start moving forward.  She also seems to want to be underfoot a lot more, I've accidentally stepped on her quite a few times because I didn't see her come up behind or beside me.  She didn't have this behavior until about a year ago, before then she would stay well out of the way if I was cooking in the kitchen or putting away clothes.
She is learning quickly and is retaining more information.

No changes.  We are home a lot more with COVID and she is with us all the time now as opposed to before COVID when we were gone more at work, so not sure any changes in the past 6 months are relevant.
more needing me next to her more

NO NOTICEABLE CHANGE IN ANY BEHAVIORS

He has anxiety and is afraid of people except for myself: He plays well with other dogs but doesn't trust people. He's very affectionate with me I can pet him cuddle but he won't allow it from anyone else. He's skittish and afraid of loud noises.

He runs slower.  He used to run (top speed) about 28 mph and pace at 7-10.  He now runs about 20 mph and paces about at 5-6 mph. Very hyper, obsessed with fetch toys, I mean thats all he wants!!

we recently moved from VA to TX, Castor became reserved when we spent two nights in hotels but once she got to a familiar place, she relaxed. A few months ago, his back leg was bothering him. Now he shows no sign of pain and is very active. He spends a good part of the day with his brother, a golden, outside, keeping the ducks and chickens safe from coyotes. He likes to lounge in the sun wearing his plaid winter coat and is keenly alert to any noise. He takes his job of watching the birds very seriously. He helps me herd them back into the hen house in the afternoon. The golden killed a chicken once, and MacDougle was outraged. While the golden might chase a chicken in fun now and again, he never killed one again.  MacDougle is the Alpa dog of the rural neighborhood. He is allowed on any other dog's property; however, no other dogs are allowed on our property. He will allow females to come to play with him and his brother. But when he says he's done playing, don't bother him.

Hitch went through what I call a grief period in June and July when I lost two senior dogs that he was close to. He was less food motivated and less interested in training and playing. He had to adjust to being the only dog in the house. He obviously had a new routine. I made an effort to make sure he had play dates with other dogs every week. Once he worked through his new situation he was fine and got back to loving food, training and killing toys. But it was interesting to experience the whole process.

I've finally learned what she needs from me so she can enjoy meeting most new dogs rather than fear aggress as she previously did since age two years. It took most of her life but with her patience and our mutual love she finally trained me. We are both grateful.

Phoenix briskly re-enters the house through the dog door from being outside and will go immediately down the hallway looking for me, even if I am on the couch or at the dining room table, both of which are easily visible between the dog door and the hallway. He seems to have an auto-programmed behavior that tells him to do this almost every single time. He either doesn't smell me or he is ignoring what his nose is telling him.   He also seems more and more restless as time passes. He follows me around more often, moves from room to room with me instead of just letting me move around the house by myself.

Franklin is now 16 months old.  His thinking and information processing during the last 6 months seems to be progressing as expected for a dog this age.
No changes. Ziggy is very alert and very healthy (@ 14 years of age). The only changes I see are related to mild arthritis. He seems to be experiencing more stiffness and pain.
No. She's stayed about the same.
Sam is just over a year old & growing up to be a very well adjusted dog.  He is very smart and has not shown any problematic cognitive behavior

Mora came to me from a chaotic home 2 years ago at age 8 years. She was previously trained as a herder but not with skills needed for life as a pet in a more urban setting. One year ago we moved to a retirement community with much denser development (apartments instead of a free-standing house). Her adjustment has been somewhat difficult, with territorial aggression toward some of the dogs (mostly small breeds), exacerbated by the restrictions on movement due to COVID-19. In the last 2-3 months, she has made good progress on learning to walk on leash, sit quietly on command while observing other dogs instead of barking and lunging, to play with a few select others during off-leash time, come on command. We still take off-leash walks twice a day in wooded areas, and her activity needs remain high, but she is learning new behavior and social skills that are making life in our new setting satisfactory. She still is very sociable with people and brings joy to many other seniors who enjoy being able to pat her.
She is vocalizing a bit more.
No changes - he is very aware of his surroundings and can figure out how to go around, under or above objects to get where he wants to go.  Mentally he seems very sharp.

"Much less interest in food/treats, eats much more slowly, and is pickier (was not picky before). She responds enthusiastically at meal time, but then needs to be enticed to actually eat. It's been an unusual few months, due to Brady being diagnosed with cancer (nasal tumor), and then putting him through 3 days of SRT radiation. We're working on it, and she's shown some small progress.  Not a lot, but some.

We had an incident in June where my dog was lost for a little over 24 hours in a very rural area. When she was found she was covered in cactus and dehydrated. Her energy level was zapped for almost 3 months as she recovered physically and mentally (probably compounded by warmer weather and her general aging which are slowing her down). Generally she's much more slow and unwilling to go for long walks in her old age but especially so since the June disappearance
"She has started some new ""games"" she wants me to play, and she has become more reliable walking off-leash."

I have definitely seen changes in my dog's thinking and information processing, but I think it was most likely related to her becoming a young adult from a puppy (Laika is now about 1 year 3 months). 6 months ago, Laika was about 9 months old, and she was still developing her personality. She has definitely matured over the past half year, and has gained more control, focus, and confidence. It has been beautiful to see her grow into her personality. She is much more responsive and focused, and isn't as scared of the things she used to be scared of before. She is more talkative than she used to be, and in some ways seems happier and calmer. She had a bit of a stubborn streak when she was about 1 year old, but with patience and training she has grown out of that for the most part too. In terms of her intelligence, I would say that she hadn't changed that much. She is still very quick to solve new puzzles and learns new commands at about the same pace.

Tank is just over 2-1/2 & is still improving on verbal & hand signal obedience commands and less E-collar correction.  He is just a normal, active, growing puppy that is a true pleasure to be with. For at least the past year, he no longer exhibits any destructive (bored) behavior. He can be left in our backyard alone for 2-3 hours and is generally in his doghouse, within the 6 ft. high kennel, with the kennel door left open.  We trained him to defecate in one area of the back yard and he very rarely fails to use that spot.
He grumbles less, but he gets more antsy when he hears outside noises or inside noises he doesn't recognize.

"I just want to clarify a couple of things about Magic. 1. When I say she sometimes runs into walls or doors, she's a klutz and is either very into running and rough-housing with our other dog when this happens or on a walk, staring at something (usually a person that has appeared) behind us instead of watching where she is going. 2. When you ask about her urinating or defecating in places she previously kept clean, she is dog who has USMI that is well managed on Proin, but sometimes, if something is very exciting/we're out of our normal routine, she may leak a little bit of urine. She also has been known to defecate inappropriately in the home or my office without rhyme or reason when she is left free-roaming. In my office, she has been much better about this over the past couple of months, but we did have a few incidents over the summer. At home, she is generally crated when we are not home to avoid this, as she does not defecate in her crate. Her preferred inappropriate place is the dining room rug, although last week, we found a single piece of stool on the living room rug, which may or may have appeared during a brief time of freedom or maybe while we were otherwise occupied elsewhere in the home. She has never had a ""schedule"" for her bowel movements and may go anywhere from not at all (which happens rarely) to 5 times in a single day. I do not have a good explanation for when or why she will have a bowel movement in the house/office. I will say that the dining room is one of our two least-used rooms in the home. Generally, Magic is a good problem solver and much more of an independent thinker than our other dog. She is good at retrieving her own toys if they roll under a couch or table or will persist at trying to get a piece of food out of a corner or under a piece of furniture if one goes astray (our other dog may make a weak attempt and then looks to us or will just stare at the location of whatever he wants). If we're playing a new game with her, she is fairly quick to pick up most of them and remembers the game quickly if we do not play for a while. She is more receptive to petting or physically contacting us while she sits with us on the couch now than she was 6 months ago. Sometimes, she's more cat-like than dog-like with the attention and affection she wants. She always wants to have a visual on us, but not necessarily interact directly. (She will often lay on the landing if one of us is upstairs and the other downstairs. If we're on one couch, she generally prefers to be on the other. She often gets up and moves to the other end of the couch if one of us sits next to her or gets up entirely.) When she wants attention, however, she will shove her head under your hand repeatedly. She full-body wags when we get home. She often used to growl at us if we went to physically touch her, and she wasn't in the mood for it. I don't believe either of us has elicited this response from her in several months, and she often voluntarily jumps between us and puts her head in one of our laps while we're watching t.v. I think that about sums up Magic's behavioral ticks."
She was diagnosed with SARDS in May 2020 so the sudden blindness has drastically affected her behavior, especially for some of the things that you asked about.

He is in herding training and after lessons twice a week, which are quite mentally demanding, he needs to sleep or rest/think for several hours, seemingly to process his lesson.  At his next lesson, his apparent comprehension has advanced and he seems able to perform the behaviors he learned in the previous lesson and incorporate new tasks and challenges. I am also working to build his vocabulary by training him to bring me objects by name (class of object and descriptor ie: Red Ball, Bouncy Ball, Yellow Ball, Red Wubba, Brown Wubba etc) and he if he chooses the wrong object he clearly thinks and understands feedback that he has made the wrong choice and makes corrections. His processing time for these requests has shortened. Also, in addition to herding, he now runs and hikes, and before we were waiting for his growth plates to close so he was not allowed to be so active.

"Spark plug started the ""pacing & panting"" behavior about 6 months ago.  It was so bad at night sometimes one of us had to get up with him & try to calm him down.  After it became ""a thing"" more than twice a week I decided to try something...CBD oil.  (I use CBD cream on my knees & it's a miracle cure!).  Anyway, I knew there was stuff for dogs & she gave me a bottle of Canine Hemp Oil...explained how much to use for his weight (5-6 drops) on his food at 4:30 pm & again at 10:30 pm (a few morsels in his dish for ""bedtime snack"").  It Worked!!  I've been using it now for about 4 months and there have only been 2 nights of noticeable ""pacing"" & restlessness."

I have not noticed any changes in any of his behaviors. COVID-19 really has not changed our lifestyles we do not visit with friends as often as we used to but we are together 24 7. I think he likes it.

We had another beagle(16 yr old male) that we lost in September, Poppy has been much more aware of sounds and new things brought into the house. She is not aggressive at all but she barks more than she used to.
I started giving him fish oil and he seems to have improved mentally as well as physically.
She has actually gotten sweeter and wants to cuddle more!
She learned a new trick this past month.  She can now back up on command!  I'm working on keeping her mind sharp in hopes their minds work like humans when they are elderly.

Our dog seems to have gotten smarter - i guess that comes with age, just like humans!   She also loves to go for rides in the car and watches us leave with expressive eyes just waiting for us to call her.
More vocal and purposeful in communicating what he wants by talking and prompting me to move in a direction or take a specific action.

Sadie is a Great Pyrenees.  The cooler weather has made her slightly more active and much more intent on being outside where she guards the yard from all comers -- mostly birds, squirrels, and chipmunks.  She is much more alert when she is outside.  She has even shown some interest in playing -- something new and different though still rare. In the last 6 months (before Prozac, even) she has shown an aptitude for language -- both understanding us & in making her interests known.

Sometimes after I say a familiar word that she would react to quickly seems to take a little longer to process, it seems like a slight cognitive decline or her hearing maybe. For example she has been using a ramp to get down to the yard from the patio for a year now, recently she has been walking over to the stairs and trying to go up those and then I have to say ramp and she goes to the ramp. I haven't had to say ramp in a long time, only the first few weeks when we introduced it, but then she would just always go to the ramp, it's almost like she has forgotten about it, but it's not all the time.
Riley gets jealous of anyone interacting with me or if I pet one of our other dogs.  He tries to insert himself between me and either the person or the dog.
Rocky has matured to looking into my eyes and using his eyes to direct my attention to where he wants something or wishes to me to go.
Zavya sleeps more soundly now and sometimes does not realize that a vehicle has driven down our driveway.  But then again, sometimes we don't know a vehicle has driven down the driveway either.
Getting more stubborn about what she wants. Getting more tired more easily

Yes , to get her to come inside . We have to bribe her with a half a peanut. She will not come until we say the words ������������. Come get a peanut . If we don't say it . She will hold her ground . I mean like we go inside . I have left her out 5 minutes.

Our dog has more self confidence and is calmer than he used to be.   He paces back and forth (especially in the car) as a sign of anxiety. We are fostering another dog, so Sadie did spend less time sleeping at first, but now she is back to normal.
He is quieter when he goes into his crate.  Sometimes, he'll lay in the crate after I've opened it.  He only goes in the crate when I leave the house.

She used to go for long walks around the neighborhood on a leash.
