Not much as far as changes, but we are not as active in dog training situations as we were.  Especially away from home.
Casper Durgin Hsieh is getting older and it seems to be happening quickly.  It takes more time to react to nearly everything and processing of information seems to take more time.
Stays closer to me than during the previous six months
Because she is allowed off leash, she now runs for the joy of running.  Life is a bowl of cherries for this girl. :)

She is very happy and active and loving and still quite young so no issues yet. I've noticed that her hearing is diminishing, making her more cautious about her surroundings when she goes out.

Actually he appears to be getting smarter as he's aging.  Such knowing more when it's meal time or play time.  He appears to know exactly when we are going to sit on the couch and steal our spots RIGHT before we go to sit there.  LOL.   Also, he has started to want to hang out outside after breakfast.  Yesterday I had a confererence call early and forgot to give him breakfast and asked if he wanted to go out.  He refused to go out until after he was fed.  To me it appeared he was thinking that if he went out, he would forfeit breakfast.  I don't see a mental decline AT ALL.

Since we just adopted our dog at 13 weeks, she is going through normal developmental changes that a puppy goes through - she had improved so much in jumping and mouthing/play biting until a few days ago, and it seems she has regressed and become more disobedient.

She just keeps learning more.  She shows no cognitive decline.  In fact, we enjoy noticing what a keen observer of our behavior she is and how well she can predict our behavior.  She loves patterns and routines in life.

"She's learning new words or sounds, like ""daddy""--maybe because he's home all the time now with the pandemic so it's used more. She's also better at following a finger point, knowing to go in that direction."

Our dog hates the warm weather. (An English Golden Retriever). Once the cooler weather came in he is like a different animal. Much more energy and enthusiasm, more playful.

she gets a portion of her food moistened with goat milk. she's eaten from a slow bowl before but I recently brought it back to switch things up. she'll get that and then the moistened food once the slow bowl is finished. I made the mistake of once putting the moistened food down before the slow bowl is done and now sometimes she'll just wait for that not finishing the slow bowl. occasionally also if I put the moistened food down she won't finish what's left in the slow bowl (maybe 1/3 of what was put in there originally?). as a puppy she got the slow bowl and other feeding toys because she ate SO FAST, and has always eaten all of her food prior to very recently. we're also in a pandemic and quarantining though, so a lot of things are different  - hard to tell if it's age-related or just 2020.
Dog has associated baby's naptime as a No Play time, will often sleep in his bed and sigh.
No!  She is happy and healthy.
She is more active now that she is no longer pregnant and nursing puppies.
At first when I got my dog he wouldn't respond to his name, but now he does all the time.

He seems to have gotten better at recognizing time of regular events such as late afternoon walk. DSTime confuses him a bit. And he's become more demanding of me..barking..when it's time to eat or walk..or throw ball. He's gotten bossier!!

Kit has always slept on the bed with us and frequently goes to bed before we do. Sometimes she will root around in the sheets and blanket before she settles down. I have noticed that he goes to sleep a little earlier than before (maybe a half hour or so--even prior to Daylight Savings time change).  He sleeps on the couch, across from where I read at night. She's more mature.  Follows commands better.  Observes boundaries (doesn't run out an open gate or door) much better.

"Biscuit is now an 8-month old puppy and is learning all the time. He is familiar with our daily routines now and recognizes the sound of our car. shes 18 month old now, she's getting better behaved but still has alot of energy

I am a single parent living out in the country. Jacques has started getting bored and has started licking the carpet.  Just this last week, he is struggling with coughing up whatever is stuck in his throat from the carpet.... She pretty much acts the same.

My dog is only 5 months old.

None so far.  FYI-my dog avoids being petted when she wants to play ball. That seems to be her favorite kind of attention

Now I am wary about letting a large dog come up to her. She is fine with smaller dogs or dogs her size and particularly dogs of the same age or older.
Have just noticed him more in his own world. Have to say his name loudly to snap him out.
My dog is more active because she had surgery to repair a completely torn CCL on both hind knees and now is able to do SO MUCH MORE physical activities! Cognitively, she is fine, no changes.

Before exercise and when confronted with stimulus ie, other dogs, people, bikes, cars unusual sights.

We moved into our new home about seven months ago, so things were still new for her. However there weren't any major changes for her in her mood or how she acted.
He is bored. Trevor is a Therapy Dog that until Covid made 2-3 visits per week. He's now unemployed. I started him in Agility and that has perked him up a lot!
Elle seems a tiny bit more patient

"Dax is only getting smarter as he gets older. It seems that with getting smarter, he may be developing slightly more anxieties. It feels that he has the capacity to actually worry about things in a way that my other dog might not. Rather than ""slowing down"" (even though he's not quite 4) he actually requires more mental exercise along with physical exercise. It's not enough for him to be just tired out from fetch as when we was younger  - he has to have some component of thinking, like carrying his ball while on a hike, or going to daycare where he has to herd and interact with other dogs, or take a trip to a new pet store or to the office that will give him something to think about, in order to be content napping when we get back home."

From Good Dog Training classes (7-weeks, Sept-Oct 2020) Henry has learned/reinforced behaviors such as staying on his bed during family meals, leaving things alone (distraction training success), coming more promptly when called, staying on command for longer and longer periods, and dropping things he has picked up that he shouldn't have (e.g., shoes).  He is doing great, not perfect, but we can tell he is learning!

no, she's seemed cognitively alert and focused.

she seems to listen better and obey a little better since she is now having everyone around all day due to covid.

"She seems to actually be ""catching on"" more to relevant words (like ""car"", ""treat,"" ""cookie,"" etc) our conversations than in the past, and she has become more ""nagging"" about wanting me to start preparing dinner, going to bed, and going for ""sunset walks"" (i.e., non business walks!) at appropriate times of the day than she used to do."

Ducati has moved from the wild puppy to a more settled adult dog.  He is better able to control his responses when told to stop barking or reacting to stimuli.  He has matured on track and exhibits good behavior for a dog approaching his 4th birthday in a few months.

He walks a little more slowly and sleeps more. I thought this was because he has an older sister(same parents first and last litter) who has raised him and he copies in everything. She turned 15 in August.
Scooby's vision issues have impacted his behavior but he is still the same little dog behind it all.
Yes I sent her for obedience training and she is doing very well, concentrating on my command and obeying most of them. Still have house training issues when it rains but much better.

Milo is really only as active as I am -- he tends to move around with me, but if I'm still, or working at a desk, he's content to nap. I do think he's a little slower on walks than he used to be, particularly in the warmer months, but is still up for LONG games of frisbee or ball.

In the last six months, we have been on a more regular walking pattern (an hour or so per day). I have notices he has been more alert and in better physical shape during that time. Since a spleen removal surgery in February (which included the removal of a benign necrotic cyst), he has been on a regular regimen of gabapentin. At that time he was on 300mg per day and exhibited occasional ataxia. We have recently lowered the dosage to 200mg per day and haven't noticed the ataxia any longer.

She has learned more language and has become more affectionate.  This has increased continually since we adopted her 2 yrs ago.  She is also way less anxious eg doesn't always get scared with thunder or fire crackers.

"Lucy finally gets how to play fetch. Now when I throw the ball, or a toy, she brings it back to me. I ""trade"" for a treat when she returns the ball. She can keep running back and forth for a long time. Eventually, she'll lay down in the grass so I know she needs a break. But a couple of minutes later, she's ready to play or run with other dogs like a maniac. "

"Choey is sleeping in more often but I recently added CBD oil to her daily dosing of medications. She is in less joint pain (she is almost 16 years old) and still insists on 5-6 walks a day. She refused to go and turned in the direction we normally go. She only does her ""numbers"" outside and the only time in her life she has gone in the house is when she was sick and had diarrhea. Best dog ever! Ha"
"Izzie is ""making up"" to my husband more than she used to. (Asking for Petting, food, walks.) Sometimes she just goes and visits him in his office in stead of being with me."
He seems to sleep more, not sure if it's due to winter with the cold air

She has seasonal variations.  She's most active in spring and fall, less so in summer and winter.  During the winter she'll typically eat less and lose some weight, but as she gets more active in spring she eats more and puts the muscle back on.  She'll be 10 in January and I haven't noticed any long term differences between this year and previous years.  She's still an energetic and active little doggy.

Gracie has grown out of her puppy craziness, so I can see her reasoning things out more. She has more firmly established habits, and she knows when certain events are supposed to happen. For example, she knows when the coffee pot starts that I'll be leaving for work, so she gets her brother George and they stand by their crates waiting for me. We live near farms, and fall is the season when rodents start heading towards houses; she's become very interested in finding mice and has already figured out where they travel.

"Waldo has always been very impulse-driven. Since he was a puppy, we have worked on impulse=control exercises. On the other hand, he has always been rather slow responding to cues or ""commands"". His responses are often delayed about 5 seconds. He seems to be responding a bit more quickly to our cues/requests; but on the other hand, he's a bit slower reacting to things that usually trigger his chase impulses, in a way that we've been encouraging. (We taught him to point at, or herd rabbits, rather than chase them, when he's on leash.) He seems to consider our requests/instructions more carefully than he did when he was younger."
Slightly more alert & active due to change in dog food per vet

No. He is still pretty sharp at 12 years old
She was confused when we all started staying home but now she likes it.

Her sense of time is different. She understands morning, afternoon, and night. Like she knows my schedule and is really adapted to that and gets very upset when we don't go by that schedule. She's also more protective of when people pass the door.

She is young, in my opinion she appears to be getting smarter. I can hide one of her toys and ask where the toy is. 99 percent of the time she will find that toy. She will want to take the toy outside and either want to play with it more or want to bury it (which we will not allow her to do). She loves praise and will smile at us knowing that overall she is a very good girl.

He is still the same stubborn terrier. I think he has ADHD as his attention span is quite short. His behavior is pretty much the same as 6 months ago.  I have noticed in the last 2 years he is more inclined to stay close to me in the yard.

When meeting familiar people or animals she takes less time playing with them. If it is an unfamiliar person or animal, her interest remains longer.
she seems to randomly bark more.  She will come up to me and start barking for what seems like no reason.

He makes a decision to do something to pester me (really trying to get me to play with him) and does it. Like swiping the pot holders or pulling my shirt off the hanger. He is not destructive. Just a stinker. A little shake of the head and he drops it.

Her declining eyesight is a factor. She has trouble navigating dark rooms- for example, the only rooms she gets 'lost' in are those in pitch dark. She also has barked at things outside- when we look, we cannot see anything and wonder what stimulated her.

His mind is sharp along with his senses.  His downside is his mobility is becoming impaired. What has been interesting in watching him over the years, he is a mix of Red Bone Coon hound and a Ridgeback and seems to have the strong senses of both the eye and scent of both breeds.
His behavior is still the same happy go lucky, affectionate guy we love.

Since 3/20, we are taking longer walks with Katie in the mornings, usually about two miles compared to maybe one mile a day, prior to this even though she turned 10 in May. She looks forward to the long walks. We are doing the longer walks because my gym closed.
Shyla is the same as she was 6 months ago in all respects.

We play a game where we ask her to find her toy before we feed her. She now prepares for this event about 75 percent of the time, so that she has the bone with her as dinner time nears. Previously, she would not have prepared at all.

Asta is afraid of the normal sounds dogs don't like-lawn mower-things like that. But for some reason she developed a fear of the sound of flies over the summer. A fly can cause Asta to get anxious and avoid a room; flies never bothered her before.

We think she's getting a little deaf, because she is slow to respond if she's sleeping or sometimes even if she awake and you call her from another room. (She's always had very sharp hearing.) She's also developed a cataract in one eye, so that occasionally causes her a little trouble. She has adapted pretty well, though.
Sully seems to be having an easier time concentrating on training these days -
He is a puppy. His endurance for being active has increased in a normal way.

"Only during Duke's ""spells"" does he seem to be disoriented and his processing doesn't work as it should.  He has ""spells"" around 2-3 times a week.  The vet said it could be something with his brain but the scan would be around $2,000.00 and we can't afford it."
He is finally able to focus longer and we have been able to do basic sit, stay, etc. training. Before this, he seemed too immature and distracted to learn tasks.
He's been sad since the loss of our German shepher. They were together 10 years. He's lost alot of energy and doesn't want to play frisbee anymore.
Wife us home and interacting with Abbey more due to loss of job(s) due to Covid.
Less energetic, likely due to anti-epileptic medications
Very quick to recognize commercials on TV that have a dog in them.  Will come from another room when the background music begins in order to bark or look at the commercial.
She will just stare into space when she is in the yard.
He seems more thoughtful and willing to focus for longer periods of time.  He can train in more distracting environments with success.
"Intensity of begging has increased somewhat. Vocalization and ""prancing"" in association with begging for treat or dinner or to go outside - has increased.  "
She's still pretty young and learning things.

If we are at the park and walking around if she gets distracted she seems to forget the direction we were walking and doesn't know where to find me. She cannot hear well anymore and I'm not sure about her vision.

I can tell that the pandemic and quarantine has increased her energy, I believe because she isn't getting to class, is getting less away-from-home training, and generally getting less varied experiences.

I'm working from home now, so my dog spends less time at daycare and more time with me. He's more bored, but it's only expressed as sighs or flipping my elbow with his nose while I'm at my desk. Spending more time together has actually improved our bond and his off leash behavior is amazing since I take him for off leash trail walks and runs daily instead of once a week. He has even learned how to socially distance on the trail. He usually runs/walks 20-30 feet in front of me; when he sees or hears a person/dog he stops, looks at me, and falls into a heel without being told. It's really amazing. We've started taking him back to daycare 1-2 times per week to maintain his dog socialization. No changes with that behavior; still loves all dogs and humans.
Annie seems to be set off by unusual noises more often. It might be do to the fact that two people are always in the house where in the past, before COVID, I was gone most of the day.
He seems to demand a bit more attention and tends to follow me around more than in the past.

"If anything Odin seems to be getting smarter. He understands more words. We have to explain what's going on or he gets impatient. For instance are we going for a walk to the dog park? or are we taking a drive up to the mountains? We now need to explain our intentions or he becomes vocal and impatient much like a toddler. For this reason we believe he ""plans"" his day. "

I have noticed that she hears me but is unable to identify the direction of the sound.  If she has fallen asleep and wakes up, she sometimes expresses urgency until she locates me. Her eyesight is reduced, but not totally impaired.  I turn on lights for her to follow me, not keeping it dark anymore.
No, other than being a bit more lazy and not wanting to take long walks (she's very stubborn).
She's more hesitant to go on rides (in the car).  She often chooses to stay behind.  I haven't figured out why.  Otherwise, I would say things have been about the same.

Ladybird seems more aware of what is happening around her.  She barks at the door if someone rings the doorbell.  This is new as of about 4 months ago.  She is also better at seeing cats, fox, deer, and other dogs or people when we walk.  She does not bark much when we walk, but she is more observant.
I have not noticed any changes.

"He does not do any of the behaviors listed here but he is I would say an anxious dog, always wanting to be with you, following you, he always has a toy in his mouth it's like a pacifier. And he is easily upset by us if we are upset, he will put his ears back and try to hide his head. All I have to do to scold him is ask in a normal voice ""who did this"" and he is horrified. "

She seems to have become more insistent on getting treats that we give her after her and/or our dinner, closely following me around as I clear the table or immediately after she finishes her dinner.  After getting a treat, she'll immediately go back to her normal mode of just laying down somewhere, totally uninterested in us.
no, I can't think of any observed changes in behavior
"much more clingy to me than before; has become a ""mama's boy"" - where before was not as much so"

I have had the dog for about 1.5 years.   During that time, his personality hasn't changed, as far as I can tell.   I think he was pretty inactive when I got him.   We walk about 2 miles every day, and he looks in better shape, but he is slower, I believe because the walks exacerbate his arthritis.
often tends to ignore my commands and do what she wants to do. Insists on us keeping her schedule, not her keeping ours.  Barks incessently until she gets what she wants.

He has been a teenager for the last 6 months in the time of Covid where he has not had as much opportunity to interact with other dogs.  He is a busy boy.  He can figure out most things and never misses food.

I have noticed, and maybe it is b/c of the pandemic, that she is not as social w/ other dogs and humans as she used to be. When on a leash she is very frightened of other dogs and humans. She reacts be cowering or barking like crazy. When at the dog park or the park she is great if she is not on leash.

She is more anxious since we moved from a townhouse to an apartment, especially when I leave. She seems to try to dig and scratch and chew her way through the door or carpet in the rooms where I lock her up when I leave for 1-3 hours at a time.

I can tell his vision has changed by the blue color/cover in his eyes. He occasionally walks into things now that he would usually see but now since he was diagnosed I can see the change in his mannerisms when out and understand why he's more aware of his surroundings and more reliant on me to lead him. It sucks to see my baby boy is having any bit of a rough go with his sight and that it may get worse. He's been my world I honestly can't imagine life without him in it. He responds to click training well and was trained as a pup so he relys on that alot more now as to where I'm directing him.

"We got a puppy (9 weeks old) 9.19.2020.  Ranger has become more active and more playful. I think the puppy is teaching him to ""play"" and he has someone to play with. Ranger now likes foods he didn't eat before (puppy influence), he plays more with us and I would like to believe he is much more friendly and not so anxious to other humans he meets. "
She has never urinated or defecated in the house so the option more, less or the same didn't really fit.  She is going blind says her ophthalmologist so we see her again next week.
He's going blind snd may have hearing issues.

"She is smart (per her trainers)but she can take a longer time to follow a command these days if she does not want to do it. If you say ""sit"" outside, you may have to wait 20-30 seconds for her to comply.  She appears not to want to do it, but will do it if you do not back down. "
Noah runs everyday or walks the family yard dailywith his 14 year old buddy Oscar
Wellesley is less active because she ruptured her CCL in September and hah a TPLO to address it in November
More active with kittens in house

"He's been pretty stable to even remembering more. One odd behavior that he's had for a while though is not that he gets stuck behind objects like he can't see them, but he will feel that he gets ""stuck"" because something is just out of reach or is on the hard wood floor. We've had to add rugs in a few locations because he acts like ""the floor is lava"" and he won't go on to parts of the hard wood floor more than necessary. What's even stranger is that it's only at our house. "
She has become mostly deaf, so hand signals are our way to communicate. I often have to touch her to get her attention.
Cinnamon is responding much quicker to verbal commands than she did 6-months ago.

I have a new treat container with milk bones in it (not her favorite) on the coffee table that is her height, she has learned to nudge it, stare at me and grumble like bark, therefore asking for a treat for her and the other dogs.
He seems better at communicating what he wants. Maybe it's just that I'm becoming better trained.
Wyatt has started separating himself from us to go rest. This is more often than before. Since putting him on dalsiquin and a heart med, it has been less.
No, she was and still is sharp as a tack!
He has become more playful which is likely caused by the fact my boyfriend got a puppy that Frisco enjoys playing with.
No changes in last 6 months going from 22 months to 28 months of age
The hair between his paw pads has grown and he is very careful on the hardwood areas in our house.  You can tell he worries in those areas, as well as slides.

"She was ""wobbling"" quite a bit.  Just stand there and start to wobble, but once started walking, was okay.  Recently she had a tumor removed and bad teeth extracted and she has improved significantly!"

We have a senior malamute that has mobility issues. In the last few months, Kurgan has grown agitated and barks excessively when Caesar whines/needs assistance getting up.  When we help Caesar up, sometimes he growls (just being old man grumpy) and Kurgan will bark loudly and won't stop until Casaer is standing on his own and walking.

Compared to six months ago, Lobo is less likely to analyze threats and more likely to display aggressive behaviors towards humans. Our assumption is that maybe it has something to do with bringing a puppy into the home and Lobo feeling more pressure to be protective and territorial.
No. She's as bright and cognitive as ever. I'm a certified behavior consultant and started nightly trainings with her years ago....
Sleeps later in the day but that could be due to the colder and darker mornings and that I am teaching remotely and she finds that uninteresting

Canny is sleeping far more soundly.  He's not losing his hearing, but if he's in one of his sound slumbers, he doesn't hear the doorbell ring - he ALWAYS used to bark to greet the guest. Now he does if he's awake.
Has shown more fear to unfamiliar objects and/or people.
We got a new puppy 8 months ago and Clare is not all receptive to playing or interacting with the now 10 month old puppy.

None. He's a hound. So he has 2 speeds, nothing or 120MPH. He doesn't get why other dogs chase balls, but loses his mind seeing a squirrel or cat. He isn't overly affectionate, doesn't give licks or snuggle, but does move to his bed in whatever room I am in, so wants proximity but doesn't need to be in my face, unless i have food.  He's very calm with my grandchildren, let's them crawl all over him. Doesn't seek out other dogs at the dog park to play, just to sniff at. Walks away if someone tries to pet him most of the time.
She refuses to learn new behavior/tricks I teach my younger dog.  She just expects the treats without working for them.
He has become more fearful when going for a walk. Perhaps because we avoid people outside due to COVID, he has become more afraid.
We just moved to a new house with a big yard, so Zoe is able to be much more active than she previously was.
She has became more food aggressive.
No. He has some cataracts and a bit of hearing loss that i have noticed a little bit more, but not affecting him in any of the ways mentioned in the questions.
Bella is losing some of her sight and most of her hearing so she has to watch me a lot more to understand what I want her to do. She is learning hand signals easily.

If she has not seen a family member or friend of the family in several weeks, she takes a little time to seem to recognize them and be friendly to them (between 15 -30 minutes). She acts as if they are an intruder and is aggressive when she should recognize that they are a close family relative like a grandparent that has often spent extended weeks here.
Somewhat mellower when seeing other dogs when on walks.

She has dry eye and the progression has had an affect on her sight. This contributes to her banging her head against furniture occasionally and difficulty finding food thrown or dropped as she has aged. Still a wonderful vet. ophthalmologist, Dr. Gross, is responsible for prescribing medications that have preserved her sight very well.
Auggie seems the same as she did 6 months ago.
He seems more hyper but I think it is because we are not going to the park as often due to COVID.

as a working search and rescue dog, my dog is extremely physically and mentally active, and has spent several hours a day exercising/conditioning/training with me for the past several years. However, in the past 6 months, we have found a better SAR mentor for us who has helped build greater confidence in our work. As my dog has more and more fun at SAR training, he is translating that into a much more outgoing personality with strangers and people other than me. In addition to excelling at our SAR work, my dog has become much more comfortable playing with and seeking attention from people other than me in the past 6 months.
No change.  Still extremely alert and interested in everything.
"Goes upstairs in the morning to be near my husband after he eats ""breakfast "". Also he jumps up in my lap to greet me before he goes upstairs "
I think has a harder time smelling his food when we put it in his bowl.
He sometimes seems to have trouble hearing me.
He has lost some hearing so he does not react to loud noises as he used to.

We re-homed our very anxious with behavioral issues 6 year old corgi in late August of 2020 and since that time Yuli has been calmer and easier to work with overall- less barking and anxious behavior about what is about to happen (or not). She is listening better and more thoroughly, less erratic and impulsive actions. Also, she turned 3 years old and something about that tells me she's finally matured into an adult dog and is better able to manage her thinking and decision making.
He seems to like being home more, e.g., after turning toward home on a walk, he's more energetic.
He's still spry and excited for his hikes.
No, she acts pretty much the same.
No changes in her behavior in the last 6 months.
once the sun goes down she scratches and the door to go out and when you get up to let her out, she doesn't want to go out. Sundowning ?
He is still learning new skills.  Recently has learned to bring me the papers from the printer.  They do come with a bit of saliva, but that doesn't seem to bother him!
She was never very food motivated. but now, she will knock her food bowl and bark to be fed any time she sees her food bowl on the floor, even if she was just fed 10 minutes earlier.

"I've now had Olive for about six months (which is why it was so hard answering all the questions that began ""in the last year"")  She absolutely adores me, but is still extremely timid around all other people (low growling, not allowing people to get near her, certainly not allowing others to pet her) and most dogs.  When I try to take her for walks, she hides behind me if she sees other walkers with dogs, and sometimes even just lone walkers.  She is taking a medication (can't remember the name--doggy Prozac; I'm checking into slightly increasing the dose).  I know nothing about her past except this:  she was rescued from a hoarding situation in South Carolina (I have no idea if that means messy house, or a lot of animals, or both).  From there, she went to a shelter for about a week and then into foster care with Pawfect Match Rescue.  She was with that family for right over five months before I adopted her.  I felt like my responses to the big questionnaire made it seem like I really don't know Olive at all, but as I say, I've had her for only six months and we still have a lot of work to do.  "
Somewhat less time spent playing with toys. More time sleeping.

The pandemic means WAY fewer social opportunities, and WAY more walks around his neighborhood. Edward Snorton has expanded his idea of His Territory to encompass the streets surrounding our house, and is increasingly rude to other dogs while he (and they) are on lead.
Likes to spend a lot of time in the garage.

He's only 4.5. The items like staring off into space / at a wall is all normal. He's a pretty calm dog in general. He a not rambunctious in that he doesn't plow through the house just moving things out of his way.
My dog seems to be more anxious about mealtime. He has begun whining while I am preparing his meal. This behavior has developed over the past 6-9 months.
He remains alert, highly interactive with his humans, and intelligent.

He seems more relaxed and comfortable at home, like he doesn't always have to be on his best behavior   I have had him 3.5 years.    He is more vocal in expressing his wishes than he was six months ago.
None that I am aware of
Nothing has changed. Still as sharp as ever just a little more attitude sometimes hence the walking away while being petted.

We live on a street of row houses and some times Sam will go up the steps of the wrong home. Within the last week, we let Sam out of the car and he went up the stairs and inside a neighbor's home. It's not daily that he doesn't recognize where his home is but it's certainly obvious he struggles at times.

She has become more protective of the house. She barks when anyone comes to the door. She stops when I ask her to but she is still pretty intense. Now that she is an adult (3.5 years old), she is more particular about which dogs she is interested in.

My dog has had isolation anxiety from the time I got her 6 mos ago. She paces & urinates or defecates only when left alone. Because of this I do not leave her alone. As you can surmise, this circumstance makes it difficult to answer some of your questions.

He is losing his hearing and this is confusing him more and more.  Because I am fostering a dog from a Guide Dog group, Bailey no longer gets all of my attention and when the other dog is at school Baily does not leave the area I am in, looking for more attention.

Considering that she was diagnosed with B-cell lymphoma about 2months ago, and died on November 13th, she never displayed cognitive issues. Unless you acknowledge the fact that sometimes she just didn't care. If food was involved. she was always ready to go until the last 48-56 hours. That was our definitive signal that she was done and ready to move on.
He's slightly more mellow but friskier since he started getting PT

Recognizing words, names, and minor commands much more. Also recognizes when I turn my back in the kitchen in the mornings when fixing the outdoor cats' food he then has an opportunity to go to the library to eat the indoor cat's food and get back to his waiting place in the den by the time I get back inside.
Due to COVID-19, there were few to no opportunities for training, showing and trialing so he is slightly more suspicious of new people or things.
I have a new puppy now, and Marshall has started to show interest and joins in play.
Fizz is a 19 month old dog, so his behavior changes pretty frequently as he is going through later adolescence!

He was neutered when he was 8 months old, so there were 2 weeks where he was in the cone, but other that that he's just been growing up, getting more active as we start to take him on a few runs and some hikes.

Our first dog, Nike, was diagnosed with and lost his battle with bone cancer.   Ike was just 4 years old and died in August 2019.  Apollo knew Nike as his older brother although they were not biologically related.  We did not realize how much of Apollo's identity and self confidence came from Nike.  Apollo is now fairly timid around other dogs and reluctant to socialize or play with any dog he doesn't know.   The loss of Nike affected him in ways that we still don't fully understand.

His perception of time is off.  His normal dinner time is around 5 pm and since being home more because of COVID,  I started feeding him at 4-4:30 pm.  He now starts pacing, wanting dinner earlier.  It usually starts around 2-2:30 pm.  He follows me and lays near me and stares at me.  Most times I make him wait but some days it is so annoying that I give in earlier.

My dog has developed a fear of noise over the last 6-months.  It started with fireworks on July 4t.  We live on the water and fireworks lasted for 4-weeks this year (every night)!  The sound carried.  She will not go for a walk no.  She is on Prozac working with a Behavioral Vet and Behavioral trainer.  We did get a CBC, Chemistry, and thyroid panel done that were all normal.

"Since we've both been working from home since March, I've noticed that Sydney ""talks"" to us a lot more to  communicate.  She always been very communicative, but she's just more vocal now with getting our attention for various things such as going outside, getting a toy, wanting to play and sometimes we have no idea what she's trying to tell us.  It's been pretty fun having conversations with her."
I have not observed any changes in her behavior except that because of Covid-19 she has become a bit more clingy since I'm here all the time.
Due to SIP she is getting way more exercise and is much hungrier as a result.

Scout is very sensitive to our routine and behavior. He also has his daily schedule, and will approach us as if to remind us it's time for a walk, cuddle time, snack or meal.  When my spouse and I start a conversation, no matter where Scout is, he will come and join us! Sometimes he will sit or stand right between my husband and I so we make sure to notice and include him.
No. At 10 years old (next week) her behavior remains very consistent.

This section/survey was hard to answer since our dog is just a puppy, 7 months old, so we're only seeing the normal expected learning curve (although she's been housebroken since we got her at 11 weeks)!  :)
We've just added 2 boy golden puppies (Hall & Oates) and she's gotten sharper in regards to keeping up with them while also being a bit motherly and looking after them.
It's not a change, but my dog is nearly blind.
No Changes.  Kylie seems to be in the prime of life.  I can't see any changes.  She is a very good, healthy dog.
With everyone home all the time during COVID lockdown, her life has changed quite a bit.
"Jax seems to be a bit more ""clingy""  and keeps a close eye on my locaton in the yard and home. "
No real changes. He seems to have gotten smarter. The only other thing I noticed, he has gotten more demanding verbally and physically he keeps pawing at me when he wants sonething.
Danigirl was walking / running 5 miles up until about this past March 2020. Now, she walks one mile in the morning and a short walk at night . We shortened her walking activity due to her arthritis.
I feel like my dog is comprehending more than she has previously.  Since being home more, I think more ideas are being reinforced on a regular basis and she seem to pick up more commands.
He seems to struggle with jumping up/down on the couch most times when he has had no problem before
More tuned in to us since we stay home more due to covid distancing. Naps less often, watches us and listens closely so is more reactive to our conversations and to our actions in the home.
I have a new puppy in the house which has given Sierra a playmate. They get along well, and the puppy actually seems to be helping reduce some of Sierra's anxiety.
He is less active and seems depressed.
He gets scared by things in the dark and is especially upset by people in reflective clothing in the dark.
None really, but she's still young.
No, thinking and info processing is the same.
She is getting much faster at picking up changes in routine than she used to, especially with our toddler.
He seems to be improving in his ability to learn from watching other dogs or humans.

"Kara is currently 10.5 months old and started exhibiting some ""teenager"" type behavior such as hearing a command/request and then visibly decides to not respond as she did when she was young.  Fairly typical behavior in my experience at this age though.  "

We recently lost her housemate and since then she has seemed more demanding, barking, when she almost never barked before. She also seeks physical attention from her humans. She also has become increasingly wary of and reticent to walk on the tile floor. This seems to stem from her slipping on the floor. She has also, over a matter of years, become more uncomfortable with strangers in her home, although outside the home she is fine meeting them.
She's recently decided that the new resident owl in our back 40 is a demon monster and needs to be barked at.
He is bored and misses dog park time. But his grasp of English vocabulary is growing.
We lost her sibling We lost her sibling less than six months ago. Her eating habits have definitely changed and as she used to guard her food.

Our dog Hank has started what we call bait and switch with a younger companion dog in our family.  If Hank wants the toy the other dog has, he will pick up another toy to lure the younger dog away, then picks up the preferred toy.

Klovis like others with autism does not make eye contact very often, sometimes avoids being touched, does not follow a point to food or objects on the floor.  His comprehension of cause and effect has gotten better in the last six months. His behaviors toward other dogs is, like others with autism, that he ignores them.  Now he will occasionally pay attention to a dog but usually ignores them. He is very sensory seeking (wants to be held or petting or stroked much of the day.

I have noticed that since we have moved permanently to our new home now in a community with no fence from a rural home that had a fence and dog door, environmental changes are so different that he has to adjust to this,  this past year and a half.  From freedom to now being leashed up all the time  till we get our fence built.  Hopefully we can get that fence built this spring then he will be happy to run around the yard freely once again.  :)
Not that I can tell. But his hearing is much less acute.

She comes to work with me every day (I'm a nanny). The father of the family is working from home. When Eleanor first started coming with me (beginning of August), she would bark uncontrollably at the dad any time he walked out of his office. If he would go to the kitchen to get food, shed follow him in barking. She doesn't do it anymore at all. She has grown to love him which has been an interesting transition to watch.   She also has started to come when her name is called. It used to make going to the dog park very difficult.   She is a runner and bolts out the door whenever she gets the chance, and runs around the neighborhood. She isn't trusted to be off leash at a dog park that isn't fenced in
He's wanting to be picked up to be on the bed instead of using his doggie stairs for that.

It's difficult to answer these questions as my dog has gone blind in the last year. I got her when she was 12, she's now 14. She had glaucoma but could see thru one eye. In the last few months, she was diagnosed with cataracts in her other eye. Her activity level has gone down a lot, she's become a very slow walker but is still happy. She loves sniffing and finding treats that are hidden.

Since quarantine, now that I'm home almost all of the time, he has become a bit more independent, less inclined to cuddle 100% of the time we're hanging out.  I noticed a similar change in behavior towards more independence when we lived in a bigger house about 3 years back.

"Better uses the words he can say to get what he wants.  He can say ""Costco"" ""I love you"" and ""out"" . Before he would say Costco and I love you when asked to get a treat. Now he initiates the ""conversation"" Before he would say out if he needed to go to the bathroom. Now he says out if he is bored and says Costco out if he really needs to go to the bathroom."

He is much more alert. That is understandable though. In January of 2020 his big brother, to whom he was very attached, died. In September a puppy joined our household. He is playing with her constantly. Sometimes he starts it, sometimes she does. He is constantly looking out for her, and is extremely patient. His older brother exhibited those behaviors with him for 10 years. He learned well, and is much more patient than I ever expected, and much more playful than I ever expected.

She is more alert and receptive to what we say.  She seems to know words we are spelling to keep her from knowing something, she is so smart.  She is so attentive and speaks to us to let us know what she wants or needs.  She has picked up so much each month she aged.  She learns so quickly.

She's become even more stubborn and resentful of my help. She'll be struggling to get up in my bed, I'll pick her up and put her in bed...she'll get down and attempt it herself. I saw this same awesome behavior as my dad wound down with vascular dementia.
I feel she has become more clever. She figures out things faster.
He seems to be losing his hearing:  he doesn't respond when we call him, even for dinner He will stand on the patio and bark rather than automatically jump up the three steps to the house
Buddy has been calming down and seemed to be less anxious as he's been growing up. He's also calmer in the winter and less interested in outdoor activities, which leads to less pacing.

I think she's gotten more stubborn. For example, stopping dead on a leash if headed home and she's not ready to go home.  I find that squatting down will bring her to me and get her moving, more than ordering her around. Still trying to figure this one out.
Emmy will sit indoors at the window watching for squirrels or birds. She does this more frequently now because she gets only 2 walk a day, not 3 outside walks due to covid-19.

I feel like there's more napping. She's always been a lazy dog (unless there's good hiking or swimming or squirrels!) but she's definitely slowing down. Re: some of the earlier questions about not recognizing people or finding food on the floor, she has eyesight issues, so I think that's the problem rather than cognitive decline.

He has become much more confident and less anxious since we moved and are no longer living with a roommate. Also, he has started somewhat playing with the dogs at the dog park versus just standing next to us.
Max seems to sleep more soundly which might be due to not hearing quite as well as he used to hear.
No. He is as bright and active as he has ever been.

"I got Fritz when he was about 1 year old, max. I also had Molly, at the time a 11 year old lab mix, about the same size. After a while they got along great and we moved from OK City to Wisconsin. After two years here Molly passed. That was about three weeks ago. I wanted Fritz present when the home vet put Molly to sleep, so he saw her leave. I live in a small bungalow so they were also close to each other, and for a week or so Fritz seemed distant. Then he started getting closer. Now he seems to have a routine for when and where he likes to lay down. He's 3-1/2 now and in the last two weeks we've gone on longer walks, and more often. That's why Fritz is ""much more"" active, and he is settling into being an 'only' dog after losing his best friend. He seems to be doing fine."
maybe slightly more chill, now extremely rare to no jumping on people when they come over

Kiki is 20 months old.  In the last 6 months she has matured a great deal in terms of her focus in training.  I would say she has transitioned from a puppy who while was very trainable, she had a limited attention span, to a much more attentive dog in obedience and agility classes.  Also seeing much less of the typical puppy issues of chewing and accidents in the house!

She communicates more.   She jumps up- but only high enough so that I can see her eyes looking at me. Usually it's when I'm sitting  in my reclliner and when she wants to get my attention.    Anytime I play a u-Tube video she jumps in my lap and puts her paws on my desk and watches intently with me.   Also, when a dog is on TV, she runs over and watches with great focus. "None.  He is decidedly farsighted, so he loves watching things in the distance and retrieves well but can have problems with object discrimination at close range. He's started going in the closet and accidentally closing the door and trapping himself in the laundry room, something he didn't do very often until recently.  He can open doors and doorknobs if he can push, so he often opens the door to the basement while I am out, in case he has to go potty   (he annoyingly decides downstairs-- an unfinished basement-- is the least injurious place, which is sort of accurate, but now he hasn't had an accident for months.). I lock the door when I go in case he gets a mind to go out.  He can't open the storm door handle so he's done damage to the storm door.  (He's smart.)   However, his kitchen sound alerting is iffy-- he goes through cycles,  and he keeps coming up and looking to the door when I am working in the kitchen. Six months ago... well, the pandemic means we both go out much less, and the increased UV-A this spring (ozone layer thinned from polar vortex) has created more sun-related symptoms for me, so I've been restricting my outside time during daylight hours.  I worry he's bored and a little depressed. When the weather is good, he wants to be outside about all day whether I am there or not and he'll watch squirrels and people and cars (farsighted, remember.) It's no longer painful, but it does still itch; and because she will chew and lick at it until it's sore and bleeding, she has to wear a lampshade-sized E-collar. Unfortunately, part of the cause of the itchiness is her anxiety and it becomes a vicious circle for her. I'm hoping that with daily soaking of the foot in warm water and Epsom salts, the foot will heal to the point where she doesn't need to wear the cone any more.  I do give her calming chews when she's especially anxious but they only last for about 4-6 hours and I don't feel comfortable giving her more than the suggested number for a dog her size.
He is still pretty young and a little hyper active.  I have another Springer Spaniel that he interacts with
Hearing seems to be deteriorating slightly. She is sleeping a lot more.

Yes. My dog has always had severe separation anxiety. This causes him to panic breathe and panic walk back and forth. Halley appears sharp as ever.  She has osteoarthritis in her front paws which has been sever at times.  She is on several different anti-inflammatory and chronic pain meds with likely phase her out a bit.  Overwise, she is doing really well.

Hungry all the time but due to lack of teeth, very common in his breed after the age of 10 .... they simply are no chewers, it takes him all day to eat. No doubt his gums are sore but at 16 1/2 no way are we going to subject him to anesthesia to pull the rest of his remaining few teeth.
No, she is has been very consistent with her behavior and thinking over the years.  Only major change would be she's mellowed out more with age.

"I have noted some separation anxiety since I have been working from home this year, starting in mid-March. Dylan used to spend all day home alone except on my lunch break. He also sleeps here, and seems very comfortable with the arrangement. He is clear when its time for bed and wants me to ""tuck him in."" The weather has been very mild and so his preference now is to be outside all day, except for meals, walks, and bedtime. We used to spend more time together, while I watched tv or napped. He will lay at my feet while I watch tv, but gets restless when I nap on the sofa (he used to nap on the floor right next to me). His hearing is deteriorating and he sleeps very soundly now. He has adapted to our routine, and doesn't really like any changes to it. When he is unhappy or stressed he will ""dig up"" a small area rug in the room where he sleeps. He also pants almost constantly now. When I am working or doing something he does not want me to do he will stand in the doorway and pant, pacing. As long as I can put him outside he is happiest. Not sure how it will go when the weather prevents that."

Six months is too short a time frame for a dog that is nearly 15 and those behaviors aren't her changes. "With the pandemic lock down, we've been working from home since March (it's now November). During this time, her behavior has changed a bit, but I believe it's due to the stress of having the whole family home from March to September. In September, the kids went back to school and now it's just the two adults, working on two different floors of the home. Since then, she's been much more angsty. She has a harder time settling, she asks to go outside on a nearly hourly basis. I think she's stressed that the kids aren't here anymore and that the adults are split apart. She's often exhibited stress when my husband has left the house and I'm home alone, despite me being her ""safe"" parent, and him being the ""fun"" one. I'm on the main floor, and he's in the basement, where she isn't allowed. I have a theory that if he was on this floor with me she'd be more relaxed, but we haven't had a chance to test that hypothesis. TL;DR - she's a bit more restless during the day now than she was prior to September, and even more prior to March. "

none. Although the question about avoiding being petted...dogs often do this because they simply don't want to be touched, just like people. she is picking up new moves playing with other dogs much quicker, and she now LOVES dogs (almost too much and more than people sometimes) vs. when she was a smaller puppy she was very shy around other dogs

Bruce does does not seem to want to go for walks as much as he used to. I used to take him for a 30-60 minute walk most days of the week and he would beg for a walk if I hadn't taken him yet. The change seemed to have started before 4th of July on a nighttime (after dark) walk when we saw a coyote. He turned around and pulled me home. After that he didn't want to go for a walk after dusk, but would go in the morning or early afternoon. Soon after that fireworks started for 4th of July (people set off a fireworks at their homes in 2020 due to Covid boredom). Because Bruce hates loud noises like fireworks and thunder, he started refusing to go for walks at all, regardless of time of day (that was my guess). Throughout November, he has started getting much better about going for walks, even occasionally going after it gets dark, but sometimes will still refuse. For example yesterday I tried to take him around 1pm when it was still plenty light, he acted excited to go but when we went out he turned around multiple times, eventually returning home after only 15 minutes of walking (as compared to an hour or so of walking on good days). It's challenging for me because I enjoy going for a walk with him and previously it seemed to bring him so much joy.

We are in the middle of a move. We have left our house and are temporarily living with a relative while we search for a new home. This relative has a cat, and we did not know that our dog would think the cat is a squirrel! We can tell our dog is experiencing heightened stress and separation anxiety. He wants to go home.

He easily remembers old rules from a year or so ago. For example, at a previous residence, he would have to sit before I would open the door to come in. It's not something I've had him do in 6-9 months, but he quickly remembered what to do when I recently paused at the door and just looked at him.

No. The arthritis in his legs is getting worse. He is slow walking, and he trips sometimes. Often now, he cannot lift his leg to urinate; he has to squat. He sleeps more hours of the day. Although he doesn't stare at walls or floor, he frequently sits and stares into open space.

He has learned some new vocabulary and responds appropriately.

Loader is scared of pretty much anything related to moving objects (bicycles, skateboards, etc.)  In March we were on a walk, which we had been doing faithfully daily, for over 2 years, when he was scared by a bicycle doing a u-turn in front of us. I engage a dog therapist who during covid could not come to our home.  We tried some behavior modification using cheese / treats that didn't help.  I then took Loader to a vet and he was put on Dog Prozac.  He then had the opposite reaction once on the medication and lost about 7 lbs. in 2 weeks (the length of time the vet asked that we give it to him to try), and was even more scared (woudn't go for a ride in the truck, wouldn't get more than 2 inches away from his people.  We had to take him off the Dog Prozac.  So now we are back to scared Loader that he was before the medication.  He will go for rides in the truck but still won't go for walks in our neighborhood.  I can take him someplace and he will walk for about 20 minutes before he starts getting scared and wants to go back to the car.

Also ... the previous questions about what has changed from 6 months ago are not really relevant for him. He does not urinate or defecate in the house at all. He always lets me know when he needs to go out, even when he is sick and it's the middle of the night.
Since she was a retired breeder she has started to act much more relaxed and happier than when I first got her.

Spending more time with her due to COVID and taught her new tricks.  She has also mastered various dog puzzles / interactive games; she is at level 4!   She loves to play with these interactive games since treats are hidden in them.  She mastered someone and done,  others took a little longer, but she knows all the tricks.  I can't locate any new games.  Maybe I should design some!
He follows me a bit more in the house than he used to.
Sometimes she can't find me in the house. We moved in March so we have been here a while now
"She understands a few more words and responds, i.e. goes to kitchen to check her food dish when I am in the hall and point toward the kitchen while saying ""kitchen""."
We added a puppy to the family nearly a year ago and I can see the them jockey for alpha status. Tripp very much wants to be alpha but he will back down to avoid being plowed over.

Wakes up multiple times each night to go outside and urinate.  Lately then drinks (vast) amounts of water in one sitting.  This is now a messy process:)  He can no longer get up from lying down without some assistance:(  He figits often, as if he has something to do but cannot remember what it is...
This happens rarely but sometimes he does not want to play with his sister. She will start a play stance and perhaps nip him and he will turn away and make it obvious he is not interested.

Kiwi and I do nose work 1 day a week, for 15-20 minutes.  She continues to progress in her curiosity for finding both food and scent, as well as her ability to zero in on objects that might contain scent (boxes, benches or other potential hosts for scent filled tins).  I believe that this practice is stimulating for Kiwi, as well as somewhat tiring, and she has stayed sharper.
She has become more verbal and is able to communicate what she wants whether it be hunger, go outside, and corral us in her space.
No changes in the past 6 months.
He's gotten more sensitive to my feeling upset and tries to comfort me more

She is extremely active, fearless, loyal, & stubborn. She has a very high prey drive targeting anything that is not a domestic dog. She does differentiate between chihuahuas and rabbits,  though. She does well at dog parks.  When I got Luna, I was her 3rd owner in 11 months.  It took about 6 months for her to settle in and to get her out of her own head. We are still working on impulse control, but she has improved significantly over the last 6 months. Once we get basic obedience down, i want to get her into agility. Not to compete, but to give her a focus.
Belle has always been a couch potato! She does run when she's in the yard a few times a day but that's only a few minutes each time. She does seem to enjoy it though.
"He has become much more picky about food --choosing what and when to eat.  Also seems to ""need"" me more.  He stays closer to me."
None noted.  She is alert, very communicative, does some tricks and ignores commands when she feels like it (LOL).

"At 3 years and 9 months Dewey has become much more communicative with me.  He comes when called faster than a year ago.  I think this is his maturing with being more connected to me.  I put down my 14 year old dog last year (Maddy) and got a new puppy 3 months later.  He is now the dog who is always with me when I'm in my office.  Gracie the one year old still has the ""zoomies"".  Dewey is a sweet boy and selective with his affection.  I think he really missed my older dog who was a ""buddha"" dog and taught him so  much.  He has really blossomed and loves his younger ""sister"".  "

She is consistent with previous behavior but has developed them.  She has new games such as snatching rolls of toilet paper and running away with them.  She recovers from frights more quickly, such as a loud new noise.  She is more confident in that she approaches strangers where before she would not approach.  She has greater concentration, as she can do a longer training sessions.   Either she or I are getting better at training, she catches on very fast and faster and faster.   RedBunny rules.

She has become more attached to me.  If I'm lying on the couch she will jump up on me and stand on my chest while I pet and talk to her.  During the night she will come up on the bed and walk up me to my chest.  Then she will roll off me on to her back so I can pet her tummy.  She will also want me to scratch her head during the night.  She loves to go into the garden with me and will frequently stand on her hind legs to give me hugs while we are there.
she needs to be prompted to eat sometimes.

His energy level has gone down a lot and is more regulated. He seems to enjoy routine more than 6 months ago and he is less interested in running around and more interested in chewing bones. He patrols the yard and house several times a day and watches out the window a lot. He is more interested in TV than 6 months ago and seems engaged while watching it. He likes Mr. Rodgers neighborhood and made for TV movies. He hates curious George and Hachi and anything with guns or fire. Overall Fudge is a lot more manageable and easier to predict than in the past. He also seems to be sleeping a LOT more.
When I am not sitting with him he looks for me.  If I go to the basement where he cannot go, he paces until I come back up.

Maggie Rose doesn't hear as well as she used to and in addition she doesn't see as well (but doesn't have cataracts).  As a result sometimes she is a little more hesitant when we are walking and may get behind me if there is a larger group of people or dogs.  Her energy level is still high though.
She seems more antsy in the evenings, struggles to settle after dinner.
Hes extremely intelligent. Learns after 1 go. As a pup he was house trained in a week. He loves to watch and learn, but not the usual dog stuff learn.

He seems more knowledgeable. He previously was unable to open the baby gates when locked in both directions, but now seems to do it when we are not around to get to our 6 month old child. He also has become more friendly with our child wiggling his but anytime he sees him.

We've observed no changes in Troi's cognitive behavior.  We are pleased that at age 9 she is active and engaged.  She even recognizes the vehicles of favorite friends as soon as they appear in the driveway.  Thank you for your very thorough data collection.
Sometimes she seems depressed and I wonder if she feels sad that our younger Lab, Mia, shares our attention.

We have moved into a new house, on the same property, and the old house was demolished. Both existed for a short time and it was really hard to get him to come into the new house. Now that the old one is gone, he still will lay on the ground where the old house was sometimes, but he does come inside the new house, and has selected a spot under a large dining table where he lays most of the time. The younger dogs and cats don't seem to bother him there, which is why I think he likes it.

The paving in circles has been going on for a while. Mostly in the evenings. Almost like she has Sundowners syndrome like in people. I guess it's good exercise. About the only she gets because we pretty much carry her everywhere

No real observable change with exception of morning medication administration time which he knows -  it is necessary to push a very large heart pill ( Vetmedin) down his throat only in the morning.  He clearly seeks to avoid this effort but cooperates when cornered (gently). His other medications can be administered with food and he is quite good about cooperation with these efforts.   Yankee is a very smart fellow and very perceptive - if anything, I think his thinking capability is a bit more acute than six months ago.

Max was having some issues with being aggressive toward other dogs.  I walked him for about a month with a haltie in addition to his prong collar.  Now I can walk him without the haltie, although I have it with me if another dog gets near.  He has not exhibited any aggression since I began this training.
Sometimes he forgets why he wanted to go outside and scratches to be let in immediately.
Milo now gets agitated by extreme weather, such as thunderstorms or heavy wind (panting, drooling). Until about six months ago it wasn't a problem.

In the past, she has been reactive in certain situations and often anxious.  I've worked with her and trained throughout her lifetime.  In the past year and certainly in the last 6 months I am aware of her being increasingly confident and calm in situations that in the past would have set her off.
She is hungry a lot more. No patience while waiting for her food.

Reagan is blind, so it's not uncommon for him to bump into walls when moving from room to room. Lately, it seems he gets confused about where he is a bit more often. It could be that slight changes in furniture locations are to blame, but it seems to be a significant enough change that we have noticed it.
has recently nipped (bruised but did not break skin)  2 people familiar to him.
No, He has been the same

Max hurt his back in January 2020. He's been receiving acupuncture for the last six months and slowly got better. After the injury, he did not want to run after a toy and retrieve it. In October, he brought the toy to me a few times for me to throw it. He had never done this before! He only retrieves about 3 times but I was happy to see this behavior.

She seems more intuitive and correctly anticipates when we are going on walks or when she will or won't be going with us in the car.  We are particularly amazed by how she knows whether or not she is going in the car, and wonder what cues we are possibly giving her on that.  She also likes to go to bed at about 10:00, knows when that time is and  starts to softly 'lobby' us to get ready for bed.  It starts with a request to go outside and potty.  Then she goes straight to our bedroom and stares at the bed, asking to be put up on it.  If we stay up past 10:00, she just rests on the bed and waits for us quietly.
She remains extremely mentally alert and competent

Rocco seems much more interested in what we are doing. He follows our movements, as if he is trying to learn the steps, anything from household chores to cooking. He is becoming more curious as he ages.
We do competition obedience. In the last 6 months, Clancy is much improved. He follows directions, and thinks for himself
She sleeps for longer periods during the day and settles earlier at night
I have only had Gigi since  mid October 2020.  I will look for these traits as time goes forward.
He is learning more words and understanding more words. We constantly talk to him and his older sister.
For 9 years of age, Teddy is doing really well.  We haven't notice a decline at all so far.

I have begun giving her organic colostrum, pre and probiotics, feeding more raw meat and bones. A week after the addition of these things, Gracie is more active, jumps up, trots on our walks, and seems more alert. This is a drastic change from previous behavior.  She has not had accidents in the house she is alert. Only sense that appears to be affected is her hearing. Sometimes, I can't tell if it is selective hearing or if she really can't hear me.
Mocha seems much more alert than a year ago. She very stand of fish being a rescue dog but now is much more loving and has her calm moments

Lately, last two months or so, she has started leaning against walls or large objects, turns or veers to the right when passing through portals, and sleeps more during the day than at night.  Her nighttime behavior is beginning to significantly interfere with our rest.  She has accidents in the house almost daily; fortunately, until about 6 months ago, this never occurred, zero times.  Poor old girl.
cognitively she seems the same, just sleeps more
She is much more vocal while I'm preparing her food.  She is also more vocal as we approach our walking spots.  I drive to places where she can be off leash. She is also more deaf.

I have a toddler who has become much more active in the last year. My dog, Tyson, had some anxiety about a rambunctious two year old invading his space. He would leave the room or move to the floor if we were on the couch or move to the couch if we were on the floor to get away from us. Anytime the toddler made a loud noise like a squeal or giggle Tyson would freeze and stare with a stiff tail and perky ears. He would huff in irritation and wanted nothing to do with an adult if they were holding the toddler. Not even for treats. And Tyson doesn't turn down treats. Ever. He was very unsure of the little human's unpredictable behaviors. In the last six months, Tyson has grown accustomed to my toddler being increasingly active. Tyson is longer phased by the activity and will nap in the middle of the floor while toys and balls fly over him and sometimes even land on him. Tyson will separate his toys from the toddler's toys when they get mixed up. He will even pick up some small toys and put them in the play pen when the toddler throws them out. He does that on his own. He wasn't taught to do it. He keeps a watchful eye on the toddler when the two other dogs we have are being rowdy in the toddlers vicinity. I've even seen him get up from his comfy spot on the couch and put himself in between the toddler and the other dogs like a protective shield. He went from being uneasy about the little human moving around to being a protector and overall pretty chill in the middle of the chaos. It's been fun to watch Tyson figure out the toddlers's behavior and get over his apprehension. He lets the toddler pet him and lay on him while he's napping. He knows the difference between the toddlers loud noises now too. He can tell if it's distress or playful and he reacts accordingly. Very cool to see.
Hera is continuing to be more affectionate.
Emma is beginning to lose control in her rear hips.  Occasionally, she will do the 'splits' with he back legs.  This tends to happen more in the afternoons and evenings.
No.  There have been no changes.
I have not observed any changes.
Sleeping more. The quality of exercise is less intensive. The quantity of exercise is slightly less. My dog never tolerated the heat very well. Lately it seems worst

None.  She seems all there with no issues (yet).

He is more aware of what we are doing - he anticipates our actions.  As an example, when I pick up gym equipment he immediately runs to the back door to go outside with me.  In the evenings, when we turn off the TV he immediately runs to the front door to go outside to relieve himself before we go to bed.

"When we are on our walk, Dyna is the one who selects the route to take.  Sometimes she has a difficult time choosing which direction to go at an intersection or a ""choice"" in her path. This only happens sometimes; not on every walk."

Six months ago, Shaggy had a second seizure and hurt his neck doing a sommersault (who knew he wanted to do one?!). Ever since he walks less and less; spending more time just sitting on his bed than moving around.

He's become more attached to me. I'm not sure if it's because I'm home more (pandemic) or more stressed (pandemic + sick parent), but he really puts up a fight if my partner tries to take him on a walk without me
Asher seems slightly more reactive to noises at night, and will start and continue barking. It is difficult to get him to settle once triggered by a noise.

He has always eaten at 5PM at the earliest, or when we got home from work/school. Now that we are home all the time, he wants food earlier (he starts begging around 3). He has gained some weight over this time period, so we are still working through the best way to manage his food intake when we're no longer out of the house all day.
Generally less responsive, less  involved. 6 months ago, always slept in same place on bedroom floor.  Now sleeps anywhere on it.
No other changes. My answers regarding not being able to see food dropped are based on the fact that she lost one eye to glaucoma, so her eyesight is definitely hindered than it was previously.

Increased capacity to think through problems -- turn tub containing toys on its side to fish out his favorite toy (sitting on the bottom) rather than pulling all 20-30 toys out one at a time.  When stealing treats away from the other dog -- using paw to pull the loose treat towards him rather than sticking his face closer
Goes to bed earlier, spends more time in his bed in our bedroom than in the living room with us at night.
Luna is 10 now, but has the same behaviors she has always had. Right now, I don't see any changes at all in her- behavior, attitude, eating, awareness, etc.

"Mozzie just turned two years old. I have seen development/maturity in his thinking and problem solving abilities. Also, he is less excitable, in the ""puppyish"" sense."

We remodeled the bathroom and she will not go in.  She used to with no problem

He doesn't always respond to his name and has gotten much more intense about his sniffing on walks. He sniffs EVERYTHING to a point where it slows our walks an incredible amount.
He seems to stare at the wall more when he has a citronella collar on, even if the collar itself is turned off. This also happens if I put fun bandanas around his neck
Less interested in going on long walks, a little slower
No changes in thinking, but he does seem to have a little more energy and motivation since starting the thyro-tabs in the spring.

He's begun sleeping in bed with us. Previously he would come to bed and as long as we were actively petting him, he'd stay. This could be because the weather has gotten colder but he did not do this last winter.
She seems much more patient  and loving

"I have only had Kelly for three months and as a 14 month old dog he is very active. I recently began feeding him with a food puzzle since he was eating too fast.
