Tennis balls are his favorite toys and they are scattered all over the house and yard. I can say to him ... ""Get your ball"" and he goes on a search for one and almost always brings one back."
She sometimes has to try two times to jump on the couch.  The couch is higher than most.  She uses stairs to get on the bed.  Other than that, no changes.
She's only 5 months old, so we don't have much data yet.
We adopted her about 3 months ago, but she is much more active and happier than when we first met her in the shelter
At 3, Sam is still learning new words and cues and is very alert!

She's been scared of gunshots, thunder, fireworks for a long time, and she now (will generally pace for a while trying to find a safe spot) seems to associate some quiet noises with those too. It's a different reaction though (slightly worried, but hurries over for attention), possibly the new behavior is a game for her.

Zelda has become really scared of thunder and fireworks.  She now refuses to go for walks at night even though we have not heard either in a long time.  She seems to be associating darkness with thunder and fireworks.  If she hears either she starts shaking and freezes.  She becomes almost unable to move.    She is also balking at walking around the block beyond a certain point.  It's like she gets scared of something, but we can't figure out what it is.
"I. The last 6 months we lost a dog, since then Sadie is much more a ""lap"" dog!  "

I've  been working on training to help him respond more to me outside house. He is a very externally focused dog (i.e.  more stimulated  by environment  than connecting  w me outside). So his ability to recognize and understand my attempt to get his attn and to focus on me has increased

Rooney has epilepsy. That is the reason for his behaviors and my answers asked about in this survey. If he isn't having seizures he doesn't have these after effects. He a normal, living, wiggling and wagging little guy. He is heavily medicated and often subdued but he still has his sweet personality.

No. She's very sharp. Understands words. Recognizes people and places she hasn't seen in a long time. Knows where to find her diving and swimming spots on infrequent walking locations. Constantly carries her ball on walks and demands frequent retrieves, although as a puppy - 2 years, she was a non-stop retriever dropping the ball at my feet for the next Chuck-It throw as soon as she got back to me.
He's young, from rescue and has grown closer and more trusting

Ethan calmed down about 4 months ago. He seldom grabs a personal item of mine to get me to play with him. He mainly uses a chuck-it ball or a squeaky toy when he wants to play. When I leave him alone he no longer goes into his crate. He just sleeps on the bed. He goes to doggy daycare two times a week which helps immensely.  I take him to an off-leash dog park at least once a week. He just started not being as interested in being in the off leash area. He seems to prefer being on the leash and exploring the paths through woods and fields. It's a marked changed.

Nope.  Aengus is still the same dog he has always been.  As hard as this is to believe.....a bit of a 'surfer dude' for an Irish Terrier.  He is so easy going.  Amazing.  And, his little IT brother adores him!
More hesitant at times going down 2 stairs to go outside to the backyard (he does have arthritis effecting back legs)
Eating pattern she seems to want to be spoon fed and richer tasting food.
Spending more time licking the bottom of his paws and sofa cushions.
Responds less to outside sounds and mail man (which used to drive her crazy!).  Hearing issue maybe?
We've moved to a new house and he now swims daily in a lake. His problem solving , following a pointing hand , and orienting himself to space has improved. However, he's much more hyper-vigilant.

Over the last couple of months and especially with the time change Deja has begun to whine a lot more- for her dinner especially. But also in general she just whines. She does not appear to be in pain at rest. We feel she is bored because she cannot be as active or play like she used to.

Two months ago, we took Kaya  camping with us for one week. Since our return, she does not seem to recognize our cat as the cat she had known for a year and a half prior to the trip. She doesn't exhibit aggressive behavior, she simply seems to think that this is a new cat compared to the cat we had before. It's like starting from scratch trying to get her to calm down around the cat again.

We've only had him 6 months, but I think he's gotten much more confident around my husband and I. He was a little nervous when we brought him home, but his anxiety seems to have improved dramatically.
no, but his hearing is almost completely gone.
I have only had him 2 1/2 months so some of the questions were not relevant.
She now plans our walks to always walk to one of her friends houses.
He is learned to step onto a large ball and walk backwards to move it out of a corner - pretty cool

She is now exhibiting behavior that confirms that she is losing hearing. She no longer wants to play ball. She has started sneezing a lot to get attention. She doesn't have any other reason to sneeze.
He's more needy for affection.  When he wants us to sit w/ him he will talk to us or when he thinks it's time to eat- haha!
He is not as excited to leave for a walk but is happy once we go

she's still very prey-driven (loves to chase her Extreme-size Kong) but occasionally gets distracted by - birds? passers-by? - and stands holding  it instead of immediately dropping it for me to throw again.
Sometimes when I walk him he just stops and wants to look around him for a few minutes before allowing me to pull him to walk
She gets a little more irritated if I forget to give her a treat when she expects one.
She's almost exactly the same as 12 years ago, she just naps more and stretches when she gets up.

Sugar is completely blind so some of these responses of staring at walls or doors, bumping into object, or not finding her way I attribute to her not being able to see, not because of her cognitive abilities.  Let me know if there is a survey or test to separate this two issues from one another and I will be happy to take it.  :-)

In the last couple of weeks he started chewing on the foot board of the bed in the guest room. It's been over two years since he has chewed something beyond his toys. I closed off the room from him and talked to his doctor who agreed with my strategy. It was suggested Eddie is picking up on my stress and that's why he's chewing wood, but...he has access to wood all around the house and nothing else has been touched. It is my belief that he just discovered the wood on the bed and due to it's age (late 1800s), he really likes it.

He is least active in july/aug -- but then by november is performing happy dances as the cold weather returns. This is unsurprising; he is a malamute. But i do sometimes think that maybe he is slowing down but then autumn returns .
She has very bad arthritis in her hips, so she spends much of the day sleeping. She still seems to recognize all family members and doesn't show signs of dementia.
No change.  Stella has never been expressive She has never barked.  She dies wag her tail when she hears treats or a walk. She is friendly with adults and children in a quiet subdued way
She needs to urinate a little more often.

Ernie seems to be a bit more hesitant (stubborn?) about doing what is asked. For example he doesn't always walk over to be petted unless it's his idea. He sometimes seems confused at what we are directing him to do
Her restlessness is purposeful. She is finding a new resting spot usually wherever we are.
Cookie can still run 10 miles in a day

Rica is a joyous, active dog with an enormous amount of energy  that is much higher than one would expect of a 6.5 year old dog. She wants to interact, play, chase balls, chase deer, go on a long walk, and just do anything with her family. No signs of arthritis or dementia yet.
She knows how to relax. She can sit with us while we wait or as we are waking up instead of running around all the time.
He's more vocal when we return home or whe he wants a treat.  He also goes and sits beside hit treat bucket, then grunts to get our attention.

Nothing of note. She really liked having the family around during quarantine and stay at home orders. She's probably a little lonely now that schools are back in sessions and the kids aren't home during the day.

This year our dog developed cataracts caused by bad genetics. He underwent surgery to remove the cataracts which along with full return of his vision, has also brought back his confidence to the level it was previously.
Some of these behaviors are a manifestation of Harry's ongoing eyesight degeneration as opposed to thinking or information processing.
No changes- he's the same as he was six months ago- he follows me around all day, scarfs down his food, never has accidents, never gets confused, never stares aimlessly and never walks in circles.

He stares into rooms -into the shadows quite often. He will wake/get up at night and look into the shadows.  He recently went through a hurricane and he showed panic where thunderstorms don't bother him nearly as much, but I know he has never liked high winds.
No changes in the past six months

Clover is learning more every day. She is quicker to pick up on things, she observes more. She is growing out of her puppy phase. She also seems more aware of the pain in her hips. She either avoids a movement or if during play she thinks she is going to get hit in the hips, she will tighten up.

Camino has improved his vocal sounds to communicate his wants with us.  He is more likely to look me in the eye and make sounds which indicate that he wants something. Because his wants follow a somewhat predictable pattern through the day, we can generally figure out what Camino wants (thereby reinforcing his vocalizations)

"He has had a vasectomy but you would never know. He has increased his urine marking. Before he occasionally marked now we clean up marked places 3 to 5 times a day. He has been to vet & is in good health. We have been told to have him ""properly"" neutered. Sigh. Not happening. We are using sprays & diapers sparingly. We don't give him much credit for thinking process. Seems more instinctual to us. "

We brought a new husky/cattle dog puppy into the house a few months ago which has certainly had an impact on her. She is mostly ok with it (until she's not), but has certainly stepped up her playing, activity, demand for our attention, and her cleverness is on full display as she out-maneuvers the puppy for treats or time or attention. While it has made her somewhat more cranky, it has also challenged her in ways that seem positive.

No changes noted. He showed depression after his brother died in January but recovered from that with a lot of attention and the addition of another dog in May.  I've been home pretty much full time since March so spending a lot more time with Calvin.  I'm very sensitive to his decreased vision and hearing so make sure that I'm always aware of where he is and what he's doing.
Murfee is only 15 months old but for the past 6 months she has been participating in Barn Hunt and Scent Work.  I feel that this has made her thinking more focused.
No particular changes in last six months.
My Rosie is only 8 months old so she is more and more playful every day

I forgot to tell you originally.  She is a rescue from a small puppy mill.  They were using her as a breeder which I did not realize until I got her spayed.  She chases cars; again; no clue until we moved from a rural property to town.  I never let her off lead, as I am terrified that she will be hurt.  She barks a lot, but especially at men in dark clothes.  I suspect some jerk kicked her before I got her.  She flinches if you have your legs on the sofa and put your foot down.  When I first got her, if you touched her rear end she would react and go after your hand.  Never biting; just letting you know she was unhappy.  Forced breeding perhaps?   Now, she will stretch in front of me and let me scratch her bottom.  I have seen significant improvement in her trust and behavior over the last 7 years.  She was 4 when I got her; now 11 and a happy girl.  I could go on about puppy mills, but I am sure that you all agree.   She is in good health now and I hope to have her for several more years.  Thanks for doing this study.
She no longer demands to be fed at 5:00am. She'll sleep in and get up with us about 7:30 and eat then.
Nothing I can think of offhand.  My dog is very young so maybe we'll see these changes later in time...
I think he's getting 'smarter.'  Well, maybe he's 'training' us, too.

Liberty was wary of a stranger in sun glasses a few days ago. We offered her reassurance and spoke to the person so she knew he was okay. The state restrictions have affected her ability to socialize, meet new people, and experience new situations.
Lily is 16 which is so incredible. She is a bit senile and has trouble seeing. She's my best girl in the world.
No. Even though he's 10 years old now he's still as sharp and alert as when he was younger.

radical difference in Sienna's behavior at night when it's time to go to bed. For many years, bedtime was never an issue! Working with our vet on the belief that she is possibly suffering from Alzheimers/Dementia, our current medical treatment is Gabapentin, 300MG 2/day; Amitriptyline, 50MG 1/day; Trazodone, 100MG and 5MG Melatonin. Roo is 1.25 years old. The first six months she grew 60 pounds and some months she was putting on 12 pounds a month... all body growth, not much brain/skull (tiny little head on a huge body for way too long). Only after she stopped growing did her brain and head size finally catch up, so now I have a 75 pound golden with the cognitive and emotional capacity of a 6 month old puppy. She hated to snuggle or be held as a pup, was supremely confident about life and wouldn't listen to people or respond to affection as a reward (although she is almost the fastest pup I've housetrained - she had the coordination to use the dog door and do stairs at 10 weeks and preferred to use grass for her business - so she did.) She's not dumb at all, but for a golden retriever, her affinity to humans took a while to show up. Now she is bold, a playful thief, sometimes with wild energy and very physical play (esp with my other golden), very busy energy, but she uses her talk buttons to ask for dinner and carrots, knows some toys by name, brings every bone in the house to lay and chew at my feet while I watch tv (one at a time, chews it for 2-3 minutes and then goes to get another one), and choose to cuddle on the couch and sleeps on the bed with me at night. Compared to all the other golden puppies I have had, she's very different in her development and people affinity but luckily she's catching up quickly. Not quite the cognitive decline you're measuring but a slightly atypical development from my own experience that might be interesting.

Monty occasionally runs into barriers--doors, fences, etc.--when he is moving too quickly due to the fact that he has been completely blind due to cataracts for the past couple of years. I believe that this is due to his blindness and not due to disorientation. In the past when he could see, he would go toward the door and bark a time or two when he needed to go outside. Now, he comes to where I am and barks a time or two when he needs to go out, which I believe is an adaptive behavior, on his part, due to his blindness. He is currently age 14+ and will turn 15 this coming Spring. He sometimes has a little difficulty finding food dropped on the floor as he must entirely rely upon his nose, although he always locates food that either he or I have dropped onto the floor within a few seconds by using his highly efficient and perceptive hound nose. While he still runs eagerly to the door to greet me or to go outside or for a ride, he sleeps VERY soundly and for much longer at a time these days. He can still hear well, it seems, and will rouse from sleep (eventually) when I call his name and will still come when called when he is out in the yard as he has always done, on his terms. He will turn his head toward the sound of my voice, but may or may not come immediately.  For the past approximately 3 years, he has needed to be on anti-seizure medicine and also takes medicine to control the essential tremors he began having in his hind legs and his jaw about 2 years ago. Fortunately, both of these conditions are now well controlled with medication. He also takes a daily CoQ10, 30 mg. supplement, 150 mg. daily of Milk Thistle, and a daily probiotic supplement.

No.  She is an even keeled dog with very few behavioral issues.  Her biggest problem is that she is leery of strangers and uses me as a refuge to allay her anxieties.  She has an unique history that  likely explains this anxiety:   she was shot in the neck with a .45 (I have the bullet that was removed) as a stray that had torn into someone's garbage.  She was taken to a shelter where she had the bullet removed and there the vet learned she had been spayed prior to her becoming a stray.  There was a TV report on this poor little beagle's plight that I saw and knew I had to bring her home to be a companion to another beagle stray my wife had taken in some years before.  When my family and I arrived at the shelter to pick her up we were greeted by a TV crew.  Her adoption made the nightly news.  She is like most beagles I've had over the years.  Get them on running game and they lose all sense of anything else.  If you are unfortunate enough for them to run a deer, it may be a day or two before you see them.  Thank goodness for the advent of GPS collars.

She stops several times on the walk and just staring and/or looking around. She is also harder to redirect during the walk. There have been several instances that we have to deviate our route because she wants to go a different way. She is less social but is still a very sweet tempered dog.

She sometimes seems to wander into another room looking for one of us, even though no one is in that room. Or sometimes we call to her and she has more trouble than usual figuring out where we are. Again, she is blind, so locating people/things can be a little harder for her but it does sometimes seem a little worse now than it used to be. She was mostly blind at the time we adopted her in spring 2018 and was probably entirely blind by the time she had her eyes removed about a year ago."

"He has calmed down.  He recognizes and obey's ""stop"" command now.  He used to treat me as a playmate, other dog. Now he is respecting a personal boundary set for him by me. He does dislike it when I spend time talking with someone while out with me.  Hopefully more training, as well as maturity , (his, not mine) , will continue to help us be together easily."
she is doing  more nesting behavior (pawing a rug or dog bed and turning one to three times before laying down.
not as playful with other dogs
Slightly hyper, alway seems to be active.
Skye is now 15 months old, I see more problem solving ability like with treat puzzles and she is more eager to learn tricks.
After a walk (abt 2 miles) she seems to want to stand at the end of the driveway and look around the neighborhood just to look around. This started about 4 months ago.

More likely to growl or snap at me or groomer when asked to move over or get off the bed or when handling his feet.  Has always been tender footed.  Groomer said he snapped at her the last time he was groomed around his haunches.  Hair there is very fine and has thick undercoat, so tends to mat easily.  I always suggest a muzzle when getting his toenails clipped or being groomed.

She is learning to differentiate rooms in the house by word command.  For example, I usually ask her to go into the TV room to get my shoes.  She does this right away.  As of this week she has learned which room to go fetch shoe/slipper from kitchen or library.  She knows those three different rooms now  and we are working on a fourth. She responds right away with no prompting.
He seems more protective of the home and barking at strangers outside than previously.

"Shane has always been the ""tattletale"" of the house - coming to me to alert me when someone is doing something or getting into something they shouldn't, and this has not changed.  He's as alert as ever.  "

We've learned a few more commands/tricks so she is exhibiting some additional decision-making to get treats (doing tricks unsolicited or in fast sequence). Her impulse control is improving, mostly due to continuing training and possibly due to maturity as well.
At times, he appears as though he doesn't know how to begin eating or drinking and has to be guided. Once he starts drinking or eating, he does fine.

As Buffy loses some of her hearing, she tends to try to keep us both in her sight.  She is very active and when in AZ, we hike , kayak, bike, etc. it will be a bit  different this year staying at home in VT because of the pandemic. She also misses her socializing now....she is a VT Therapy dog.  When she sees folks, she wants to greet, esp. children and I'm sure doesn't understand why she can't.
Perhaps slightly more grumpy and lethargic. Slower to get up in the morning or respond when called, etc.
No, he seems like a healthy young male.
"She is worse at ""come."" I'm not sure if she can't hear or if she is less obedient"

I have only had my dog 5 months and 5 days so I am mostly getting used to him but he seems to be increasing in his responsiveness to us.  He is not a nervous dog and mostly hangs out near us or gets in his kennel.  We have just begun letting him loose while we are outside in the country where we have a cabin and a big property.  He loves to explore and run like the wind. He may take a few minutes to return when we call him but so far he has always done so without making us worry too much.  He did sniff out a coral snake while on leash but had the where with all to jump back to my side and leave it alone.  Had it been a rattler it may have not been such an easy exit for either of us.
He listens better, is slowing down on the jumping and is more considerate of two other older dogs.  He'll actually lay down and nap now.

Lucky is almost 15 years old and has started to sleep more than she ever has. Not sure if it's age related or due to the COVID pandemic for which her humans are home during the day so we notice it more.

Since covid began, we are all home and are able to spend more time with the dogs. they are more active and getting less treats and more attention. Instead of begging for food, they tend to bring a toy to get playtime.

Hand jestures/commands are better understood and followed. Performs more complex commands (i.e. go get someone for dinner and he has to go up two flights of stairs). Still very schedule driven (i.e. walk after breakfast, swim after dinner). Much more interested in following scents, though his family tree does not have hunting background (the breeder specializes in show/house Labrador retrievers and the dogs have a much calmer demeanor.
No changes or declines in cognition
She seems to be slowing down. Not always as quick thinking and moving as she used to be.

Starting about 6 weeks ago, if our dog, who is blind and deaf (and 18.5 years old) smells people food he wants, is unsure of where he is or wants his water filled, he will stand in one spot and bark over and over until he gets what he wants.
He seems like a big puppy at 9+ years!  Loves his toys, his food, his walks, his road trips (which unfortunately have been greatly reduced due to Covid19)/

More friendly and willing to meet new people and dogs. With COVID many people keep their dogs away from other dogs when they are out walking and Ezme loves other dogs so she misses out when people don't stop and let their dog meet her.

"we just moved in Aug 2020 and Lucy is not used to indicating when she has to go to the bathroom.  If she needs to go to the bathroom in the middle of the night, we find that she'll go in our bathroom or by the door.  She not only knows she did something wrong but she acts almost disappointed in herself for having an accident.  We have to make sure and sit with her to tell her ""its ok and that accidents happen""  like a kid!!!  she's so smart"

I think her sight and hearing has decreased slightly so I am not sure it is truly cognitive, but more of a struggle processing life with less sensory input. A good question to add to this study would be - Has your dog become more vocal as I have found that as my dogs lose hearing, they actually bark more.
Yoda is becoming much more focused on food.
Emma learns very quickly. She notices and remembers events easily.
she's a little clumsier, tripping on the stairs coming in from outside, a little, but more than before.

Peggy is only 8.5 months old, so her thinking and information processing has improved dramatically over the past 6 months. Her vocabulary is growing rapidly. She has made great strides with her attention span and focus. Her impulse control has improved a lot, too.
No real changes from 6 months ago
New puppy after losing an elder dog. Not adjusting as well as hoped. Tolerates the new dog, but does not play or otherwise interact.
She may have slowed down. However we are working from home full time.  So she gets some playtime during the day which she previously didn't have.
I have Moose only 6 months and nothing changed , all the same
He has begun to hesitate to jump up on the couch. He acts like he is afraid he might not make it. He walks up, backs up and then takes a running start. Occasionally he just aborts his attempt.

He licks himself a lot! Hind legs definitely are bothering him. He struggles going up and down steps. He paces a lot, just wines to go back upstairs to our bedroom to go to sleep even though he has a bed downstairs also.

To clarify about my dog not recognizing things or people...it is pretty rare and, I believe, usually in low light/changing light settings.  Her hearing is excellent, and if she hears a dog bark she will run to the window barking back....although the barking is coming from the tv.
He gets grumpier with young dogs as time goes on. I don't think he would really hurt them but he puts them in their place a lot.
Appears to want to eat more food. Always wanting food.
she is satisfied with less walking (45 minutes instead of an hour) and she is walking in general slightly slower
When she seems annoyed wirth me, she will sleep in her kennel and not on my bed.  Although someyimes I suspect failure to make the bed is because she is stiff or sore from chasing squirrils.

I think the pandemic / being at home more has affected the pets as well as the humans. There are times when Edgar seems unnecessarily anxious or cranky. Also, in 2020, I have had to be away from home for weeks at a time because my dad was sick and died on August 9th. So 2020 has been a year unlike any other for us . . . and for all kinds of reasons.

Yes - I have noticed that after he comes in from his first morning pee - I always feed him - he knows that. But lately he has been going to the wrong place for his food and then back tracking, maybe going in one other direction, then finally gets to the right place - we have had the exact same routine for years...just recently he started doing this

I've been able to begin to reduce the amount of Prozac he gets and his behavior remains within acceptable limits for anxiety, which is mainly excessive self-licking.  Instead of two pills daily, I've gotten him down to one pill nightly and in the morning, only one pill 3 days a week.  My goal is to get him down to only one pill daily.

6 months ago I went to work every day and only suspected Chiana snoozed all day. Since covid-19, I work at home and know for certain she sleeps all day. Her hearing seems to either be failing or she is choosing to ignore me more often. She does have an extraordinary sense of the clock.
Everything is normal about the old guy: cognitive,  eyesight, hearing, teeth -- all more like a dog 6 years younger than he is

"Our dog seems to forget where he last saw ""his dad."" So he spends time looking for him. We partially attribute this to his hearing loss. Now he needs to see people to feel secure. Where as before he knew where everyone was due to hearing them. It's the same with dropped food. He used to hear where it landed and then sniff it out. Now if we point it out it saves him from searching around."

"After the lockdown happened Boomer was really sad because he couldn't hang out with his ""girlfriends"". He does see them occasionally now with safety protocols in place. But, he gets really sad when he doesn't see them. Normally we will see them on an afternoon walk and if that doesn't happen for a couple of days, he does act kind of blue. "
No, he has stayed the same.

"Sunny's vocabulary has expanded in the last 6 months. He now understands ""No swimming today,"" ""This is garlic,"" ""Can you see...?"" (when looking at FaceTime to see our grandchildren or favorite friends), ""Waterpick?,"" ""Hairdryer?,"" and lots of other fun stuff.   Sunny has also become much more protective of the house and will sound the alarm if there is a knock at the door or the doorbell rings."
He will fetch a toy that I throw a short distance from him once, but then won't do it again, as he always did before.
Tucker seems relatively unchanged over these last six months.

My dog's cataracts and hearing have gotten much worse. She cannot see well at all, and her hearing is very bad. She cannot find crumbs from her kibble and biscuits that she drops on the floor. She is hungrier than ever however!
He is reluctant to come in the house. Granted, he is an outdoor dog, but he used to love to be invited in.
He's been spending more time running free in the woods (with supervision but off leash) and has become more attuned to scents and sounds of animals
She has not taken the lack, due to COVID,  of regular interaction with people outside the household well.  She has just returned to her normal happy friendly self.
Dunkin has been stable for the past 6 months
She is more particular when entering the car she only wants to enter on one particular side of the vehicle to jump up into her seat.
She seems more affectionate, not always, but enough that I noticed.

"He's definitely pooping in places he never pooped before (indoors.) In the last six months he is now blind in one eye and his hearing is so bad I have to basically tap him on the shoulder to get his attention. That could be confused with inattention or ""zoning out"" but he just can't hear me. Once I get his attention he acts normally."
We've moved in with someone else and their dogs, and I've changed jobs so she can sometimes come in with me. She sees to be more socially active and mentally/physically worn out at the end of the day
Never had any geriatric behavior and has none now

She has started barking aggressively at other dogs when on leash but plays and gets along well with other dogs when off leash at the dog park. Also, she has become a hunter and has killed possums in the back yard and goes crazy when she sees rabbits in the park but is on leash so she can't get them.

Instead of lying in the family room with us after dinner, she goes upstairs to the bedroom until it's time to get a treat and go outside before we all go to bed. This started about 8 or 9 months ago on a sometimes basis, but now is nightly. In our vacation home, she does not do that. She stays with us until she goes outside and one or both of us goes to bed.

In the Covid-19 world, DanDan's life has changed completely.  He does pet therapy and was out and about doing his thing 3-4 days a week.  With Covid, that went down to 1 day a week.  When he had to stay at home and not see a lot of people, he seemed depressed.  Same amount of physical activity, but not people oriented. I think most of his issues are behavioral, not cognitive.  He stares at me and ignores me when I ask him to come in the door.   I have since made an effort to be sure I could take him with me several days a week, even if it is only to sit in the car while I run errands. He is much happier when he can go into a store, sit in a cart and greet people.  Now when I ask him to come in,  if he sees his leash he gets excited--he still makes a beeline for the car every time I go out the door (no leash required for him to be outside).
With the addition of a new puppy, Primadonna has been less faithful with recalls -- she comes when she feels like it rather than right away.
Sue is 2.5 years old and competes in agility, obedience and Rally.  We have started up trialing somewhat after CoViD and she is so happy to be out and about.

I am pregnant, and Orzo has developed more protective behavior over me than he has in the past. He tries to separate my husband and I if we hug which is new behavior since becoming pregnant. He also (non aggressively), just walks in between me and other dogs at a dog park.
she has become more vocal - talking to me more than before.  don't know why but just started to moan and talk more.
Less active and less interested in playing with toys
I have not observed or noticed any cognitive or behavioral changes, except being more demanding for our attention.
He is less aggressive with other dogs and more social with dogs and people.

"He has never had separation anxiety before, but a new behavior has emerged in the last 6 months. Now Mac feels he needs to be in the same room with us at all times. Even if we just get up to go into another room for a minute to grab something and come back, he has to get up and walk with us. He's always been very good at the ""stay"" command, but he completely ignores it now when we try to tell him to stay when we know we will be out of the room for just a quick minute. He still has to follow us regardless."
Ruby is in the process of losing her sight which affects some of these issues. She lost one eye to glaucoma 3 years ago and the remaining eye has a cataract.
Oberon has recognized that puppies need more gentle treatment than adult dogs.
Max is 19 months and is getting smarter every day.  He understands and does things that have not really been taught to him, like getting a toy when asked... :)
Nothing at this time . Three months ago we moved and she is settling into a new routine with different smells and sounds .
I think she has been about the same (very active, very mentally sharp) over the last six months.

I feel that Vinnie is as there cognitively as he ever was. Except for when he had his Vestibular episode in the spring of 2020. He's back to his normal self. He didn't take his cognitive medication during that time and has restarted it this November.

Chaco has had some serious physical health issues (trachea, lungs, food allergy) in the last five months.  I think he is slightly more anxious when we drive up to the Vet's office so he is processing information and learning from his experiences.
My dog seems much happier, as there is a human at home at all times, as my husband is working from home. He doesn't need to be kenneled up when we are both gone. Side benefit of COVID, I guess

I have not really noticed any major differences as far as cognitive changes. He is only a year old, so I guess most notably, I've seen him respond better to commands. He seems more relaxed on walks and to be paying better attention to both my voice and body language. He also seems less excited by the sight of other dogs on walks; where he used to want to run over and meet every one that we passed, he now seems much more ambivalent.
Oliver needs more encouragement to go up and down the steps in our split-level house. It's probably more about his rheumatism and weakening hind end than it is about mental processing.

"Sadie is <2 years old and has lived with me for approximately 18 mos.  She still has puppy behaviors and has not learned to obey all commands.  She is calmer than 6 mos. ago and more consistently responds to ""Down.""  She knows to sit, stay, come and lay down but does not stay well.  Her biggest not learned behavior is pulling while walking.  She is very difficult in this regard but much improved over when I first got her.    She is very demanding when wanting attention, using her large foot to request her needs, but she no longer bashes me with her head when wanting attention.  The pawing is something we are working on removing.  She does 'down' better than she did 6 months ago but will jump when I return home or someone visits.  She uses little nips when attention-getting or during loving. Loud whining is another attention-getting behavior we are working on eliminating.  Sadie was beaten with a newspaper by her previous owner.  As a result, she is head shy which we are working on.  There has been some improvement but it requires more work.  Sadie does not chew furniture or clothing.  She appears not to experience separation anxiety possibly because she has a dog companion.   She is a reasonably intelligent dog but hard-headed.  Her most aggravating behavior is that she is not fully house trained and will urinate and poop right near the open back door on occasion.  She will ask to go outside and receives reinforcement going out and returning but the house issues persist and are not understandable and I don't know how to break her of them."
Sometimes has more trouble jumping up into the car or on the bed, although that seems to be better recently.

Since I've been home the last 9 months due to furlough, I've noticed how needy my dog is and how attached he is to me or it may be because I'm here to notice it? Maybe he always was. He is much more protective of me now, too. He has shifted his loyalties, which were 50/50 with my husband to 95/5 to me. Too bad! HA!
She is the same crazy girl

"He shows that he can keep learning language and changes the way he communicates his wants with us.  For example, he started gently scratching our leg and leading/signaling that he wants us to do something for him, perhaps feed him or let him out.  He has also devised a way to respond to our request of him if he is hungry (makes a broad ""lick of the chops"") or if he is thirsty (a quick little extension of the tongue out front.)  He can also catch on to new games that we may try to play with him."
I've started using a lot more interactive feeding toys with her in the past few months, and she gets quicker and quicker at figuring them out!

Gibson seems slightly more stubborn, mainly as evidenced by not coming immediately on command (e.g., to go outside; to come down the stairs to eat; to come over to us on the couch when we want to pet him, etc.).
He is much better on the leash and riding in the car.
She has always wanted to be around us but now it is even more so. Likes to lie right at our feet.
Ted is now 2 and a half years old and his reasoning skills seem to be improved.  He seems to have more understanding of actions and consequences.
Lucy looks to me before trying something
Tucker only has one eye, and is going blind in that eye, so I attribute most of the issues in this survey to that.
Chester has some nerve damage to his right eye caused by chronic ear infections, his pupil is permanently dilated so he has some trouble finding treats when tossed to him.
Micky is as sharp as he has always been
No, I have not seen any behavior changes in my dog in the last 6 months
Just not hearing as well as before, I use more hand jestures with her now.
We got a cat, so Mollie is more active, alert, and territorial. They play together but they also compete.

As a result of Covid-19 we've been working from home full time so Margot's routine shifted dramatically in March (about 8 months ago). She's become more engaged with us and more vocal about requesting attention, to play, etc. She's more curious about our food and seems more interested in being around us. She's gotten smarter with a lot of games, like she's learned to toss her ball to us with more force when she's playing fetch or digs the ball out of corners or from behind furniture more easily.

My dog has shown no changes in thinking or info processing, in fact she has become more active as I recently purchased a pup and they actively play in the house and back yard. I often ask my grandkids to walk her, which she truly enjoys.
She has had back problems and was put on medical rest by her neurologist so hasn't been active bc of that. Still playful despite the medicine though.
She has lost her sight and her hearing is reduced.

He is more affectionate. He comprehension is improving and he can now  be given srveral commands together and follow them correctly.  He has completely learned our daily  routine  and habits.  We have had several very smart dogs, but we both believe he is the smartest.  His nature to please is enormous.  For some strange reason, he is absolutely not a watchdog.  He will bark at nothing, but when someone comes to the door. He never barks.

Neville was diagnosed with primary epilepsy in early fall.  In the summer, he was hiding in the yard and would avoid busy life.  He was sometime slow on walks as well.  Now that he is on medication, we he does not hide, he is much more social and asks for attention.  He is also more alert.
If anything, his cognitive function seems sharper since he and I stated to take lecithin with sage.
Sometimes she will shake or tremble and I'm not sure if it's anxiety or stress. Often it happens when I feed her. Sometimes she won't eat unless I hand feed her
No, she seems the same mentally as she was as a puppy.

I'm a bit worried that my working from home during the pandemic will lead to an increase in his anxiety when I return to the office whenever this is over. To try & remedy it, I've been disappearing for a couple of hours each day so he's on his own for a while.
At 3.5, she's finally able to focus well enough to excel at agility, which she loves.

Feel the behavior of staring at the floor might have been caused by medication. He was recently on a short course of prednisone. Have not noticed the behavior since the med ended. The behavior started right around the time he was on the med.

Sydney seems more aware.  In August we doubled the gabapentin and  stopped the Tramadol.  In September we added Amandtadine.  It seems that this combo of pain meds is keeping her more comfortable and less hazy.

"Abby often waits sitting on a lamp table in front of large windows for the mailman to arrive. She is also well aware of the UPS truck if it comes up the hill.  Abby is very active and motivated by these two trucks to run and will chase if she has gotten out. On several predawn visits to the backyard she has spotted rodents in various areas of the yard. Now she checks each one of those areas every time she goes out. She is focused on those four places.  We adopted this animal after she had produced five litters of puppies for a breeder. She was never trained and was ""a crate dog"". She has several habits that are strange to me. 1. She marks, often in a house with another dog so she must wear pants when we visit  2. She lifts her leg to urinate almost every time she pees.  Abby was never treated unkindly or abused. She is extremely social and loving. We do not have any cages in our home. We have noticed that she always seeks a quiet dark room for sleep. "
We added a chihuahua puppy to our household in August who Badger plays with all day.

My dog has been a bit more deliberate in his decision making when outside.  By this, I mean that when determining which way he wants to go or whether to stay or leave a location, he will often sit or stand still for a minute and - literally -  turn his head back and forth between two directions before picking which direction he will move in.

Prior to the March COVID shutdown, Stella seemed to be showing more signs of slowing down and decline. She sometimes had difficulty jumping up on the couch or bed and was sleeping more. Since we are now home with her most of the time and walk with the dogs for 30-40 minutes or more each day, she seems to have rejuvenated. She is more alert, energetic and coordinated than she was at the beginning of the year.
No, none that I can think of.
understands more commands an will obey them sooner

He's pausing more before using people or doggie stairs/ramp.  When I gesture for him, he delays to see if I'm going to the kitchen or downstairs to take him outside and moves with varying speed.  He cleans his sister's ears and eyes less often - he starts but then seems to get distracted and moves away.

He's more tolerant of less exercise. 6 months ago if he didn't get 2 miles he was a terror all night. Now he's okay with a mile. It may be that he is more active the rest of the day with me being home though.

Because I broke my hip, I can not take Dylan out. He eagerly waits for his Dog walkers and seems to know what time they come. He then goes to the front door and waits. He loves to go out for his walk with them. There are three walkers who take turns.
Just wanted to note, that Ziggy has trouble finding food on the floor because he has a great deal of hair covering his eyes and impeding his vision, not because of any cognitive issues.
She has figured out how to open doors with latches so we now have to lock the storm doors.
No changes in her thinking or information processing.
My dog's hearing has declined, so I've started using hand signals to communicate with her.  She has picked this up very quickly--right away seemed to understand what the different hand signals meant.
No. He wants to go in the car more often.  He used to seem afraid (whining once we drove out of our neighborhood) but now begs to go with us every time we leave.

I have noticed that she will go to the opposite/wrong side of the door to enter after returning from our walks. Also she forgets about the screen door and will not move back and just stands there instead of moving back like she used to do when I open the screen.
While in the house, Serenity barks more when she hears people outside or sees them out the window.
In the past 6 months, Rissi has developed a habit of sitting on a hill in our yard to sit and wait for deer to come through to chase. This patience is new from 6 months ago.

I do want to share something on the orginal questions.  We were asked if Clem ever guards his food, shows aggression when he is eating, etc.  He is a very polite dog when eating in the house.  When we are out tracking and he gets some critter in his mouth he becomes somewhat aggressive and it takes quite a bit of work to take it from him.
We go on more walks since I'm working at home. He barks less at other people while we are walking.
She just turned 1yr old so she experienced what I think are normal puppy developmental changes
"It seems Halle has become more affectionate. She mostly wants to be in the same room with me and if I don't pay attention to her she ""paws"" me. Not a complaint, I love that she is this way!"
He learns quickly and obeys regularly.  He is a therapy dog.
He's the same energetic and engaging dog. Always willing to please especially if you have a treat or ball. Happy Thanksgiving! Kathy & Bullet

Seems to be more playful after getting high blood pressure under control at beginning of 2020. May be related to Syringomyelia, which has not been verified by CAT scan, but is more common in Cavalier King Charles Spaniels.
None. She's a smart girl that also knows when she wants to be pet or not, which makes me sad sometimes haha
Understanding direction and commands.  Acknowledges more from us

The tempature definitely determines how active Loretta is each day.  She doesn't not like the sun or heat so in the Summer she is less active than when the months are cooler.  We live in North Florida.

"No changes.  We decided to get Jill a baby ""sister"", Kiera, from the  same breeder just before her 2nd birthday (Jill's grandfather is Kiera's father).  We saw a great change at that time, with Jill acting more like a puppy and being much more active with a constant canine companion.  The younger dog gets very upset if Jill is not around - she screams if Jill needs to leave to go somewhere with my husband or me, even if the other parent remains with her."
No.  My dog is less active because I went back to work and six months ago I was home because of Covid.
She does not want to walk as far as we used to but this could also be because we moved from the coast of NC to the mountains 6 months ago where there are more hills and the altitude is different.
Brings me my dirty socks from the previous day when getting dressed in the morning.

He has become more communicative (barking) when he is lonely, wants to be let out to urinate, wants to be let in after being outside to sun himself on the lawn, or play with his tennis ball, or to urinate or defecate. He has become much more communicative about wanting affection such as putting his head under my arm to indicate he wants to be petted. He has also become very energetic (he bounces on his forelegs even though he has arthritis) when I take the leash /harness out of the closet. So, his thinking processes seem to have become more advanced. He is approximately 12 years old and was an owner surrender; he has been our dog since we adopted him ten years ago, when he was estimated to be 2-3 years old by the veterinarian at the animal shelter.

talk about Pavlov's dogs!  we have a ring, and every time Alexa speaks, she barks and runs to the door.  I also knock on the window to get squirrels off of my bird feeders, (they have their own feeders)!  she now knows there is a squirrel outside.
Slightly decrease in hearing and sight

Not really. It's hard to believe that he was diagnosed with lung cancer in Aug. He has been hacking in the mornings for over a year so not much has changed yet. I am really surprised. Tonight he got happy with the cold weather and bounced and ran!

She is the same.  But, it should be noted that I have been working from home and with her FT since the end of March.  Prior to that time, I worked outside the home three days per week.  Her thinking or information processing has been consistent.
No changes. He's maintaining like he was much younger.
None at all. The questions in this exercise are a little tilted. She has never shown ANY of these activities. Not now and not 6 months ago
Haven't seen any cognitive issues with Quest at all
If anything it has increased as I have been home more and have worked with her more.
Taiga actually seems much more attached to us. He likes to follow us around our apartment and be near us at all times. He seems to not enjoy being left alone as much as he used to
As Molly has matured, been trained and socialized more; she shows less over-excitability, and is able to give more appropriate responses when meeting people or dogs, and in unfamiliar situations.
She's more anxious.  She's slept through the night since she was a puppy, but in the last month she's begun waking up in the night, shaking and drooling with fear.
Greta is deaf, but was trained to understand hand signals when she was young. She also has problems seeing at night. We shine a flashlight for when she goes out a night

I took him to a dentist, who scanned his head and found an abscessed tooth.  Two teeth were pulled, and he wanted to pull more, later.  That did not stop the sneezing.  I took him to a specialist, who wanted 3K to take more detailed pictures, samples, etc.  I'd already paid out 3k and had no further funds available.  I brought him home, and one day noticed the health food store had some Now Pets Animal Allergy pills.  I gave 1/2 pill once per day.  This went on for a long time, and one day I realized he wasn't sneezing.  I took him off the pills, and his nose started running, so I have kept him on them, since. I gave Mikie Rimadyl 25 mg sparingly for the past two years maybe. He was doing well walking happily for a few days at a time, with his tail curled up. Then as I gave him the meds, he began to have less good days and would drag hind toes. I called the vet & we switched to Deramaxx 12 mg day. Again, I used it sparingly and he did appear to have more good days walking without dragging toes. I began to notice he gradually struggled sitting down and had an awkward resting style and his body would shake after he was given the Meds. I spoke to the vet and we cut the Deramaxx in half  in addition to giving him Gabapentin 50 mg 1/2 tablet twice day. I don't know if it's coincidence or it's a reaction to meds, but Mikie, in past three weeks, walks like he's drunk. We have wood floors in many areas and his hind legs slide all over. Now he struggles using his upper body to lift lower. He is over 18 years and this could be an indication of the end but he eats his kidney care dog food, doesn't have accidents unless someone forgets to let him out in AM. He does, however, follow me everywhere and cries when he can't find me. He often needs help going up stairs and sometimes down- depends on time of day. I'm wondering too if his vision got worse. nothing has changed over the last 6 months

in the last 6 months, sometimes, she does not want to jump down from furniture. She whines - which tells us she needs help. She is scared sometimes  I think. Our work schedules have changes drastically since the coronavirus. We are both essential workers. She seems to understand that her hearing is not as it was.... I say this because always in the past she did not allow our other dog ( Jude 11years August 2020) to bark at the door if the doorbell rang. That job was hers and hers alone. They worked that out all on their own- peacefully.  I do wonder if you are  missing out by only accepting 1 dog per household in your study. She used to sit on my lap whenever I was home and sitting, and while I am working she is not able to do that.  It was very stressful for her for a couple of days until I ordered a new dog bed and stairs.  I had to move another chair into my office right next to me, put the dog bed up on it, and then the stairs leading to the bed.  This allowed her to sit right up next to me.  She has since relaxed and we have gotten rid of the crazy contraption.  She is now able to lay under or around my desk with the other dogs without any stress.  Me being home has actually resulted in her being more independent.  I will eventually have to go back to the office, and I am curious to see how she reacts when that happens.

These medications made him violently ill to where I had to take him to the ER for 24 hrs.  We did not give him a second dose of chemo and tapered him off of all Prednizone.  He has more energy and life than he had before.  Has gained back the 4 pounds he lost and is a very happy and active dog now after 3 months.

Murphy is continually learning tasks. The first 15 months of his life with the previous owner he didn't even know his name or any commands. I adopted him when he was 15 months old. It took patience and two months to get him to relax and settle down to begin any real communication. The previous owner only gave him water with his morning meal then took it away for the rest of the day. My first success was Murphy understanding he would ALWAYS have water. This promise was the breakthrough to Murphy totally trusting me. My other dog Petey helped Murphy to learn many basic communications. Petey (miniature Doxy) is a trained service dog and is 10 years old.    Murphy has learned to pickup objects I drop, basic commands and makes eye contact when I am talking to him. He still has a way to go due to his traumatic beginnings with the other owner.   We continue to train daily. It has been slower with Murphy than any other dog I have trained. Patience is key.

Mav is beginning to get up at night and walk around the house....he goes to the TV area and possibly looks for any food...we believe....then he comes back to bed....sometimes he pushes on the bed for us to get up and let him out, but when out, he does not pee like he really needed to go.....not sure what that is....Still, by the minute can let you know when it is feeding time....

No. Surprisingly, she turns 15 next week and still loves to learn new tricks. I recently taught her to open the baby gate so she can go thru in an emergency. Reading this survey reminded me of the behaviors I've seen in my other dogs who weren't even as old as Aquila and I am so grateful for her good health.

He can be a reactive dog, strangers are not his thing. He used to forget he knew some of my daughters' friends and would be reactive when they would come over. My daughter and her boyfriend live a few hundred miles away and visit every few months. He has accepted the boyfriend and does not bark or try to nip at him, he runs up to him for attention without waiting (spontaneously), he always remembers my daughter (with love).

Our senior girl crossed the rainbow bridge in April, and we adopted a year and a half girl in August and she has really brought out an amazing side of him. He is finally the older dog and has helped with her training and she has helped him be more fun and not so serious. He is still serious but when you have a goofy pup who will not be denied being serious is hard sometimes. Our old girl was mostly blind and so sadly he was not able to play and roughhouse the way he wanted to, and now he can. :)
In the past six months, we have adopted a second dog, a puppy.

Bodhi has never been an affection-focused dog.  He was really indifferent to us as a puppy but now at 1-1/2 (almost 2) will wag his tail and run to us when we walk into a room or when we've been away.

Sadie is a very active and happy dog however in general she is a bit calmer in general than she was 6 months  ago but still likes to play with other dogs. For example,  I dog sit 2 other dogs about once a month for several days and one is a 6 month old Great Dane puppy.  When she comes over to stay, Sadie plays a lot with her rather than the other dog who is a smaller calmer  8 year old male mixed breed.
She has slowed down and does not instantly partake in behaviors from her previous life on a horse farm. Her guarding and prey instinct are still quite high.

My daughter has a puppy, he's now 11 months but quit larger than Nessarose.  In the beginning she tolerated him and even played sometimes.  Now he's 5x's larger than her so she hides most of the time when he's at the house which has also made her gain a lot of weight.
She can s actually about the same . Some things she's better somethings she's declined.
Follows commands, sit, wait, down, ball, come. Makes eye contact, shows listening head tilt etc.
Something to clarify on the walking away when being petted - he still shies away from anyone outside of our immediate family petting him.

Ajax had 6 weeks of diarrhea but we finally cured it with a powder the vet gave us.  His problem is that he is unstable on his back legs.  The vet thinks it's neurological versus physical.  I think it's both.  He now has trouble getting up but can walk around once he does.  He is a Border Collie and probably the smartest dog I've ever seen.  Our vet says he is very determined to stay alive and he has good blood work.  He is 15.  The biggest problem is he gets frantic around 2 in the afternoon but will sleep most of the day before that.  Then he walks in circles around tables, paces back and forth, and keeps stepping in front or back of me and my husband so he can touch us.   He had vestibular disease a few years ago that he recovered from but I think he still is unsteady from that.  He can remain frantic for about 4 hours.  When we take him upstairs we are giving him something so he will sleep through the night or he would keep waking us up.  The thought of losing this dog is killing us but he knows he's not what he used to be and I think that's what's bothering him, along with normal aging.
Six months ago it was 100�� here so my dog was not very active now it averages about 70�� and he loves it
No real cognitive changes, but some physical changes, like decreasing mobility, difficulty rising, etc.
none her cognitive functioning is excellent
He will sometimes stare off in the distance.
He seems to understand more verbal communication and has continued to develop unique barks for activities he wants to do.

Diezel has become much more mature. He's learning to not focus on other dogs treats or toys (since he has always believed all treats and toys are his) his training is coming along nicely.  He still thinks he's only 3 lbs...he's definitely not.  He understands his daily schedule and is well used to it. He's actually incredibly intelligent and understands quite a bit
He sense of object permanence seems more evolved
He has become more affectionate and separation anxiety prone, likely due to us being home due to the pandemic but nothing as far as cognition.

Her eyesight is compromised, so she is cautious in dark areas.  She refuses to go down one set of stairs (which are steep) and will only go down another (less steep) if coaxed with treats.  She has arthritis, and is probably in pain when she moves. It is harder for her to get up from a lying position and she has taken to barking when she is left alone in a room, rather than getting up to come join where people are.  We have placed yoga mats around on hardwood floors to improve her footing.  She seems to bark more often, and has always avoided letting strangers pet her without a lot of coaxing and reassurance first, but that is getting a bit worse. She seems happy and her usual friendly, and is very food motivated, but spends alot more time just lying around. When we walk her, she cannot go nearly as far without getting winded or slowing way down.  She seems to have increasing separation anxiety, but can also go long periods being calm and quiet. She sleeps through the night and has not trouble with her elimination, but is beginning to refuse to go outside without coaxing if it is raining.
Ren is an energetic joy, a lovable, affection and attention seeking little guy whose behavior hasn't changed at all in the past six months!
Gifford has exhibited more anxiety regarding sounds, inanimate objects, or 'strangers' (someone with hat or mask on) than he has exhibited more than 6 months ago.

He was briefly on Carprofen following an accident and that seemed to seriously change his thinking and information processing. He paced endlessly and was confused and very anxious. I cut the treatment short as he didn't seem to be in pain, but was struggling to get through the days, and he slowly went back to his normal self within about a week. That is the only major change I have seen to his thinking and information processing.

Romeo is definitely having changes with his vision and hearing. Finding food on the floor is extremely challenging for him. He also used to be great at catching treats in the air. We have stopped attempting it but the past few months they would hit him in the face or he would jump super early. When food is on the floor we have to guide him to where it is. He occasionally walks into walls, doors, tables, etc. Romeo is also having a decline in his hearing. Sometimes he won't hear someone coming until he see's them or until they get very close to him or touch him. Romeo occasionally has urinary incontinence in his sleep overnight.

She used to sleep on my bed all night, but since I adopted a second dog, Paisley gets off the bed when the other dog comes into the room and jumps onto the bed. Maybe she's relinquishing her power (although she's still the alpha). She's been happier with a companion; they bonded from the day he arrived; and she plays more and seems to keep up with him (although she has slightly less stamina). Changes: she has started licking the carpet and her bed. She only urinated in the house once, and that's likely because I didn't open the dog door on time.
No.  He's awesome, even if he is (guess) about 11 years old.

We've only had her a year (a re-homed senior) and she has learned very well what buttons to push to get her way; feels safe to be very stubborn or balk. She's got us wrapped around her paws. No obvious decline in any area.

Sambuca has recovered from vestibular in the last six months.  I notice that she has become more active; playing a couple minutes a day with our three year old mini schnauzer.  She enjoys her morning walk of about three-quarters of a mile and only experiences balance problems when the younger dog runs into her during play.

He is maturing and going through what I would consider adolescence so sometimes he is exerting more of his independence and is a little more bold about doing things that I might not like him to do...like not coming right away when called or eating things I would rather be didn't like sticks or horse poop!
She is the same. She runs and plays with other dogs in the home and is very happy and active. Darla is a fast runner too!
No, he is pretty much the same as 6 months ago.
Rascal is full of life! Loves to ride anything that rolls! Ride in wheel barrow, ride on bicycle, stationary bike, riding mower, auto rides. He is a happy camper!
"Nibbles understands many more commands than 6 months ago.  One in particular is, ""go find your ball.""  She takes off like a rocket to the spot her balls are kept and brings one to me."

One of our older dogs seriously hurt his back while playing with Tulip.  We have been showing him more attention and affection than usual and Tulip senses this. We have not noticed any changes.
Not at all. Or at least nothing that has been obvious or readily apparent

she sleeps more, eats less and is pickier than previously

Just maturing from puppy to adult.
she doesn't go after squirrels quite as aggressively  as before; still goes after golf carts, though

None, Rowena is a very happy and healthy girl.

he has learned more words and commands but does not always obey

Well, the last 6 months have been during the COVID pandemic, so my husband, my daughter and I have been home pretty much all day, every day. Became deaf and blind in last 6 months

She took us to each one so we could collect them all from the ground before the rest of the dogs could get to them and hurt them.  "

no.  he acts like a puppy most of the time

She's just a little over a year old so she hasn't changed too much
behaves the same as 6 months ago

I think Panda is maturing and becoming more and more attentive and conscious of me and my emotions. As far as I'm concerned, none of the small changes I see in him are unexpected or troublesome.  He continues to be the love of my life.

"Being mostly border collie, my dog has always exhibited extreme intelligence and a desire to learn more and to communicate with me. Mia's willingness to learn seems to actually be increasing as she sometimes acts ""bored"" with familiar toys and activities. It appears that she needs more stimulation as she ages. She also has a lot of energy that at times I have a hard time keeping up with. That said, Mia is still only 3-4 years old, so she is still in her ""younger"" years. Maybe this will change as she ages. "

My dog seems unusually smart. He is always monitoring what's going on.   When he was young, I did not put him in any crate. Some people leave their puppies in crates for long hours while they are at work, but I did not do this. In fact, I hired puppy sitters while I was at work to come for 4 hours every day and play with the dogs (Nikki and his brother).  I think this helped their brain development.  In humans, if you would leave your child without stimulation for hours every day, it would be very harmful for their development.  I suspect this is the same for dogs.    My dogs seem smart and aware, which I think is partly because of the stimulation they received.
Slim's vocabulary seems to be bigger. He understands more words than 6 months ago. He also seems to be communicating with us in a logical way.

I have worked with Gus since we first got him 5 1/2 years ago. On walks especially, he would bark at strange dogs. If I see the dog first  and talk to him, he will ALMOST NEVER, bark at the other dog. I have noticed that he is (human interpretation of dog behavior) proud of when he can have the freedom to be off leash on sidewalks. He takes pride (my interpretation) in walking down the sidewalk knowing that if he doesn't behave as expected, his punishment will be to be put back on the leash. That is not a back thing, but he loves the trust I show in him.  We live in the suburbs so I can see far enough away if another dog that he doesn't know is coming to put him back on the leash to help him until we find out if he can say hi to the other dog.
I feel that Franklin is very intuitive.  He quickly picks up on cues (bath prepping, food prepping, me leaving)

He's interested in the different assortment of outdoor wildlife we have in Hawaii. (Ie. Lizards, birds, toads, and frogs) which are very different from those he observed in Arizona (Ie. Squirrels, Owls, Hawks)
More anxious. Will lie down in corners. Barks more
Peanut has become more vocal and more headstrong over the last 6 months.

"I find Daisy more in tuned to what we are saying. Like if I say, ""In a bit I am going to take the dogs walking."" she will lift her head and wag her tail. I have not gotten out of my chair or made any moves to go. She seems to understand more words that she has heard before.  Daisy has had a habit since she was a puppy where she scratches her ear or neck incessantly, either side. She seems to only do this when she is not otherwise occupied. We often wondered was she feeling like she had to go potty or discomfort. I had her checked at the vet and there are not ear issues. We were prescribed an ear wash and that was of no help. Her ears are clean and groomer clears the inner hair.  Before she settles in to sleep she scratches for a while. I'll pull her close, tell her ""No scratch"", try to soothe her by petting her, but she needs to do this for a few minutes before settling down. She will wake through the night and scratch as well. I often take her out for a quick potty break and she settles back in bed. I wonder why she does this. Communicating to us? "

Chez is going on ten years old, the only difference I've noticed is physical, harder for him to get up from lAying down and he needs less exercise, and gets sore if he over exerts himself such as running a long ways or keeping up with younger dogs all day.

Cocoa chooses not to sleep with me anymore  He is very anxious.   Sleeps mostly in the bathtub  And will come to my bed around 6 each morning  Albeit very anxious for a few minutes when I put Him up with me.
Fairly often, while inside, he'll start barking at a wall or the ceiling, as if he is hearing something. This is definitely a new behavior.

Tess loves to be outside.  She continues to ask to go out in the yard, but I have noticed she is staying on the patio more than usual.  If I go outside and work in the flowerbeds or sit and read, then she will jump up and explore the yard, digging holes, chasing bugs and being her usual self.  it seems like she is reluctant to leave the patio if I am not nearby.

"Bodhi has learned a lot over the last 6 months, including but not limited to, not chewing on the couch. He is currently learning to leave the Christmas Tree ornaments on the tree and learning not to chew on his sweater, coat, and jam jams that are needed to keep him warm on chilly Missouri nights. The only real change in his behavior that is ""new"" is he has gotten into the habit of preferring to chew on his ear when he is sleepy over his once favored toy/bone. He has, on occasion, even been seen carrying is ear around with him as he once did his coveted toy/bone. He does, however, still love his toy/bone, but relies less on them and more on his ear. "
He's more curious, smarter, more confident.
This past summer Napa learned much more about obeying commands and remaining close by us outdoors while off leash.

He has been going to bed in the evening earlier. He will sit in front of us and stare at us. My husband will carry him to our bed and put him on his blanket. That usually happens around 8:30pm. If we haven't come to bed by 10 or so, he will come out  dragging his blanket and stare at us again!

"She seems to be quicker learning behavior. For example, she has struggled with ""stay"" or ""wait"" in the past, but over the past 6 months she has easily mastered the command. Physically she has tripped going upstairs twice. I don't see any cognitive changes.
I've given him time to play with the 'Trixie' puzzles - he enjoys them and has figured out how to 'solve' some of the challenges.
He is a happy dog who knows all our family and friends by name. When we say we're going to see them, he gets excited because he know where we are going.

Sometimes she can't find me and I hear her going from room to room looking for me.  She was never like this before.  She also has been very stubborn with me when I call her to come here when we are outside or when I try to pull her away from something on walks ....like a stubborn teenager.  She seems to be more stubborn but yet needy all at the same time.

Sometimes he'll wait by the back door or the screen door, waiting for me to open it, even though he has a dog door. He seems a bit 'spacier,' although I can't quite put my finger on specifics. I have brought this up to my vet, but she can't find anything abnormal on exam.
she is very slightly less excitable.  she is very slightly more apt to process(take action) a command.
- A little more reactive to strange dogs when out on leash - More fearful of loud noises - fireworks, etc. - More fearful of going to the vet
No changes, he does seem grumpier as he gets older but he is a chihuahua who just doesn't like a lot of people.

Learning more commands and attention span slightly longer.

He has some trouble processing the entryway coming in from bright light; less of a problem at night or darker days. Very picky about food now. Didn't used to be.

We've been doing Nose Work training in the last six months, so he's actually been learning new things and increased his activity and training in this area. We also competed at a Nose Work Trial on October 31, 2020.

At times (once a month) he appears to have a harder time recognize that it is my husband outside working in the yard or walking in to the living room, and he barks as if it was a stranger. As soon as he recognize that it's Glenn he stops.

Nothing she has her good days and her lazy days she is still pretty active for 12

Becoming slightly more affectionate with family.

After we all started working from home because of covid, he didn't want to leave the house as often, and went from 3 walks a day to usually only one.  He refused to go walking with our dog walker, who used to take him for a walk at midday every day.

Because of COVID I have been working at home thus have been able to observe him a lot more in the past 6 months then I ever have before, so it is difficult on some of the questions to know if it is really a change in the past 6 months or simply b/c I see his behaviors for much more of the day than I did previously.

she is probably more active because we are home full time!

I have not observed any changes so far in my dog's thinking or information processing.  He has remained the same throughout.

"Tessie is becoming much more inquisitive, maybe because during COVID she was being walked constantly and now since being back to work she spends much more time without human presence. When outside it is more of a ""sniff and taste"" battle. "

Rocky seems to be less frenetic over the course of the last 6 months. I can't tell if that's due to someone being home to let him out during the day or if he's getting older. Dog likes cold weather which is why he is more active now than six months ago.  His anxiety has increased. Need to hold water dish for him to drink and hand feed him his dinner for him to eat or he refuses, is afraid of the bowl. Very afraid of sounds (like his collar tapping the bowl).
She seems pretty much the same.

Calvin is a calm, attentive, human-loving dog. He isn't exhibiting any of the signs of aging mentioned above. That being said, he is not an active dog. His favorite thing to do is snuggle on the sofa next to his humans.

he seems smart enough just his ears and eyes

Buckeye was recently diagnosed with having some seizure activity. She was put on a medicine and is having hardly no seizure activity now.
I notice that Cash is more restless, even at night when it's time to sleep.
No. In fact, he seems to be quite alert for a 15 year old pup. He starts barking for food and to go to bed at the same time each day and has always done that.

He has learned how to more effectively communicate that he has to go out to potty (without barking).
