He's had two strokes (one left lobe, one right lobe) and then followed by two seizures. Since the second stroke (two years ago) he's been unable to process the direction from which a sound is coming. I can walk up behind him and he hears me, gets excited, and runs off to find me when I'm standing right there. This hasn't changed much over the last six months, neither getting worse nor better.
"He has definitely become more vocal on expressing his needs/ wants. ""Talks"" to me to go out, get fed, to play, when his dog ""siblings"" have toys he wants."
He has become a bit more demanding of our time, and wants to go and be everywhere we are.  However, I attribute this to having moved to a different house.

"Note: ""active"" is more restricted due to pandemic.  Also, Chauncey has a very odd behavior:  When we first go out in our own yard if she is on a leash, she kind of ""goes crazy"" barking, and jerks to end of leash in all directions, and then tries to attack trees -- especially skinny ones.  She stops after 3 or 4 minutes, and then is quiet and pees/poops.  I cannot figure out about the tree attack. I have tried numerous variations of behavior modification.  It doesn't happen every single time, but I'd say at least 50% of the situation described, and especially for 1st morning walk and late night walk.  Oh, and she mostly does it to me. If someone else walks her she doesn't seem to bother with the trees.  PS we have a lot of trees!!"
Doesn't like to be petted as much as he used to. Doesn't respond as much when he's called.
she seems to be more of an observer than a participant these days
His back legs/rear of body function is less.  He often needs help getting up with us raising his back end to standing.  He sometimes comes back to the house with fecal matter in his fur.
none, he appears to have full cognitive abilities.

I believe his failure to recognize those he knows is a visual problem. For example, he will bark at a family member in the front yard while he is looking out the window, or he will bark at a family member coming into the house before recognizing who he's barking at.

She has had much more difficulty navigating stairs.  It seems mostly mental, as she does not appear to have any physical limitations.  She just struggles to manage getting her feet in the right spots, and has lost confidence in her ability to navigate stairs (for example, she now is cautious with smaller sets of steps where she was not before).
She is coughing more due to an enlarged heart that presses on her trachea. So she is on meds that makes her drowsey.

He doesn't respond as well to being called. We think that is because he has hearing loss.  He seems less inhibited about doing behaviors that he knows he's not supposed to do, like trying to get into the garbage or open cupboards. He will now do that even when we (his owners) are at home.
Our dog is now 8 months old, so she can walk much farther, so her activity on a daily basis is much higher.  her thinking is more mature as well, she is working on her obedience and learning games.

Apollo was always a very high energy dog, hard to calm down and just chill out. He will be 2 yrs old Inna couple weeks. 5 months ago we got a puppy. Maybe seems  a little harder of hearing and possibly seeing.....seems to take her just a bit longer to recognize us on sight, and to hear us when we get home.

Lily's sight has really started to go downhill which has resulted in her not being able to locate food on the floor as easily and not moving around as much. Physical changes to walking, only increase of difficulty. Under Vet care.
Much more food oriented and has become very verbal.
He has had no changes; still fully with it

In the past 6 months Bella has earned her Cooperative Care Certificates 1 & 2 from Deb Jones, psychologist, whose certificate program is coordinated by Fenzi TEAM titles online. Cooperative Care techniques have helped Bella become more tolerant of vet and grooming procedures.

After returning home from a week (day/night) at a doggy day care, he showed unusual aggressiveness toward a neighbor dog while chasing a thrown ball.  One-time incident; the dogs have been together since without a repeat of that behavior.

readjusts more often when resting as though it is somewhat painful to stay in a single position too long. Max is maturing nicely. He has settled down and has not wandered off to the neighbors in over a year. He comes when called and as always is so gentle with visiting dogs. We hope this next year will help him relax even more as he ages. What a wonderful and very beautiful breed.

I wonder if her eye sight is getting worse. She sometimes gets scared when I do a sudden movement and she seems to think I strike her when I am just moving my arm over her to get to something.  Or if I startled her and she gets scared and ducks with her body as she is not sure what to expect. This behavior is a new one I would say say as of the last 6-12 months.    She always was the more vocal of the two (her sibling sister also lives with me) but over the last year she has become very talkative.  Just to talk but also sometimes to demand something.  She also has this habit which is maybe 2 -3 years old where on walks she stops and wants to go a specific way or not want to walk anymore for what seems to be no reason.  It takes a lot of coaxing, redirecting, and sometimes just pulling on the leash to get her mentally out of that mindset and once she moved on it is usually fine.  Mechanically I have found that when she runs it is not the lean running machine run but more the gangly goofy run almost like when she was a little pup when she is off leash.
No changes in the past six months.
About two weeks ago, Angus suffered vestibular disease in his left ear. He's recovered-and is leaping curbs in a single bound, and is willing to take himself down the front steps.
no noticeable changes in the last 6 months
Bodhi seems more territorial of his dog friends. If he sees one out and another walks up he doesn't want the other one by the one he knows.

"No 6 month changes - but I will note he is blind so bumping into things, difficulty finding food, staring into space are pretty par for the course and therefore I think survey results are probably less applicable for him. No but I do want to point out that I had difficulty with figuring out how I would answer some of these questions bc bumping into things, for example, can sometimes be attributed to bad eyesight vs a change in behavior. Jasper is much more aware of his humans, myself and his Grandma (my Mom), and overall he is very submissive to The Littles, Roxie our 8yo Shitteranian and is very much a Mommy Dog to his new BFF, our 5 mo Shih Tzu puppy Winston. I broke my leg in January 2020, then COVID stay at home began in March 2020, so I have been at home with my dogs all day this entire year. I have found all my dogs more demanding of my attention. While they still sleep all day, they do in the room I am in. They follow me from room to room around the house. In addition, if I go 2-3 hours without paying attention to them, they demand my attention by standing up and pawing my arm or leg. Max has been especially demanding of this. Ultimately this is a good reminder that I need to get up and walk about (respite from Zoom).  When I first began staying at home, there was also greater jealously between my dogs, especially Max. Dylan (another of my dogs) would growl at Max when he got too close, then the two of them would get into a snarling dual. This has now faded as they have gotten used to me being at home all the time.
Since starting on galiprant, she is more curious about things, and more likely to act like she wants something from me

Herschel will bark when someone approaches the front door. Sometimes when I come in through the back door he will start barking at the front door and will continue to bark until I make contact with him.

she walks away from breakfast; picks up food and puts it on the floor but otherwise is unchanged. Her urinating is due to chronic renal insufficiency.
No changes--still on top of things!

trying to bite flies. that we cannot see.

At 17, she is more demanding of our attention. She quietly barks until we notice her and attend to her. Sometimes its to life her up onto a chair but often it is just hanging around.
not that I'm aware of. We just moved into a bigger space so he's much more active and playful!
He seems to be a little quicker to get annoyed but it's hard to tell. He is 12 so grumpy with old age I'm guessing
I think she processes commands a little more slowly.
No. Also his activity always goes down in the winter months. We live in Michigan and it get get really cold.

Our dog no longer wants to leave our driveway for a walk. She likes to ride in the car and is happy to go on a walk starting anywhere but our house.  She looks for people during the day and when she can't find them, she stays by the door until she sees someone again.
There are times when Bella seems to not know directionally where voices are coming from. Within the last 6 weeks, Bella has been diagnosed with mitral insufficiency or possible endocarditis.

Since I am now retired so I am able to spent more time with Collin McKinney Sherrard.  I realize that he has a sense of humor when we are playing and he realizes I one up'd him.  His eye mouth coordination if incredible catching anything while he is on the run, he loves super balls that bounce very high.  Even at 7 years of age he loves catching them on the first bounce.  Collin understands the English language on Lets play ball, lets eat dinner, lets go to bed, lets get a treat, lets go outside and get the newspaper.  He is still a very stubborn male Boxer
No, his cognitive state has remained unchanged throughout his life.

She has recently (over the past year or so) gained some weight and acquired a minor injury to her iliopsoas. She's on a diet and the muscle strain is healing nicely, so her activity level is returning back to what I would consider normal for her.
I can't think of any changes at all.
We lost our other dog in September so Zoey has been seemingly lost at first and seemed to be always looking for him.  but now she seems comfortable being the only dog.

My dog is now 13, she is slowing down but still active and ready to go for long walks, she is in good health (besides kidney disease).  I wish I could share a pic of her with you. She is a 40lb terrier. She is less curious and a little lazier but that is probably because of her age. Her brain seems as sharp as ever, her eyesight might be getting a little fuzzy.

I have noticed that in the last few months he will sometimes not get up to go greet my husband when he comes home from work.  At one time he always ran to pick up a toy and then carried the toy to say hello when my husband came home.  Now he will just lay on the couch and look at the door instead of getting up about 1 of every 10 times.

Willow seems to have lost her hearing or a large portion thereof over the last year, so her behavior has changed a bit in that she's not as tuned in to what's happening around her and misses a lot. Her cognitive abilities appear largely the same.

As of the past six months, she gets nervous walking over bridges and walks very slow and cautiously. She also seems to recognize the noises of the trains go by much more frequently than she did when she was younger. She walks into walks or doors when she is preoccupied and not paying attention.

"Because he has lost more vision, his ""sniffer"" , as we call it, is more in use as the food and treat finding tool. He still sometimes has some difficulty homing in on it if it is a particularly fragrant treat :). He does more frequently ""get lost"" if he is off of his routine path of travel. He also is more afraid at sudden noises or sensations, such as a truck coming down the street. Poor old guy!!!"
it seems that her thinking is slowing down. It takes her longer to make a decision.
Lady is more fearful of the dark.  Needs light on to see outside at night.  I believe this to be an indication of lessening sight rather than lessening cognition.

Freddie is now a little over 18 months old.  While he seems a bit calmer and less mouthy than he was at a little over a year, he also seems a bit more anxious when any of us, but especially Mom, have to leave.  It's difficult to tease out how much he is affected by the pandemic which has resulted in much of the family working and attending school from home.  Prior to March he seemed to be OK with us leaving him for short times, and those short times now seem to bother him.

I haven't noticed any changes in my dog's behavior over the past six months other than those associated with being in anti-anxiety medication to help with her fear of noises such as gunshots, fireworks, or loud bangs.
Ziva is observant of our behavior and knows when we are going somewhere. She understands when we tell her to stay because she is not going with us. Ziva is learning tricks.

"Sometimes she has ""spell"" were she seems confused and disconnected and wanders about the house. They occur randomly. Sometimes she goes 8-12 months at a time and has no problems. Then she might have 2-3 over a few days. I don't see any pattern or trigger. The vet thinks it's related to the heart. I think its mental possibly stress related issue having to do with the first 6 months of her life before I found her as a stray. "

She seems more needy for attention when she is awake. She has always been an anxious dog when her humans are not present, but she seems to really be anxious when she sees me leaving the house. We try to keep her from seeing my exits and that helps her not be as anxious about my absense.

He has become a little more calm around other dogs since we have started full time traveling in our RV and spending more time doing positive reinforcements training as well as spending time with a friend's two dogs, which gave him a chance to socialize in a new setting.
About 6 months ago we got a puppy to keep Chloe company.   Chloe seems to have regressed as the puppy keeps trying to play with her.
Indy has started to sit in spots that are more isolated and hidden like a closet or corner in the dining room.
While she still wants to be close to us most of the time, she sleeps under the bed or in another room more often during the day.
She is slower to get up off the ground and more scared of the washing machine than before. Not sure why the washing machine noises are making her more scared other than age.
He has no problem being left in the car while I run an errand but since we moved I can not leave him alone in the apt without him howling.
much slower at responding to commands
He seems calmer and cuddles more
No major changes noted. Still very mentally sharp

Reba has almost human like in her understanding of spoken words by humans. She follows commands in a very human way and even has a sense of clock in many things such as food, walks, sounds of here parents autos sounds, parents step sounds. Reba will without command pick items off the floor and hand them to me as I am disabled. The one issue we have and that is our fault is she has become very food motivated.
It seems as if his scenting is somewhat diminished
"He's even more fed up with ""stay at home"" orders than we are. He was used to getting lots of alone time and now gets frustrated that people are home 24/7...."

I have unfenced property behind my house and she is now learning she can run on my command and learning to come back on command. I only allow for a little time cause I don't trust her 100% to listen. Also, when I open the front door she is not running out. I point my finger and say stay. She is listening much better. Of course, I always tell her she is a good girl and then she goes to the pantry for a cookie.

She's began hunting and chasing squirrels and birds much more. Using her nose to smell out the yard and been much more attentive to the outside world. This is in large part I think because we moved from apartments to a house with a yard. Before the house we moved into 7 months ago she had never lived anywhere but in 1 bedroom apartments. She is noticing much more. This winter I plan on training her with sound recorded buttons to better help her communication and thinking
Taught himself how to open bifold closet doors without food/toy reward.
No she acts the same as 6 months ago.

Amber is a want to be Alpha.  She was born first in a litter of 8 to Flip who is 1 year older.  We kept 2 of the pups and have a 12 year old (Zoe) all Chesapeakes.  Zoe is the alpha.  Amber challenges all  3 but usually is put in her place by Zoe and Flip(her mother).  Steak (her sister) puts up with her but enjoys teasing her and playing.  Amber is the most active and plays a lot even if it's just with herself.
Our dog has much more separation anxiety and has become more protective when walking her in the last 6 months
I think his main problems are that he doesn't hear very well and his arthritis is getting worse - no apparent cognitive issues noted
Slight increase in frustration when problem solving.
no, not at this time.  She seems good

No, Lucy is VERY bright! She will not tolerate a closed door in the house and will paw to get it open, nudge it open, and insists on free reign in the house! She is a fantastic alpha guard dog and always alerts to visitors or passers by.  She observes the invisible fence even when she doesn't have her collar on.  She loves to curl up in chairs.  She has two bad habits...she loves chocolate and her big nose will seek it out if bags or purses or anything is left where she can access it so we are careful to keep it out of her reach, and she loves to chew up tissues.  She will sometimes unroll the toilet paper and chew it, she will dig tissues out of my purse and she has even learned to open the garbage can that has  a lever to open the lid so that she can dig them out of the trash!  I think this is just anxiety or boredom so I am trying to take her out for walks regularly and make sure she has plenty of playtime and mental stimulation.
slightly less anti-social yet still negatively reactive to perceived inattention
"He's the same. With regards to these questions, his behavior has been stable since he was 2 (or when he out grew the ""puppy"" phase)."

Lucca has always been a nervous dog.  Still skiddish and runs at the slightest noise or anything unfamiliar.  Told when I adopted him that he had been abused.  It has been 7 years and he still worried.   He is a gentle loving soul. Wouldn't harm a fly

In the last 6 months, my dog has slowed down a bit. She has not displayed any of the previous dementia symptoms but she opts to stay on the couch rather than follow me and my other dog around the house, like she used to.

Seems to recognize more words and directions to places he likes to go (example grandchildren's house). More familiar with family routine. Able to more readily tell when he gets to go places with us and when he will be staying home. He used to get excited whenever we put on coats. She is still keen and protective. She loves to bark at anything that moves outside, but she is sleeping more.

"She seems to be having a bit more trouble ""settling down"" to sleep, both at night and during the day. She sleeps the same amount, it just takes her a lot longer to get settled and there are substantially more circles before she lays down."

My puppy is getting 'smarter' by the day learning new things and following commands.

I haven't really noticed any changes in Button.

i do notice a very little maturity in her thinking, if that makes sense.  she is growing up, lot of puppy though

"not really - the only ""old dog"" behavior is occasional low volume bark/growl, usually in the evenings, as if something was outside (person or dog) but nothing there.  not incessant and we usually ""call him out on it"" and he stops.  he sleeps more, doesn't range/run like he used to on our morning and afternoon walks (99.9% off leash and in an area safe/away from traffic, etc...(i.e., a field) "

No. With COVID restrictions, we go out much less than we used to.

Seems a little more needy.  HIs routine has changed in many ways.

She's completely blind, so some of the answers are hard to answer (I wouldn't say she stares at the floor or walls because she can't see. Typically, she's either laying down (and snoring) or pacing. Related, she recognizes many more words.

Wilson is a very smart and sharp dog.  He can distinguish between different toys when called upon to retrieve them.  He is a hunting machine who loves to work the field, point and retrieve upland birds.

Over the past month, Pongo has started waking us up in the night, not to go outside, but to get our attention. He paws at us until we pet and snuggle him. Sometimes that isn't enough if we fall back to sleep and stop the petting, he paws at us again.
No. He's enjoying the pandemic since we are home much more.

Nothing really has changed.  She is very alert, has no problems with cognition.  I have noticed she has become more in control of her actions. She is not as impulsive as she has been in the last 6 mos.  Finally maturity has settled her down!
His level of activity remains constant except that I walk him a little less since he suffered a luxuriating patella and sometimes I notice a limp so I pick him up..
No longer chews on furniture or baseboards. Less restless in the early morning now. Somewhat less playful with toys in the past 6 months.

"I notice that she is slightly less obedient. Nothing dangerous but slower to respond to some commands like ""come"" or ""stay"" used in everyday life. Not sure if this is due to any cognitive change as she's very active and ""with it"". She has been an obedience competitor and typically is very responsive."

During the last month my dog was hospitalized twice.  The first time, I believe the doctors gave him too many enemas thinking he had a blockage in his intestines'. After, releasing him he came home and vomited large amounts of blood(twice) before we could get him to an emergency animal hospital. There he stayed for several days.  He required a blood transfusion, and several tests. He had a camera they inserted that took pictures of his whole intestines, stomach, etc. And we did a biopsy of his stomach.  He is cancer free but is suffering from stomach ulcers and a very irritated lining of the stomach and small intestines'. He now requires special dog food and several medicines as well as restricted activity as least until his next check-up in two weeks when we repeat blood work. He appears to be slowly recovering but I'm not sure how well be can be free on my ranch to consume his favorite dish, horse manure, etc.
"On occasion, Peggy seems to have trouble getting started when going up carpeted stairs. He seems hesitant or almost like he ""forgot"" how to climb steps. "

We have a new puppy. He replaced a dog who was older that was killed. Maple doesn't like to come thru doors anymore as the puppy jumps on her in a playful  manner. Maple is 20 lbs , puppy 9 lbs. maple also won't do a trick anymore unless he is restrained as she has to lie on the floor.  Maple seemed depressed after our other dog died but the puppy seems to make her sad as well in a different way. I try to make sure she is petted and loved but the puppy is demanding and very cute.

This is a rescue dog. She was 5 months when adopted with no info about previous life. She was received withdrawn and during Covid had little opportunity to socialize. As the restrictions ease, we attempted to expose her to different experiences off our one acre property. We found her to be reactive and fearful. We used two different canine behaviorists who came to our home and enrolled her in basic class skills with one later for five sessions. She seems to be slightly less reactive and fearful with practice and exposure. More treats are always her favorite tool for new experiences. Working with both household adults and the other rescue dog of 4years assists with the acceptance of new surprises in her environment.
He seems to respond to commands less than before, but he is also losing hearing and sight, so i'm unsure if this is explained by a cognitive decline.
Obsession with solving treat puzzles decreased in time (from will spend 40-60minutes- to now spends 20-30 minutes before ending the activity.)
Sophie is mentally very alert and enjoys learning new things.
Maybe some slight vision/hearing loss. She seems to use her nose more to identify food, people, and locations. She'll be 13 in January.

Luna is almost 11, I have noticed that she doesn't want to play crazy with her sister. her sister Sadie loves to play. She also thinks about stairs, when before she would run up them. I have added ramps on the stairs in the back yard and she often uses them. hers sister will not use them.  Luna also doesn't always want to jump into the car, although she loves to go places....so we often use a ramp for the car tooo. Luna loves the ramp. her sister does not. Luna is hard of hearing and a very visual and very good at making herself understood.
As she is getting to know me and I her, I can tell that she is a typical poodle -- very smart!

No change in thinking or information processing.  He is slightly more anxious due to presence of new pet, a cat. He has returned to his normal activity level following an L5-S1 strain with supposed herniated disc (unconfirmed by CT/MRI).
No changes observed, but I'd like to note that the dropped food question/test isn't answerable in Olive's case, as she has been taught to ignore food that is not expressly offered to her.  FWIW:)
"She has become more of a ""beggar"" when it comes to people with food. She has also become a little more independent."
No changes that I'm aware of.

He seems to learn faster now, this is mostly in regards to his physical therapy exercises. The first round took forever to get him trained to do what we wanted him to do. We recently got a new set of exercises and it took about 2 try's of doing them before he picked up what I wanted him to do.
slight difficulty/hesitation before jumping onto bed or car's tailgate

Before March when the pandemic lockdown started we had a decent handle on managing his separation anxiety. I was temporarily laid off for 6 months. When I returned to work his severe separation anxiety returned and we were back at square one. He would pee and poop in the house and destroy doors, including a steel door, to get to other rooms. His vet increased the dosage on his fluoxetine and we medicate him with gabapentin and trazodone before leaving the house while we work on behavior therapy. We are attempting to desensitize him to the cues we are leaving the house. He seems to be slowly improving.

"It appears, as an RN, that he may have some ""sundowners"" symptoms the last 6-9 months. He is just not as sharp as he was in the evenings. For example, where he would always actively play fetch with his ball he is apt to loose interest and need to be reminded of the task at hand."
No, she seems to process new information the same as she did 6 months ago.

His eyesight is deteriorating because of diabetes. He seems a bit more confused and doesn't always recognize us but that may be because he can't see as well anymore. But sometimes we wonder if he's getting senile in his old age.

Not really that I can think of.

Not really. Toby is an active, healthy 3 year, 5 month old dog. On second thought, he's getting better at following the hand signal to sit that I've been teaching him, but that's about the only change

She seems to stay alert and extremely interested in food.  She rolls over to express her excitement before and after meals or whenever she thinks foods are coming. So, we did not walk long and went back to my car. Her behaviors at home seem to be stable with no obvious change.

As she continues chemotherapy, I occasionally observe Josie seemingly to forget what she's supposed to do, kind of like she's just slow to process things/commands.  She was never like this until starting chemo.

She is an active girl! We are always eager to train. She is a therapy dog missing visits due to Covid.  So we are working on agility. We also work on new tricks and working on some scent work. Also creating a game for her to search for treats in the back yard. She is  very smart . I love having new adventures with her. She even played Sandy in Annie at one of the local high schools.  Hoping for Things to change so we can get back out in the community
He seems more affected by sharp sounds, like high pitched bells or pings on the television. They make him tremble.
He is more demanding of attention as we have played more since we have been spending more time at home. It clear he knows things have changed and is enjoying the additional time & attention

Covid has been tough on Bosley, who was already prone to separation anxiety. When things started to open back up, he'd get really stressed when I left the apartment - so much so that I put the crate away and now let him free roam. He takes a little while to settle down (I invested in a camera to observe him) but is getting better each time I leave.
She now goes outside and barks at nothing. Will walk around smelling the ground but in no specific direction. Normally eats feces but now not as much.

Inara 'asks' for things a lot more lately. In the last 6 months, Izzy seems more aware of the schedule of eating and specifically getting her pills in the pill pocket after eating. his coordination is starting to go when catching things in his mouth. You used to be able to throw a treat at him, unannounced from across the room and he'd always catch it like a ninja. He's catching fewer and fewer of them. Same thing with balls :(

No changes in cognitive abilities. She does not hear or see as well as she used to.

My dog stopped chewying on rugs and furniture

"She has actually improved in her responses to family and ""playing"" since surviving acute kidney failure last December. "

Emmett is having issues with our kitchen tile floor. In the past - no problems, but he was running across it one day and slipped in a particular spot. Because it is on the way into the Family room and also to the outside, we ended up putting a rug in that area and now he has no issue. He is definitely afraid of slipping and falling.

We also have another family member able to help with her walks, so she's getting 3 mile walks at least 5 days a week.  She loves being out and I think it helps keep her young.  She reminds me of her much younger self again.
Neville is losing his eyesight which is why he is sometimes running into walls and doors.  So far, it hasn't impacted his recognition of people or his ability to find food on the floor.
"Since the Pandemic he becomes somewhat more anxious if my husband and I are both out of the house. We've been working remotely and he likes this ""new normal."""

He has always had a tendency to want space from us and will just go where there is no noise or distraction to sleep or just be by himself.  He has always done this, but more so over the years given he is now @14 and has congestive heart failure and a severe heart murmur.  He remains engaged, excited about any new activities, food, sleeping, and loves loves his walks., and hanging out in his dog run for hours at a time, day and night.

Not at all. He is blind, so a lot of the first questions were a bit hard to answer, but when thinking about his cognition in all activities while attributing things like bumping into walls sometimes as an effect of blindness, he hasn't changed much in years. He's the same little guy, and since he lost his sight 2 years ago - he has shown an incredible determination to learn how to navigate the world and communicate. At 15yrs old now, he sleeps more, and is less active overall - but cognitively he is not showing any signs of decline.

We recently had a baby (he is currently 7 months) and Penny has now started to interact with him by walking up to him, sniffing him, and licking him. She is a lot more interested in him now. Our son has also started crying a lot less, so that may play a role?

"Although Bomber has always been very social - and friendly - with both people and dogs - both known and unknown to him, over the last couple of years, he has become less interested in ""greeting"" people.  When we are out in public and someone wants to pet him, I may say ""Bomber, go say hello.""  Although he always does and is  always friendly, he will sometimes look at me as if saying, ""Do I have to?"" Bomber has never shown ""separation anxiety"" although frequently left for the day.  Over the last several months I have noticed him sticking closer to me  when walking on occassion , or waiting for me to make sure I'm coming.  I have noticed  over the the last year or so that Bomber has become less interested in playing with other dogs at dog parks.  Although always friendly, after making the ""rounds,' he will generally come back and stand with me. To some extent, like most standard poodles, he is more a ""people"" dog and not all that interested in other dogs. "

Sundae is a rescue and has been with us now for one full year.  She is much more confident and independent than the was six months ago - likely because she feels more secure.  She is cognizant of our existence and respectful of our bond, and at the same time more willing to decide what she wants to do in the moment.  It will be interesting to see how this develops over time, and how much she is willing to be obedient constant with her training.

he has started barking without any clear reason.  i take him out many many times, i've  given him food (but not to reward barking) , i pet him. so i don't know what he wants.    when i sit at the dining room table any time   of day, he will go through periods of barking at me.  it might be separation anxiety because today i picked him up and put him on the couch next to me while i sat for a few minutes, and he calmed down.
"He is learning (slowly) the command ""quiet"", because he is a barker when people come to the door, or a golf cart goes buy, or he sees people/dogs walking in the street."
He now has a head tilt due to vestibular disease, but has regained everything else, balance, movement, gait, etc.

Farley has always had an issue with high pitched sounds, like a smoke detector going off. He gets nervous for 30 minutes after hearing it, even if it was just for half a second. He just acts unsettled and wants to be by one of us. Over the past year, we have noticed that he has started becoming more afraid of thunderstorms. He was never afraid of them before, but last year we lost our other dog, Darla, to throat cancer, and Farley is now a single dog family. I don't know if it was always present, but due to having another dog around that didn't care helped him, or now that he is by himself, he is unsure what to do.
I notice that Pongo doesn't like to walk as far as he used to on his (almost) daily walks. He used to walk a mile or more easily and is now about a half a mile.

Lexi has always exhibited anxiety during fireworks (4th of July stinks).  She does not need medication to weather these episodes--but really wants to be with us. I have notice that overall, smaller noises (including certain cell phones tones) will cause her to leave the room and become anxious.
Nothing really has changed in the last 6 months in Molly's behavior.

We met with a behaviorist to help deal with her anxiety. It was the best thing we've ever done. She was prone to submissive peeing and was terrified of going outside, but within a few months she really improved! She's only had one accident during a thunderstorm, and now she begs to go outside. She doesn't pace like she used to and sleeps so much better.
He is 18 mos old.  He is learning to not jump on people when they enter the house or if we meet them on the street.

She was diagnosed with thyroid cancer and laryngeal paralysis in June 2020; had surgery to address both in July. She is actually more active/energetic now in recovery. This does not appear to have impacted her cognitition.

Cooper has changed since the Covid-19 events  I believe because I do not leave the home except for Dr. visits, which have occurred only twice since Feb.  Cooper is used to going in car often to Opera, Symphony, Jazz, Grocery. Family brings everything to me. Cooper has not been a dog that sits on my lap a lot.  Last six months he is on my lap most of day and all night.  I sleep in recliner due to neck/back issues. Cooper comes to me wanting up on lap.  Very unusual for him. He also seems to know words like chicken, dinner, warms, heat, lunch, David (my nephew) water.  He has not responded to words  before.  I'm not sure if Cooper wants on my lap for himself or for me.  The few times that he was on the floor when I fell asleep, I wake up with him barking, wanting up. I'm always shocked! Cooper barely EVER barks.  I should say NEVER.  This is new. When at opera/symphony he never even moves. Peeps I know, are the only ones that know he is with me. He is my perfect companion dog. So I'm not sure if he wants on my lap for himself or me. I have not been myself because of the election.  I've been very upset worrying about our forests and environment and not wanting Trump re-elected. Is Cooper reacting to me?  I wouldn't be surprised. Or is my ego too big and he has just become a lovely little pup in his old age.
No. Luna has been the same! A little more active (walks) now that Covid hit and we are all home!

the only thing that changed his behavior was when we got a second dog just under 2 years ago. after the second dog came into our home, he became much more aggressive to strangers and especially strange dogs. he has stayed the same with his human family, seeking contact and tummy rubs and the like. he has not demonstrated any of the behaviors described in the preceding questions.

He is getting a little slower and has trouble jumping into the back seat of a sedan car, though that does not stop him at all from wanting a 30 minute walk in the morning or dog playing with our younger dog outside for as much as 10 minutes at a time.

Scotty is now 1.5 years old. Since reaching around 9 months his behavior has remained the same. Previous to that he had typical puppy troubles with housebreaking and adjusting to growth (like getting stuck in small places he used fit into). He is intelligent and has figured out how to open doors and unlock a gate.

The COVID virus has kept us both from engaging actively with others. He has become a bit bored,  he is less likely to to approach others on walks, and he is less likely to respond to engagement by others. He has always been shy. The virus is, sadly, amplifying this behavior.
No, I have not noticed any changes in his thinking behavior.

Much less irritability toward 1 dog and 1 cat housemates, both present in household when Ollie was adopted.  The irritability began about 8 months ago (age 3 yrs) and medical evaluation found no medical cause.  The behavior seems associated with protection of person or food.

In the last couple of weeks he has started chewing on his leash and attempting to play tug with it while we are walking.  Not sure where this came from, but his trainer is coming tomorrow to help me figure it out.
With consistent walks in the park, he is understanding even more my gestures (such as pointing ahead to go forward)
due to the virus activities have currently put as hold so I would say Lucy is indoor more and playing with her toys or keeping me company-sleeping but we do go outside
In the last year Bogey has preferred to sleep in a quiet space - on a bed inside the closet. Often when we all go to bed, hexx CA walks right into the closet.

"She no longer likes dry dog food.  We have tried just about every brand available from Kroger and while she is polite about it, she just isn't all the interested.  Put gravy on it, and it's the best thing ever! She is either experiencing arthritis (hip, knee, or both), or maybe a torn ACL or CCL.  It's her passenger side rear leg that she favors.  She has a bowl of clean fresh water every day inside the house, but prefers to go outside and drink from a bowl covered in algae and full of rainwater. If I toss a milkbone biscuit at her and it lands in the floor, she is more apt to look at it, then look at me as if, ""You have bad aim"", and ""You throw like a moron"".  "
Not that I am aware of.
She is more clingy, and follows me around the house. She is often so close to me that when I turn around I step on her or trip over her.
I had another dog (Rogue) who passed away 2 months ago. Jax is less active and more affectionate with people since her passing.
Becoming more alert / looking for something to chase.
Much more sensitive to light and shadow and tends to get confused with where he is outside
Follow me around the house much more than before
She plays with her toys less often.
He seems more jealous of the attention given to my other dog. He is more loving to me and often sleeps closer to me in bed.

"I have observed changes.  Leo is much more clingy. He'll go through the house but without real purpose. When I escort upstairs to our bedroom at night, he often takes a wrong term until redirected. in the morning I have to redirect him when we get ready for a walk.  I see a decline. He's a wonderful boy who gets along so well with his ""siblings"" (a German Sheppard and another Shar Pei). "
Not really. He seems to be on his game for being 12.
No changes so far. Yankee turned 8 in October
She sleeps slightly a little more than before.

He is still a puppy and only about 6 months old so he is still growing and learning about his environment and surroundings as well as how to problem solve. He seems to get slightly smarter every day and is picking things up faster as well.
Just very recently, she has started whining more for attention, including in the middle of the night.

Overall she is still perky and cognitively intact.  I've noticed changes to her senses in the past year. For instance, if I throw a stick in the water for her and there is a lot of glare she can't see the stick.  She can't control her body movements as well and might run into the wall once in awhile. She's less aware of herself spatially. These are some of the aging signs I've noticed.

"He occasionally spends time on walks just looking around for a few minutes. We had an older lab that would get stuck in  ""neutral"" for 10 minutes or more where he would just stop and be in a daze, but this is nothing like that as Ralph just seems to be observing things around him."
He's getting lazier prob due to his age. But he love going to the dog park and running around for a few hours. He usually sleeps much more after playing, I've noticed.
Things have remained consistent in these areas for Calla over the past 6 months.
Pumpkin is now on a regime for a t zone, I think, lymphoma. Pills at home. So there have been changes, Much less active. And now the staring. No all the time but some. How sad.
She appears to have more of a personality now than she is before and is a bit more needy

"Bradley was taken to the vet for a recent check up and to get annual vaccines. It was detected that he has lyme disease and he also has a urinary tract infection. So his behavior has changed in the last few months and we don't know if it's aging or from the lyme disease. He does sometimes pace around more than he did in the past and sometimes we notice him staring without purpose. The lyme disease or aging seems to be effecting his joints and sometimes he's randomly ""lame"" in one front leg or the other. He seems to ""know"" that it's more difficult for him to jump up on furniture or get down. He seems to contemplate whether he can make it or not and then sometimes just lays down on the floor. Sometimes when he gets down from furniture and he can walk well initially, he'll also lay down on the floor. We bought him a ramp to go up and down on the couch and he's learning out to use it, which seems to help him. "
He has seasonal allergies so he was experiencing discomfort in his paws (licking them raw), having to wear a cone so he would stop, making him more lethargic when wearing the cone inside.
At times more reluctant to come out for a walk when called.
Has become a little skittish and gun shy. But not terribly
Still enjoys meeting other dogs but not quite as much
I've only had him for 2 years, and he is actually getting better.  Less anxiety and more trust of me.  Doesn't let any other people come near or touch him.  Will bark or back away.

I have noticed he just cannot hear or see as well and sometimes will walk into a dresser or the screened door.  He never does it too hard.  He seems to be able to see in areas that well lit compared to dim or dark areas

For the last 3 months I've been taking her to the barn every morning when I feed the horses.  I attach a 50-foot leash because she has a tendency to run off.  She hears me but is hard-headed and easily distracted and doesn't come reliably (like someone else she knows).  The last few weeks I'm letting her drag the leash and she is returning and minding better.   Another thing we are doing is teaching both dogs everybody's name.  It's funny that they know their own names but not each other's or our names and certainly not those inferior cats' names.
Sundance seems to be getting more clever at opening gates and finding places where we have people food...she waits until we are in bed.  Also, she doesn't seem to be as frighted of storms.

She's gotten a little more neurotic. Between our hot summer, we werent able to do as much with her and the elevated stress in our house with everything going on. She's very intuitive, so she can get stressed easy.
she has been more affectionate and seeking attention, not less.
She seems a little anxious (ie barks at car doors slamming and people walking by) when we have to change our schedules to work from home.
Our vet thinks Lily is going blind with cataracts. Her eyes are very cloudy and if we don't point to a dropped food item on the floor, the doesn't see it.
None, except that I think she loves the pandemic!  It means we are here with her almost all the time.  She's in heaven!

He has had a major change in food preferences compared with 6 months ago. About 2 months ago he developed diarrhea and was diagnosed with pancreatitis and kidney disease. That combined with his heart failure led to him not wanting food. We were slowly able to get him to start eating baby food, and now occasionally some meat or food nuggets. But, he is very picky. He seems to show an interest in food once he sees the other dogs eating it.
Memory for people and other dogs seems to have improved.
He has been the same happy-go-lucky mutt.
Very aware of her surroundings and hearing is very good
Extreme jealously of the other dog in our house.  Very curious about anything new she notices, make-up on your face, different clothing, new household objects.

"We live on a farm and he's decided that the peacocks warrant chasing, but the guinea fowl are not worth bothering.  Not sure why he does not seem interested in chasing the guineas... he did when he first encountered them.   I have not done much to train him not to do this - maybe telling him to ""leave it"" a couple times. So I can't truly attribute it to my excellent training skills! ha ha... He also has become interested in deer, when before he did not seem aware of them. "
She is still a puppy and is very active.
the masks can sometimes be confusing when trying to recognize people she knows - but she adapts quickly once she studies the person a bit.
She seems a bit more aggressive with one of the other dogs in the house.
No cognitive deterioration that I observe. Sometimes she doesn't notice little treats on the floor, but that is not age-related.

She is pretty much the same. She is not food motivated, pays no attention to dropped food. When she goes outside she has 80 mostly wooded acres to wander, she's a hunter and will dig mice out of a rotted stump. Sometimes she will stay outside at night and sleep in a chair on the porch where she can see up the driveway. Animals that intrude on her domain, deer, dogs, and coyotes get chased off. She has caught 8 possums so far this year. She defecates in the woods away from the house. Her favorite treat is cheese, which is given as a reward for coming in the house at night and after having a bath.
No she is about the same.  She gets up for attention a lot more often, but she has been feeling poorly due to bladder issues lately.

He seemed to be more aware of noises in the evening, whether they were on TV or actually outside; and wanted to go outside to investigate much more than usual. I felt this was becoming a weird quirk, so got him a friend, a 9 week old labradoodle puppy friend. The change in Jack has been amazing, he has become an awesome big brother and plays with his sister nonstop! I think the quarantine was beginning to get to all of us, and a new pup was just what we needed!
Since Lucy is only 15 months old we have seen a lot of changes in her behavior.  She is much more confident around strange people and dogs.
Beau seems to take more or longer naps. He wants to be near us most of the time. But when it is time for action, he's always excited.

If anything Bex is a little more skittish than he was and more reluctant to go up to people.  (It was always a battle to get him near to people)  This may be due to the fact that because of COVID he meets fewer people that before.
She use to take a nap everyday around 1:99 with me now she will lie down but get back up unless my wife lies down with me then she will stay in bed besides me until my wife gets up.
she had a gallbladder issue for a few months now that it has been cleared up she is much more active
He seems less restless and calmer than when he was younger. It seems like he's growing out of his puppy zoomies stage.
Wiley has become more anxious.  Barking at sounds going on outside or in other rooms of the house.  He has more times also of sudden whining for no apparent reason.
The other day I called her from the kitchen and she went to look for me in the bathroom, which is the opposite direction. I thought that was odd, but she has also been battling an ear infection.
The only change is he is playing with the 22 month old bitch and they have become almost inseparable.

He is becoming more cuddly and seeks attention and affection more often.  Don't know if this is a function of age or if he is just starting to get more jealous of the attention our other dog (who has always been needy) gets.
He steals more things that are not his.  Seems to delight in this behavior.
Probably sleeps a little more but is always ready to go if you head for the door
She is a rescue and we have only had her for 6 months. We have been through several trainings so her thinking and processing have changed because of that.
Happy has been chewing on my tree branches out back. Pine tree and Rose of Sharon trees. She loves to chew wood.
I have observed none of these behaviors in my dog's thinking or information processing ever.
Worsening night vision, lower visual acuity in low light environments

Dixie seems to be losing some sight ability and quite a bit of hearing ability in the last year or so.  She has a wonderful appetite, loves treats, and, although our floors are all light-colored wood, (the same color as her treats!) she can usually find them without much help.  One thing which is new is that she jerks her head as if she has received an electric jolt several times a day.  This seems to be connected with her vision loss because she does it when something surprises her which she may not have seen (or heard?)  Also, until December 2019 she walked about two miles a day with me.  Now I'm lucky if I can get her to walk a few hundred steps outside.
"I don't know if this is relevant, but he seems a bit more ""clingy"", always needing to be wherever I am."
He seems more reactive on leash than previously. It seems to have gotten worse.
We do sometimes wonder if he is not seeing as clearly.  When off leash and at a little distance it seems like he takes longer than he used to to identify me.
There are no noticeable changes in my dog's thinking or information processing in the last 6 months
Her problem solving and critical thinking skills have increased and can solve existing puzzles at a faster rate but learning newer and more complex puzzles seem to frustrate her instead of inspire
The biggest change has been her decreased vision and then struggling to deal with shadows as she walks around the house, making her more anxious and fearful at times.

Betty seems to ignore us sometimes. At first we thought she had gone deaf but she reacts intermittently to her name being called or a loud noise. This behavior started January of this year and seems to have gotten a bit worse.
No changes in the last six months.

Emma seems to be slightly aggressive to other dogs in house without being provoked. Example jumped up and lunged at a dog on other persons lap when person moved suddenly to get up. At the dog not the person.

Seeing a steady increase in separation anxiety. Gets much more anxious when he realizes someone is going out. Used to be able to leave him uncrated when alone but now he becomes destructive if left loose
She frequently used to avoid being petted or cuddling as she wanted to play instead. Gradually she is becoming more interested in being petted/cuddling instead of always wanting to play actively.
He takes a couple seconds longer to process we are home if he is awoken from a deep sleep. There is more of a lag before he gets up and starts wagging his tail.
If anything I think he struggles with the fact that he can't be as active as he'd like to be, and he'll throw little fits

Because we believe his hearing has deteriorated considerable this past year, we asked our vet at his most recent visit last month.  The vet confirmed that he had great difficulty in getting Murphy to respond to sounds.  Murphy also has had cataracts for about two years we think and there are now times when I take him for a walk outside in the evening, if the lighting is not really good that he may walk into some plants that he would have avoided when his vision was better.

She has become more demanding in the evening barking for her evening pill accompanied by a dog biscuit treat. She is an outside dog.  She stands in front of our kitchen window and barks for her treat once darkness begins to fall.  This is mostly new behavior. She seems to want more affection and petting, but this could just be that we notice it more now because we have been home almost constantly since mid March 2020 and pandemic.

Marley has been on Vetmedin for enlarged heart since April 20th of this year. Since he has been on it, he seems more alert and easier to wake up. He is also more active. He is going on 14 now and of course he sleeps a lot but I can definitely see a positive change.
More time seeming distressed during the night  Sadly her tail is now curled under a lot, tho it quickly raises if she sees a deer out the window! And she doesn't appear to be in pain
When she goes out to pee or poop she sometimes seems to forget why she is outside. She also does not hear as well as she used to.
"He shows more ""selective"" hearing.  He ignores me a little more when I must call him to stay in front of the house. No other changes."
None that I can think of.
She understands and is consistently more compliant with behaving , drop it, sit, settle, walking better on leash
He doesn't play as hard or as long but is still very active.

Not a change in the last 6 months but something he has done since I adopted him in March 2017. When it's time to go to bed he does not want to be petted or have any other type of interaction with me, just wants me to go to bed and be left alone. Then in the AM it is the exact opposite, can't get enough love and attention.

The main change is in his stamina. He will play hard for a few minutes, but runs out of steam quickly. Also, he has significant arthritis so he doesn't run/walk as far as he used to. He also only has one eye (from birth) and the sight in the other (along with his hearing) has been significantly reduced. So he perhaps startles more easily than he used to, but I think it's because he can't depend on his other senses to alert him to people nearby.
Bias: the past six months encompass a pandemic
I can see my dog grow physically and mentally every day.  He is just 6 months old and loves to learn.
I have only had my dog for 6 weeks

She has these little random spurts of puppy-like energy where she wants to play like she did when she was younger (e.g. tug of war with her favorite stuffed kitty, running/charging at you playfully, pouncing on her kitty, zoomies, etc.). It seemingly comes out of nowhere and has no observable rhyme or reason as to when it will happen. It's always at different times of the day although more frequently at night and definitely not everyday. It typically lasts anywhere from 5-15 minutes and then she's done and is content.
Luke is the only one who thinks this Pandemic is great! He spends 99% of his time with one or the other of us.
I haven't observed any changes in that time period
Brando will be 2 years old next month. He seems to have gotten smarter. More of his personality is showing. Great dog!

"Musty was adopted by us in January 2020 at the age of 9yrs 5mos. We've come to realize he is very intelligent and thrives when I clicker train him. He gets so excited and ""lights up"" trying to figure out what behavior I want from him. There is a sparkle in his eyes during training---and it's not the treat that he gets. It's the fun interaction. It will be a challenge to keep him mentally engaged."

"Casey is intent on keeping track of his pack members. He loves to play and understands some new commands, like ""drop"" and ""find your stick/ball."" He's exceptionally good at catching toys, especially balls, has a very accurate built-in clock-times for breakfast, dinner and walks-clearly knows words like ""dog park,"" ""ride,"" ""pool,"" ""wait,"" ""cold water,"" (which he shows a preference for over tap water) and ""swim or swimming"" (his favorite sport). One of the most noticeable changes in his behavior is that he now understands that touching/stroking his head is a sign of affection, not aggression. 6 months ago, he would back off somewhat when we tried to pet him on the head. Casey is still a little slow at processing ""no,"" but it is hard to tell if it's obstinance or lack of understanding. "
In the last 6 months, his vision has decreased slightly. This may be due to his microphthalmia or another condition. He will be seeing his board certified ophthalmologist this week.
We moved across the country (from Boston to Eugene OR) in early August 2020. Since then she is more agitated by new sounds or specific trucks that drive by.
Jack seems to be a little sluggish lately. Granted, he's now 8 years old but he is slower to walk up the steps and doesn't get too excited for things.
She is now an unruly teen. She forgets she has a name when she sees a deer or rabbit.

Scooter has always been hyperactive, but going on 12 yrs old we are observing  a slight slowing.  We live 70% of our time on our 47 acre vineyard property he gets a 3 mile hike around the vineyard every day.  The rest of the time he just runs free on his own.  The other 30% of the time is spent at our cabin in the Cascades on 7 acres.  Every day we hike 6 miles on various sections of the PCT.  It takes 2 hours.  He determines the speed, but is on a leash as he likes to chase deer.
Moochy is an alpha her entire life. Stoic, proud, wicked smart, fearless. But now she's hesitant to even go outdoors some days. Its like she knows she's aging and feels vulnerable.

Not in thinking,  but behavioral. I think its due to her possessiveness of me. But, we have another dog that we got 4years ago as a puppy. Now, a neutered male. English bulldog. They have been pals and played ever since we got him. And now, this last January,  she has started attacking him. To the point of severe aggression.  We cannot let them be together any longer.  I don't know why this has happened. But, figured I had better let you know. This is the only change in her.
No, has just slowed down a little physically, but still cognitively the same.

She is much more clingy than she used to be--often she does not tolerate being left in a room for even a short period, especially if it's her favorite person.  She'll bark until she gives up on the idea of us coming back, then finally will get up (she has significant arthritis) and check in each room until the person she wants returns or is located.  That's a new behavior in the last 6-12 months.    When she gets stuck around objects, it is clearly related to arthritis (she's 15+!), but she's always been a fast learner, so unclear if it's stubbornness or not figuring out she is definitely going to get stuck if she lays down under a particular table.  The defecating in unusual places is interesting.  Her whole life she has pooped along a fence line, or as far away as possible.  In the last several months she still walks in those areas, but comes back to the bottom of the ramp (highest traffic area) to poop.
Changes in behavior from 6 months ago could be attributed to moving to a new home and no longer having another dog in the house 100% of the time.
None, he is goofy, energetic and a thinker.

We had a broken water pipe that did significant damage to house.  There have been a lot of tradesmen repairing the damage.  He had been put off by strangers in past.  He now greats strangers with a few barks and rubs up to them
My dog does not seem to have problems with thinking or information processing at this time.

The vet gave him Maxi Otic for ears and he lost hearing, which after the fact they said happens in geriatric dogs. Oh My!  Some hearing has returned but he  doesn't hear well.  Sometime when he is eating he will stop and stand still. Not sure if it is a mind issue like dementia or if he is trying to hear something. He does sleep much more than he did last year. He does still have lots of energy at 7 pm at night wanting to play, but like us all he has slowed down.  Sometimes I think he has a little trouble seeing far away, not sure.  He is an GREAT DOG at 13.
Become increasingly anxious and afraid of high pitch noises, people on video chats, jumping gate to hide

She seems to get more excited over squirels than before. She use to just watch for them and maybe if they were close by she would bark, now she barks anytime there is one around far away or close. She barks more over all. She will go out back and just start barking for no apparent reason, although I assume it is because she hears a door close next door or smells another dog. It is just a new behavior she has never done before.

About a year ago Ulf has shown anxiety ( whining  running around the house with a toy in his mouth ) and slight aggression to people who come in the house.  Does not matter if he knows them or not.  Take him away from the property and he has no problem at all  Do not know if this has to do with our other German Shephard or not.  Our other German Shephards is possessive and tries to keep him away from me. She tries to keep any other animals away from me, no problem with people only animals.
She seems to have a harder time waking up happy. She used to wake up and be a happy dog, but now- not so much, she seems to be in slow motion more often now. That is concerning since she is only 2.5

"Miles has trouble with problems and puzzles. His first response to every situation he gets into is to ask mom or any human nearby to solve whatever problem for him. He will look at the problem, look at you, look back at the problem, whine, and look back at you. He repeats this until he gets what he wants or gives up. We started puzzle games and when he gives up he will go into down position and repeat this process. I am his primary caregiver and he doesn't beg food or tenaciously whine when he isn't given a treat. He likes to push boundaries with my parents, who will sometimes give in.  Since we've had him since he was a puppy certain behaviors he does have started to mean different things to me. He has consistent separate vocalizations for wanting a treat, wanting to get under the covers, and ""mom help"". When he knows the person at the front door he won't alert, if he doesn't he will alert. Hopefully this will continue.    As for leaving while being petted or avoiding it, Miles' greatest motivator is play. If he can get you to play over being pet, he prefers it every time. For example, I work in the backroom next to the dog door and every time he comes in from outside he will always come over and get pet before heading off wherever. However, if I stand up or go after him he will run and grab whatever's in reach (hopefully 1 of his 30+ toys) and try to get me to chase him. The same goes with anybody coming into the house that he knows. He won't come over for pets he will grab something, wiggle, and hop in and out of that person's reach trying to get them to chase. Then he will bring over a chew and get the person to hold it for him. Miles was not a fast learner other than potty training. The situations that taught him the fastest were those when we had overnight foster dogs and tri-weekly puppy socials. He prefers other dogs and seems to mirror behaviors they do to an extent. "

"Storm is now 14 months old. She continues to build on patterns that she has learned or that we are training on. For example, now she readily trots to her mat, turns around and lays down when she wants to receive a tasty treat. We have shaped her behavior so that she must have all 4 paws on the mat, and she now corrects herself (sometimes we help with an ""OOPS!) to get every paw on the mat. Interestingly, she applies ""go to your mat"" to any rug/bed/small defined area that we point to. Also, she applies those same principles to our front porch, (go to the porch!) and one time she was going to step off the porch, and as she started to put her paws on the ground, I shouted a quick ""OOPS!"" and she tucked her legs back and got herself so quickly back onto the porch, just like a little kid who might get in trouble.    My main point is that we see her apply this principle of being or staying in one small, defined area (go to your mat- a small foot rug by the door) to other areas. her dog bed, the front porch, the mat by the front door, the rug on the front and back porch, etc. The training has really paid off in that regard. We shaped that behavior by progressing from a food reward when she was on the mat to only getting it when she eventually did what we wanted. "

If he leaves the house she will greet him at the door . She get much more excited to see me when I return but its nice to see her happy to see my son too. They are good friends.  My son loves her dearly. Overall we got a older dog from a shelter and I never expected for her to live this long. She is very loving a cuddly dog . Strange she will no just stay and eat all her food until it is gone.

No changes in thinking or information processing that I have observed.  I am a retired person living with solely a canine companion.  We are each like two halves of a Velcro strip.

During this time of pandemic quarantine, Duke has been more active because we are home all the time and so we are available to take him for more walks--this is why he is more active than before.  We have not noticed any changes in his thinking/info processing during quarantine.

With wetter winter weather, he has to dry off in the laundry room when coming in from the outside.  He resists being put into the laundry room even if it's with his dog sibling.

I started to notice this last year in the fall as well, so this year I'm trying to really watch this year, but I think my dog gets seasonal depression when winter begins to set in since we live in MN and sometimes its too cold or too snowy for him to go out. We try to keep him active indoors, but we definitely do start to scale back on outdoor exercise once it's less than 40 degrees in the morning. When this happens, even though we make sure he potties several times outside before coming in, and he is potty trained to an indoor grass patch, he decides to pee on random objects every so often indoors (mainly shoes or our barstools). Last month he went several days without curling his tail, and we couldn't figure it out. He could curl it, but was choosing not to. There was nothing we could see causing him pain. We did get 8-10 inches of snow around this time, but it finally warmed up and most ofbthat snow melted off and I waa able to take him to the dog park, and since then he has had no tail curling issues. We just got another major snow now that it is November, so I am sure the indoor peeing and stress symptoms like the tail might start again.

Rusty seems more olfactory in assessing his environment. He did K9 Nosework for a few years when I first adopted him but only recently does he seem to depend on his nose more. For example, he will bark or react in areas where a dog has recently passed by or I think he may be smelling wildlife that has passed by.  I had his eyes checked by an ophthalmologist recently and was told he eyes are normal for his eyes. In other words, changes seen are normal for his age so nothing seriously degenerative. He recognizes those he knows, but he seems to need to be closer before he does recognize them and he seems to be depending a bit on smell.  As far as uploading his medical information, I just thought right now that maybe I should include the report from the eye specialist. Should I try to get it now?

Difficulty figuring out how to eat his usual food after having several tooth extractions. We moved to a new home where he is outside more often and has more stimulation.

she is now deaf and her vision has deteriorated. she startles easily when approached from behind or touched. she has her own dog door and now asks us to watch her when she goes outside. she spends time outside standing and sniffing the wind. we believe her problems are more related to sensory loss rather then cognitive

No changes; over the years, some change in excitement level, but in the last six months, no change.  I think the changes over the years were as she became an adult. no, she is still an active border collie ( a little wild)

Continuing to improve at retrieving and hunting in preparation for organized Retriever Events.  Earned title of Started Hunting Retriever at 2 years and now training for Seasoned Hunting Retriever.  Learned to sit on a whistle and respond to hand signals.

After removing Teddy from Adequan, Neurontin and Tramadol 6 months ago he has stopped standing and staring into space. His sleep pattern returned to normal as did his cognition. We also started him on BrightMind Purina food which has contributed to improving his well being.. He gets half of a Xanax for sleep hs and a Galliprant in the morning with omega 3 oil. When Teddy was on the pain meds we thought for sure that we would have to put him down due to dementia. This has cleared and he is a happy dog again. Old - still has arthritis - but happy!  As are we.

just gotten much slower when walking although still wants to go for a walk. a bit more groaning when laying down.

I had a 16 year old Australian Shepherd who also had dementia. She displayed more symptoms so I'm hoping that at this point, Drake's are on the mild side.

Willy's behavior has changed a lot in the past year. (I know that's out of your time frame, but I'll throw it in.) As our other dog, Sparky, who died last October, aged and exhibited all of the behaviors you ask about in this questionnaire, Willy became very aggressive toward him. We always had trouble with Willy's aggression toward people (us mainly!) and had even considered putting him down because of it. Our vet said that he was a Level 3 biter. He and Sparky had gotten into spats before, but once this started, Willy really seemed to want to kill him. We had to keep them in separate areas of the house.  Willy has become a completely different dog since Sparky died. He hasn't offered to bite anyone since and, believe me, that's amazing! In all the 11 years the two dogs lived together with us, neither of them ever learned to ask to go outdoors to pee. The day after Sparky's death, Willy suddenly started asking to go out, and accidents now are rare. He suddenly developed different food preferences and now won't eat some foods that once were favorites. All this has amazed us.

Now, he will still go in sometimes before I do, but when he does he will leave for about an hour and lay on the couch in a dog bed, then come in. Moby has always been fearful. He was dumped or got lost at some point before he turned 1 and left to fend for himself. He must have been out there alone for a while because he was very emaciated and one giant skin infection from demodex when he was found. His body condition score was 1. Once he got healthy, he did well emotionally for awhile but over time he seemed to get worse. All of a sudden he was afraid of thunder, where he hadn't been before. Certain sounds would really seem to traumatize him, others that I thought would, didn't. Anyway, In the last 6 months his sensitivity to sound has gotten worse and the terror he feels from it can last for a very long time (Months). It seems like a panic attack or PTSD, and the feelings that were triggered seem to linger for a very long time. At the end of September He heard gunshots (or something that sounded like gunshots) that seemed to be pretty close. He was so terrified it broke my heart. He clearly panicked, and he would have fled if he could have. He's been traumatized ever since. He had been doing well when practicing his bravery before this happened. After that event we had to start over on trying to work on his bravery. He wouldn't step out of the garage at first. It's taken six weeks to get him to walk up and down our street.  I think he will be better able to be out in the world for longer periods of time if we keep just doing baby steps and if there are no more scary sounds . But since you can't always predict sounds, it will likely happen again. Poor guy.

"Over the past six months, Jack has seemingly become more vocal and anxious in the later afternoon evening. I think of it as ""doggie sundowners."" He will run into it as if his legs didn't do what they were supposed to.  He increasingly doesn't like eating at 8 am when he wakes up. I am often up before he is and need to wake him up. (he sleeps in my bed under the covers). The harder it is to wake him up, the less likely he is to eat that morning. He goes out, does potty, usually, and then goes through the food routine with my other two dogs - I make them sit before eating - Jack has decided he doesn't need to sit, so he stands and then walks over to his bowl - he then sniffs his food, stands in front of it for a bit, and then walks away. (Fromm's dry kibble with Grizzly Salmon oil and warm water). After his morning nap, he is ready to go out and then eat - usually around 10:30a -11a. In the evening, he gets a Tbsp of Nulo wet food on his kibble and does not miss a meal.   Increasingly he has been peeing in the house. He can just have been outside, and then 30 minutes later, be right next to me and go potty (usually when I am occupied doing something else). Luckily his urine and feces have little smell - I think because he eats healthy.   My father thinks he doesn't always see or recognize him, but I have not observed that behavior. I think there is a vision issue possibly, but he can be sound asleep and know I've left the room, showing up behind me shortly thereafter.    "
