He's more cautious about jumping (he was an amazing jumper) He's careful about going down steps He goes up steps slowly He slips; his hind legs slip out from under him He walks more stiffly, especially in the back legs. and his feet point outwards
It seems this summer she was more scared of storms than previously.  She was always scared of thunder, now she will hide when it starts raining, even with no thunder.
He seems to be a less destructive. He is a little calmer

Glenn is exactly the same as he was at 5 years old. He is his own dog. He doesn't wander aimlessly or seem confused. Glenn is razer sharp. He's always decided when he wants cuddles or he'll walk away. Any crumb of food - he finds. We now have a 5 month old white Shepard. Glenn wants to play, play, play. When he wants to wind down for the night he lets her know in no uncertain terms.

She seems a little bit slower to move out of my way.  She is sometimes lying in a place where I would have to carefully step around her. Until recently she would always be aware that she needed to move and would do so.. Now I have to ask her to move. When I do, she is a gets up immediately but is a little slow to move out of the way.  I wonder if she is a little bit confused or just slower moving.
Sometimes when she wants to go outside, rather than scratch the door, she gets turned around and faces the wall across from the door and scratches.

Izzy came to us about 4 months ago - she slept more during the daytime as puppies do and was much less confident to be exploring her new environment.  As she has gotten more mature and confident, she has become much more active (and vocal!)
No changes have occurred in the past 6 months
No, she still behaves as she did as a puppy. Very active and excitable, but willing to listen.
He decides if whatever he has to get up and move for is worth it or not.
Her thinking is fine. I broke my leg a couple of months ago and have not been able to walk her as much so she seems more needy but she has not changed cognitively.

Charlie has what we think is a good grasp of understanding language, and he seems to continue to learn new words. He emembers patterns that have stopped; for example, our letter-carrier who always brought treats retired,  and Charlie still gets excited when I get the mail.

he is coming up on his third birthday and second year with us.  Being deaf, he has had to learn how to communicate and I would say that he is better at reading our body language.  Our non-verbal communication has improved greatly.

She likes to get me up to do things more for her, like moving her bed so it's just right for her, or trying to go to the park.  She is moving better since she has lost some weight and runs and prances more.
Max spends more energy being right by me and constantly needing to be petted and wants more attention. Not a bad thing but he seems much more needy.
Possibly more attuned to our routines and behaviors.
Sight is going which I think makes her more apprehensive
He now takes steps (9) one at the time up from the yard instead of in two leaps.

My dog has Cushing's Disease and has had it for over a year so some of the responses I gave have to do with changes due to that disease.  The Cushing's causes him to be focused on food a lot of the time.  He does wander, also due to Cushing's, but doesn't do any of the other things in the questions.  With increasing weakness in his hind legs coupled with some arthritis in his spine his activity level, especially regards playing with toys, is much less than it was in the past.
No.  She has always ran in circles for no apparent reason, but does not appear age related.

In the past 6 - 9  months, Darwin has become more food motivated and demanding. After being trained at around age 4 , when we got him, he would sit patiently waiting until the release command to get up and go eat. Now, he sometimes gets up while we are preparing his food and must be told to go back to his pillow and wait . Once corrected he will remain on his pillow until told to go eat.

She us young.  She is still learning to interact with others - humans and other animals.  She thinks she is the center of the universe right now.  actively playing is what she looks forward to each day.  enjoys running with other dogs rather than leash walking

His nesting behaviors have increased. It used to be perhaps once or twice per month, but now is nearly daily. He gets very focused and involved in rearranging a blanket for up to 2 minutes and will then just walk away. If no blanket or sheet is available, he will dig at the carpet when the urge to nest strikes.  The other behavior change is that he has always slept soundly through the night, with occasional, expected position changes. But in the past 6 months he has gotten out of bed, left the bedroom to get a drink and go outside where he will wander around the yard for several minutes until I retrieve him. He then sometimes has some struggle settling again before he finally goes back to sleep. This behavior has been occurring 3-4 times per month over the past 5-6 months.

No. Luna is 9 so I expect some differences in how she does things, but there's nothing significant. She's gotten a little bit slower with age, but she can still outrun my mom's 3-year-old dog. That's really about it.

Darly has vastly decreased hearing and sight, therefore much of her attentiveness is diminished.  It is hard to tell how much of her behavior is because of the this, or because of cognitive decline .  She also has had 2 Vestibular attacks .   She has recently started daily Selegiline to see if this improves her attentiveness and lessens wandering and confusion issues.
Even with melatonin at night, she is often on and off of our bed one to four or more times without needing to go out (except once nightly).
wallie seems to have lost the spatial sense of where his nose ends; he often bumps it while turning around near or walking past objects.

Due to COVID we are home much more so things like mid-day walks are more prevalent. Prior to the pandemic he would always have an iron bladder while we are away at work with accidents rarely occuring.
The dog wants to sleep outside on the porch every night. This behavior starts a little after sundown.  He really has a strong opinion about it. I let him if it's not too cold .
Nothing I have noticed she is still active at home and day card

Mayhem was neutered last December.  Since then probably sleeps a little more, wants to eat more, relatively speaking for a Golden Retriever.  He still likes his walks, but is a little slower.  He still does some agility training, but isn't as energetic as he used to be.  He is still energetic about playing ball, but he doesn't catch it or trap it as well as he used to.  He used to be very good at keeping me from kicking the ball past him so his brother wouldn't get it.  Now I can sneak it past him on the ground, he doesn't move quite as quick as he used to.    Mayhem no really keeps a close eye on me, makes sure he is always near me.  Likes to beg more when one of us are in the kitchen.   There will be a new Golden retriever in the family in the next few months so we will see how he reacts to that.

Just started to bark at other dogs when she is riding in the car, window down. If other dog on leash walking with someone. Does not bark at dog if they are not on leash. I thought this was interesting.
she's more frequently asking for snacks throughout the day.

If I am outside doing something he will go back to the house under the porch to lay down or on top of the porch.  But before he would just stay there but probably because he would rather be laying down. He sometimes will lay down there if I am doing yard work or whatever.
She does not respond to verbal queues including her name most of the time. I.e., she rarely responds to verbal queues including her name; it seems as is she is losing her hearing.
He has been about the same for most of his life, from what I can tell.

He is going on 12yrs and I have noticed he has some days more active than others but since last year we have also brought a 4 yr old Husky (My sons dog) who also lives on the property in a separate building away from my house ) on our  5 acres Vineyard  and this has kept Myo more active and I think improved his aging. In the morning when he wants to go outside his first move is to bark and call his male friend down so they can socialize, mostly pissing matches and a little sniffing , later following each other around the vines.
Walker is more time sensitive, for afternoon treat, and later in afternoon his evening kibble. Easy to train in some areas, but very stubborn when it comes to obeying when outside.
He is more active now than 6 months ago
He seems slightly more disturbed by noises from outside (doorbell, other dogs etc.)
He has definitely matured.  He is still easily distracted by people or other animals but seems to be able to focus more readily on commands that are given.

Mote has achieved greater understanding of surroundings; clearly has improved understanding and awareness of her own behaviors, acceptable/non-acceptable; major growth in vocabulary that she understands.  Mote's cognitive growth continues and we work daily to support this.
Typical puppy development, with rapid pattern learning (commands, routines, games)
Rufus has never been a deep-thinker :) Fortunately he has other charms. But his information processing is about the same as it always has been.

Jamie is a very hyper and anxious dog. He never stays still and will pace as he is bored with the space we are in. We  recently moved from a house to an apartment and did notice some changes in behavior (more anxious, unhappy with the size of the room, barking).
Difficulty sleeping. Does not want to be touched or petted. Very afraid of grooming. Stares like she is lost very often

She does seem to be more anxious, particularly with unrecognized sounds like shuffling cards. She seems more hypervigilant, looking out the window for objects that move like squirrels, people, raccoons, etc.

I have not observed any changes in Ellie Rose.  She has never walked in circles or looked at walls.  I do think that during the last 9-10 months our activity has increased.  I take her and her brother, Charlie, on walks every day!  Our goal is at least three miles.  This does not include the time that she has been able to get outside in her yard because Mom(s) have been home so much...due to the pandemic...
I've been working from home since mid-March so I've spent most of every day with my dog. He's always wanted to be near me and now he sleeps in a basket at my feet while I work.

She is learning how to interact with our toddler and his evolving behaviors. She is realizing when he is showing he wants to play roughly and to avoid those interactions and when he will give gentle attention.

She seems to be more alert on some nights after she has gone to bed. With that behavior she goes to door to yard and barks - a distinctive bark that says she wants out. Sometimes it is to pee or defecate but often to race around the yard ( it has a double lot chain linked 5 ft fence) and bark or just race. We are rural with a large area beyond fence that has deer and other animals in it. she cannot get into that area. We are not really thrilled with this behavior as it gets us up to let her out and then within 5 min. let her back in.
No, but a note on the wall staring-is because our other dog is reactive, so Ezri stares at the wall to avoid eye contact that will set him off.
Leroy seems more indifferent towards us. Other than his routine outside time, he doesn't seem to care if we play with him or not. He could be bored with us since we are WFH and with him almost 24/7.

We recently moved to a dense urban area (Paris) for 2 months and Sophie clearly misses nature -- at home she swims in the ocean or the lake, she runs on grass and in the woods, and we go for long hikes.  She's less enthusiastic to go out -- and I am too.

My old girl and Scout's housemate, Mo was put down in late August. She was 15years, 8 months old, and having lots of problems navigating and going about her day. I called it doggy dementia, the vet called it senility. Since then, I realized how often Scout looked to her for cues in unfamiliar situations. He's learning to live without her guidance, and I'm learning to live without her presence.
Meech has become much more anxious. We are considering putting him on Prozac.

We were playing with a toy recently and after walking away for a second, she seemed to forget what game we were playing. She started sniffing wildly as if looking for something, but walked right over the toy in the process.

He sometimes gets focused on a certain area of the yard, like he has found a bug or something, but there is nothing there.  He will maintain this focus over a period of several days.  I will have to carry him into the house but the next time he will make a bee-line for the same place.
Georgi is the same lovable dog who is less active on a walk due to a recent diagnosis of arthritis in both hips.
He currently is stable and has been since the beginning of this year (11 months).

Less inclined to do annoying behaviors on walks, such as try to attack and knock over garbage cans, or lunge at vehicles that make a lot of noise, such as trucks. He is somewhat less overly hyperalert.

No Poppy is pretty consistent other than because she has her whole pack (i.e. my whole family rather than just me) at home due to online schooling and working, she is loving having more people to give her attention during the day!  She's a cuddle monster :)
She will come to us for attention and do a stretch, then walk away, then come back a few moments later.
Her vision is starting to go and I think that has had an effect on her.
Trico's thinking and information processing has remained stable in the past 6 months.  He is a goofy, sweet, derpy, doggo.

She is getting older, can not catch treats in the air as much. She does not like noise or romping as much. less tolerant of noise or play.  a little grumpy sometimes
Ruby is not as insecure as she was as a younger dog (so in the last 6 to 12 months).  She used to tear up her dog bed or pillows if we left her alone in the house.  She no longer does this.
really his cognition is the same, please note he has been trained to focus me not the food hence he does not easily pick up dropped food unless given the ok command.

"Wall-E has become a little more affectionate, allowing us to sit next to him on the couch and actually lying down on our laps, relaxed. There has been an increase in resource guarding from the other dog in the house.

"Anja tries to figure out how to elicit treats with behaviors she has been taught.  She has figured out how to push doors open and whether outside sounds are meaningful -  barking vs not barking. he's developed a little separation anxiety when one of us leaves for short periods. he is a little more sensitive to our moods and emotions. he likes sleeping in and snuggling as the weather gets colder. he's very affectionate when people come to the house (which is much less frequent than pre-pandemic)

We have not seen any changes in his ability to process information or think. However, Stitch is motivated by training treats or Mintie chewy bones.  He loves to do tricks. Stitch has been trained to sit, stay and wait to eat his dinner each day.  His dinner bowl is placed in front of him on the floor. He waits patiently, he will sit, shake and kiss (lick my hand) then he is  told Ok which means time for dinner.  Stitch is very active and loves to play fetch.

No, she is a young dog and her behavior is the same as it was six months ago

She recently went deaf, and now sometimes just sits and barks.  She doesn't seem to want anything (have interrupted her barking to offer food/attention/comfort which are usually accepted but do not stop the barking), and is just trying to hear herself bark is my best guess.
He is definitely getting smarter and more mature, although he still, occasionally, will shred a pair of flip-flops or a small item like a writing pen.
She is less excitable (less barking/licking) when people return home after being gone for a few hours
She seems more eager to learn more as we intentionally work on getting her to be more active (as the weather gets worse in the PNW, we have to get more creative about being active indoors)

None that I can think of.  She's perhaps a bit more jumpy, (i.e. smaller noises will make her jump up and start barking looking for an invader) but wouldn't say that was over the last 6 months, but more maybe over the last couple of years.    Her sensitivity to thunder / loud noises is getting a bit higher, (this one perhaps over the last year or so - could be the last couple of years) and actually now includes a predictive element, so she now knows that if the sky's getting darker, the winds are picking up and the rain is starting to increase, she sometimes starts going into the bathroom, (the place where she tries to hide from thunder) before thunder has even started, but other than that, wouldn't say that she's shown any real changes in cognitive abilities.  You still have to be careful with new words you say around her, and now often have to spell them backwards, as she keeps learning how to spell, even new words.  That's not to say she doesn't still do stupid things sometimes, (she is a Lab, after all, and has been doing both surprisingly smart and amazingly stupid things since she was a puppy) but she definitely continues to show the smarter side she has, as well.
Addie sleeps much more.  At times she will bark at me for what seems no reason.  I decided she has a reason I just can't figure it out. She still processes information just fine.
She has a set routine for the day and keeps us on schedule!
Only that he seems more engaged with us and interested in life than ever
More aware of, and annoyed by squirrels in and around the yard. Barks more and wants to chase people passing by or in neighbors yard.

Tundra is getting smarter. We train daily when walking or interacting with other people/dogs.  For example, while walking Tundra's now about 80 - 90% correct with these directions:  forward, right, left.   Recently she's exhibited some resource guarding (of sticks) at dog parks.  I wanted to nip this in bud right away.  A trainer suggested I trade a  'drop' or 'let go' with a 'sit' for a treat.   She's 100% in our yard.  We haven't been to the dog park much lately but the few times she was nearly 100% (with balls) there were no sticks to practice with at the time.
She occasionally has not slept in our bed. Use to be 100%, past month 85%.

She licks the living room rug sometimes
no - she just turned two years old so she is calming down a bit but still very smart and enjoy's problem solving.
Wants more affection but he has been pretty affectionate since I got him there is a slight increase.
No real differences in behavior versus 6 months ago
She's communicating well using buttons ala the Fluent Pet, which has greatly reduced her frustrations when we don't understand what she's asking for.
No other changes Hikes, friendly all cognitive issues are fine
Pandemic has meant fewer and shorter walks and family outings

Less social interaction and exercise due to COVID. She is hyper to begin with and now even more so. Prior on walks she would be out front pulling, now she is going in 6 directions at once, tangling leashes with the other two.

Since adopting Ocean, Callahan is more needy and vocal about having attention.  He was not this way prior to Ocean, when it was just Callahan and our other dog, Nina, whom we had prior to Callahan and who passed away in May.

He is very intelligent, as verified by his trainers.  He's almost a two year old Golden Retriever.  All necessary shots  Have been given.  His only illness has been an ear infection.  He has a wonderful disposition, and doesn't suffer from separation anxiety.  As are most Goldens, he's very calm and not anxious, territorial.  He does bark at other dogs
Lulu used to be able to chase down and kill squirrels.  Now she has difficulty killing them but she can still catch them.  We do not discourage this behavior as on our farm squirrels are a nuisance.

Tula is very smart and sharp.  She has a fairly small muzzle, so her sense of smell probably isn't as keen as that of a retriever, but she is still a skilled hunter and she is as fast as greased lightning.
We've actually been more active since the pandemic started!
She tries to attack people. With her training, mostly e-collar, now she whines and comes to sit next to me.
Sean's mental capacities are the same. However, as he ages his dysplasia becomes more painful and he is consciously limited vigorous exercise. He is still a very happy boy.

"Mishka was rescued from a puppy mill so she is actually getting much better & more confident. He seems more depressed now that his people are going back to work and school.
At times she will stay still while the door is open to go outside and just waits.
She whimpers at bed time if I don't pet her or show her affection.
Beckett only circles when I put his RuffWear Web Master harness on him before car rides.  He hates the harness but I make him wear it as part of the seat belt system I use in the car.
He's very intelligent and aware of his surroundings. He seems to understand most things and sometimes responds in his way.
Her arthritis slows her down, some days are better than others.

Since we are home all the time now, instead of visiting schools and hospitals as a Pet Therapy team, we are significantly less active. She clearly misses that people interaction.  I still take her out for long walks, but she'd be just as content if I stayed home instead.

I understand this refers to past 6-months but I as Cowboy is now 3-yo I would like to report a few trends I've seen in him as he has aged. He used to be very calm when traveling in a car. He still begs to go for rides but once the car is moving he becomes agitated, panting whimpering, and barking/lunging at passing cars if not crated. When he is in his crate he scratches incessantly at the bottom of the crate and licks. He has also become much more protective of the car and of his home. His difficulty with recognizing people he knows happens if they are wearing a hat or are with others who are strangers to him.
Taz is getting smarter, learning new tricks very quickly.
She is stable in this area

seems a little more anxious when I leave her alone. Now she gets on the bed when I'm at work, she never used to do that. She is not allowed on furniture.  Also, if I go over to the neighbors house without her and she sees me, she wails and howls. She even tried to climb out a window a few months ago to get to me. Otherwise, she never makes vocal sounds of any kind.

"Lorel seems to have learned that she does not always get her way and does not throw a tantrum or try to make her choice, the only choice. She has learned patience. We felt the behavior was a sign of immaturity. If she wanted to take a path in the woods and we said, no, we go this way today, she would have a tantrum. (The path might be flooded after a rain.) She would first try to pull away but is on a leash on long walks. When that didn't work, she seemed to know that running the leash around our legs would trip us. Wow. She learned that she could snap a leash in seconds with her teeth and free herself so her leashes need to be thick material. Finally, she would give a long nasty stare at us and try to bolt away. She would run about 8 feet, come to a screeching halt and stare back at us. Then she would run at top speed at us, swerve at the last second, grab Lacey's harness (her 6 pound dog housemate) in her mouth and run full speed away from us with Lacey curled up and dangling from her mouth. If she was running away, she was going to take Lacey with her and leave us. That would scare Lacey. Lacey did not want to go on walks with Lorel for months. She would hide under a pillow and visibly shiver when the word 'walk' was mentioned. Lorel has finally started to not seem so self centered and will take an instruction that she might not be 100% happy with. ""No, today, this way."" She is less self centered than she was. A mature, good change. "

He is less frenetic, although still much more active and distractible than our previous huskies at this age. He seems more like a 9-12 month old than a 3 year old. But, the good news is that he can now greet people without jumping up (whew!), so there's progress.

As a high energy herding dog, Jojo easily spots patterns that end in play time.  It only took her a week to anticipate frisbee time after my wife and I finished working out.  Now with every workout I do, she's anticipating playing when we finish.  Not sure it's going to be easy breaking that when the weather turns.

Since working remotely started (March 2020) Mellow now spends his time in the basement bedroom sleeping, which surprised me.  He used to keep watch out the master bedroom watching the driveway and street but now prefers the dark, no view, quieter space to nap and relax during the day.  I realize he enjoys the quiet and not getting interrupted by my constant sounds and bopping around the house.  He turned 10 on Wednesday so I guess this is one of his first aging changes I have noticed.

Jabooty is 14 yrs old now and is starting to slow down.  She sometimes has a bit of a tremor and she falls down, meaning her legs splay out.  She pops right back up though.  I'm unsure if it just weakness or neurological.  I believe that this has slowed down her thinking and information processing a bit.
Frodo sometimes goes into the living room looking for the other dogs and doesn't seem to realize that they have already gone outside. I also think his hearing is worse.
Slightly less exciteable, however still high energy and anxiety
I have not, things seem the same.
None. Lilly Bee remains in full form!
"Cali is currently a ""young"" Golden Retriever which we attribute to having a 5 year old ""sister"" that keeps her curious and active."
Recently, when inside the house Peach seems to bark and growl more at sounds heard faintly in the distance outside.

She has become protective of Ernie, our 11 yr. old Golden who has a hip displacement. She considers herself a human, she knows she is not allowed on the furniture, but takes over the middle of our bed and thinks nothing of climbing up on top of you while watching tv. We have 3 acres of woods and she knows every inch of it and is seen running all over whenever she hears or sees something. It is her...showing responsibility for what  is hers and her family.
None at all.  He is sharp as a tack.  I have had a dog with dementia brought on my cancer that had metastasized to his brain.

"Our dog has what I call ""episodes"" with no recognizable triggers.  He's had these since he was 1 year old or so.  These most often happen in the middle of the night, but sometimes during the day, and can last for hours.  He becomes restless & scared & clingy.  He often hyperventilates.  He cannot settle & be still, pacing, wanting to be right on top of me or my husband, or on top of our pillows & heads.  If we are up & about, such as cooking, he will be right under our feet.  His behavior in these episodes is very unusual.  His usual behavior is to be close by or snuggle peacefully.  He is not normally clingy, restless, and anxious.  "

Up till 6 months ago Eaton would get into the car by jumping up to the seat (SUV), now he has chosen on his own to jump into the floorboard and then jump onto the seat.  Likewise when getting out of the car he used to jump out from the seat.   Now he chooses to step down to the floorboard and then jump out of the car from there.  This behavior change was his choice.
"He seems less confident to venture out on his own and more likely to stay close to his humans. He also barks more at people and animals walking by or in ""his"" yard."

Scout seems to really pay attention to the television! She will watch the screen for several minutes at a time, often reacting with a bark when animals appear on screen.  She continues to get better with having her feet touched. As a puppy, she would run away at the site of a towel to wipe her feet. Now when we need to wipe her feet, she will stand still and allow the towel to touch her paws without any problems.   She still continues to run away at night when her back legs/paws are touched. For example, she jumped into bed last night, I pet her back hip and right away she jumped off the bed.
Our other dog died. We had him 15 months. Izzy at times would not eat would walk slow on a walk. In 6 weeks we got another rescue dog and Izzy is back to herself

No.  She is active, alert and plays like a puppy.  She can still jump on the bed, go on hind legs & dance. Sit.  Follows commands with eyes, no words.  Listens do words she knows.  Remembers.  Knows her 'people'

The length of time between going outside to urinate or defecate have shortened. It was 2.5 hours and now it is 1.5-2 hours. He seems more affectionate and seems to want to sleep next to me or my husband (he sleeps in bed with us). Six months ago he would sleep at the foot of the bed. His tolerance of our other dog (a 1.5 year cairn terrier female Lilly) is deceasing. She tries to nuzzle him and lay next to him and to play with him and he tries to get away from her. Six months ago he would tolerate some interaction. HIs sleeping is deeper and longer - once he has his walk after dinner (about 6 pm) he goes to sleep on the sofa and stays asleep until we go to bed about 11 pm. Now it is difficult to get him to start the walk and he isn't always able to finish it - we put him into a dogger cart to start the walk and then he indicates when he is ready to get out and walk. Not in the last 6 months, but something dramatic in September 2019.  He is intact, had been going to daycare for play, always acting comfortable and confident around other dogs.  Something happened: his trainer thinks either he was attacked or near an attack on another dog.  Daycare is silent about what happened.  From that point on, Odysseus has been reactive and shown fear around other dogs. "Frankly, I haven't observed changes in Jasmine's thinking or information processing.  She wouldn't think of soiling inside, she has her own ""potty spot"" behind our shed which she uses. She doesn't always welcome being reached for by strangers.    The question about being active is hard to say because it depends greatly on my day.  She's allowed to go out and roam and sniff which she does on most days.  She's learned to stay out of the road and doesn't cross the street without permission so she has a large territory. We have many acres of woods behind our house which she explores at times.    However, I'm a psychologist who used to have her work with me.  On the three days when I still work, now on Zoom, rather than go out, she often chooses to lie at the top of the stairs where my clients used to come in.  I think she misses her ""work"" a lot.  Until last March, as soon as I told her it was time for work, where ever she was, she headed right into my office.  Now she sleeps through most of my sessions.  But she love to play frisbee, which we do two or three times per day as well as take at least a two mile walk.  "

High cognitive function. It is my belief she paces because she is bored, and we probably do not walk or exercise her as much as we should.

"I let my wife write these first comments. They're about the indoor Chloe. I'll finish with the outdoor Chloe (I walk her and let her out into our fenced in city lot which is 37 1/2 feet wide by 150 feet long).    Chloe is no longer affectionate. She never wants to cuddle. She either doesn't want to obey or she doesn't understand the command. She is almost completely deaf. She still responds to hand signals most of the time for Sit & Down but only occasionally for Come. Chloe's on pain medication (rimadyl) but it isn't completely effective. She has always had the ""shakes"" on and off, but she shakes more than previously. She isn't as happy as she used to be. Her tail was always up and now it's often curled under. She still plays but not much. She always caught the ball (or stuffed animal) and always brought it back for another throw. Now she seems confused and doesn't really know what to do with it. Chloe doesn't really know how to play anymore. Sometimes she still gets excited and races back and forth in the house which is great. She hasn't lost all her mojo.   When she's outside in the yard she has a routine that she has done for years. She checks the complete perimeter of the yard, pretty much in the same pattern depending on if she let out the front or the back door. There are many birds, squirrels and rats in the yard. Plus an occasional faction, opossum, or rabbit. She just killed her 49th rat last week. She was alone in the backyard  . I took the garbage out and as I walked by her she was exhibiting an indoor behavior that I haven't seen her do outside. She was just staring at our building's  brick wall. She's always very active outside. Even if it's only walking  around and smelling everything. When I returned from my trip to the garage there was a dead rat right where she had been standing. It had the bruised back and fresh blood on its ear. She always has shaken the prey until it stops steeling and then drops it and walks away. She has in the passed, if we weren't present for the kill, brought the kill over to us and dropped at our feet and then just walked away. Our garbage cans are kept in a cared area next to our garage and neat the alley many kills have happened in this area over the years when she is outside and I am within her sight she'll stand at the gate and look back at me to see if I'm coming to open the gate. But now when I let her into that rather large area that she use to completely explore, she'll just run to the furthest point and then turn around and run passed me back into the yard as I'm still standing at the gate. It's like a routine she has to do as part of her outdoor mission.  When we go for a walk it's to the park directly across our street.  I used to walk her on heel, off leash for years. She would play fetch returning the ball as fast as she chased it and the opening her mouth releasing the ball as she made a U-turn and the ball would roll forward to my feet. I would field it and could barely out throw her as she fielded it and ran back repeating the process for throw after throw. Now she has almost no interest in the ball at all. Because of her lack of hearing, everything she does revolves around smelling. About six months ago she might return the ball two or three times before being distracted by some smell. She'd drop the ball wherever she was and not return it at all over those months her fetch instincts have completely disappeared. She won't chase the ball anymore. There is a fenced in dog park in the main park. We used to play fetch in there also. In the summer I set up a wading pool for the use of the dogs a hose was attached to the side of the pool near the top of the sidewall and a drain was placed near the bottom of the sidewalk 180 degrees away. The hose was outfitted with a shut off valve and a quick release mechanism. If we were there alone or with just a dog or two with their owners I would release the hose and cast the water onto the asphalt pavement, into the pool, out of the pool on the other side, back into the pool, out of the pool and on and on and on. Meanwhile, Chloe would be hot on the hunt chasing the water jumping into and out of the pond. She had lost interest by the end of thi summer after about seven years of thi activity. She was never very interested in the other dogs or people but liked some of both and tolerated the others. The last couple of times I took her into the fenced in area she stood by the gate trying to leave on her own when other people came in. She eventually learned to squeeze her way through the wrought iron fencing that surrounds the enclosure. After escaping twice into the larger park area I stopped bringing her into the dog park. We have a routine. I walk der on leash until we come to the dog park fence and then I let her off leash and she walks in the ""parkway"", a grassy area between the public sidewalk and the street. She sniffs, pees, sniffs, pees, sniffs, eventually poops and continues to sniff. She walks in the parkway at her own pace and I walk on the sidewalk for about 1000 feet. We the renter the park and she sniffs her way around one side of the park about 2000 feet and then when I catch her eye I lift my hand and she'll sit. I'll put her on leash and walk her home. She can here a loud clap but doesn't always obey the following waving come command. "

Now, she will try to visually find it first by trying different observation angles (look under the couch, behind the tv, go upstairs to look over the railing downstairs, go up/down different steps to try that vantage point...etc.) When ""seeing"" the ball fails, I tell her to ""use you nose"". She will then proceed to sniff and eventually find the ball. "
Casey was recently put on medicine for hypothyroid and Carprosen for arthritis which has made her more active and social.

A few times a week he gets super excited and starts going a little bit crazy barking repeatedly at our other dog, and dodging around biting at him (not intending to hurt). We think he is trying to get the other dog to play, but sometimes it seems overly aggressive because he really won't stop and he won't respond to our commands. We sometimes wonder if he is jealous of the other dog and trying to get our attention.

"Both of our kids are now in college, so he seems a little lonely or sad. He is less physically active now, because they spend a lot of time playing with him and taking him places when they are here. But cognitively, he seems to be getting better at understanding our words and communicating his wants with yawns, sneezes, paw, ""follow me."""
She yodels when she's happy.  It's a specific sound, only heard when she's particularly happy usually when we arrive home or it's almost dinner time.
He seems more anxious and is unable to settle.  He is less reactive to noises.

"Rosie is remarkably ""young"" for her age. Maybe it's because she's the smallest dog we have had, but she is in phenomenal shape, loves being active, and still seems very puppy-like in many ways. She has always been a little out there -- kind of Asperger-y in certain respects -- but in all the ways that she is sharp, she remains as sharp as a  tack."

The problem she has always exhibited it when I throw a ball, she is so excited that she doesn't watch where it lands.  I have taught her to search for it by going back and forth over the ground. She finds it but not always.  This has been an issue since I adopted her at around 2 years old.  She gets so excited over balls she cannot focus. I cannot seem to change that behavior.
She is getting smarter as expected for a 1.5 year old corgi
Once in awhile he appears confused, like he wants to go out, then he doesn't. He will go out, but then just stand in the yard.
He's starting to calm down a bit from his puppy behaviors.
We have noticed that Milva has accumulated a large vocabulary and is, at this point, still quite trainable.  She is able to do some tricks that she wasn't performing six months ago.

We have a sneaking suspicion that Capone's hearing may be going. He is usually very attentive around feeding time, but at least a couple times a week we find that we have to get his attention before he realizes we have opened the back door to let him in for chow time. We have also observed that if we put the food down before letting him in he gets confused and doesn't know where to look for his food, even though the bowls have not changed location and even though his sister dog is eating right next to his bowl.

"I think it may take a bit longer for his eyes to adjust when we move from a brightly lit area to a low light area, based on my observation. But if I give him 30-60 sec that seems to do the trick. I don't think this is a cognition issue; rather, based on a conversation with my veterinarian, it probably has more to do with aging eyes (I can relate, since my ophthalmologist recently told me I have ""baby cataracts"" !!)"

About 3 months ago (after she turned 1) she started this restless behavior at night of scratching at the wood floor or wall while the family is relaxing. Pretty consistently between 8-10 pm and she's chill before and after that. She will redirect to certain treats or playing fetch but is not typically interested in toys at these times.

He barks at nothing, just lying on the ground looking at the front door.  Not to go out, but like he is seeing or hearing something, even though he is almost completely deaf.  He also stands next to our horse and barks non-stop at her, even though she is just standing there.

He has ceased relying on auditory input entirely and has begun processing input from his other senses much more. He has begun cuing off my other dog's responses when he sees, feels, and presumably smells a difference in posture or attention.
We've been spending more time together because of Covid.  Before, i would be gone for 3 to 6 hours day when she would be alone, now we're together basically 24/7.
Just getting slower, has more skin tags and bumps growing

No, though the pandemic has him wanting to go on more walks (because I'm working from home!) I am also 15 weeks pregnant. I noticed a change in his behavior (became more protective and stays near to me) than before I was pregnant.
Her vision is clearly getting worse. She will bark at anyone that walks into the house until she's close enough to to see or smell them.
She plays more with our other dog, who is a puppy (1 year old)
The same as6months ago why I said same

No significant changes in behavior in the past 6 months.
Through the Covid shutdown he has become much more attached to me. The good side is because I'm home more we walk numerous times a day. Average 30-40 min @ a time.
Since the beginning of the pandemic he does seem to be more excitable when a visitor enters our house.
Evelyn seems fine, no changes in thinking or information processing

Avery is a little more insecure/anxious than she used to be.   Sometimes it seems related to the indoor cat's unpredictable behavior (just being cats playing, not necessarily interacting with Avery). Molly will bark when she hears someone coming up to door but as soon as she sees the person (whether she knows them or not) she is wagging her tail and wanting to be petted
Tar appears to be handling cognition and training exercises and activities as well as she ever has
No she's still very on point with what I ask of her.
No she is the same active puppy.
he's a playful little puppy who loves to eat!

Well she's only 16 months old, so she's gone through a lot of normal maturing that you would expect. More self-control and focus, and the ability to chill out in the moment because she knows we'll do something exciting later.
Yes, Hitchcock has become fearful on the same 4 mile loop in the woods that we have been doing his entire life. He is very fearful of loud noises not, even unrelated to gunfire.

Giovanni has unlimited access outside and uses a doggie door. Within the past few months, even though he has just gone outside, he will come inside and suddenly turn around and run back outside. Initially we thought that maybe he had to relieve himself or wasn't feeling well. As we continued to observe him, to see what he was doing with such urgency to run immediately back outside, we saw that he would just go outside and stand out there without any agenda or purpose.
6 months ago she wasn't afraid of anything, like to her detriment. Lately she has more typical fear of noises and large moving objects.
Spark is 7 years old. She has never been particularly energetic. She is less energetic than other dogs of this age that I've lived with, but her behavior hasn't changed in the last six months.

Moose was recently hospitalized and diagnosed with Immune-mediated thrombocytopenia (ITP).  He is on quite a few drugs - one if which (prednisone) has a side effect of excessive thirst and urination.  Prior to this he had never urinated in the house, however he did have a few accidents when he initially came home from the hospital.

If anything, Lucy is slightly more alert/sensitive to sounds/smells such as vehicles she is not familiar with going by the house or a new dog that has moved into the neighborhood. There is ongoing construction in our neighborhood, so there is an increased amount of noise from the construction vehicles, etc., as well as new neighbors moving in - and bringing their dogs!
We moved to a new house 3 months ago, seemed to take her a while to get comfortable with it. She was scared at first when left alone but has gotten more comfortable.
He is gradually calming down as the years pass, but still anxious.

At his current age (1yr), the main difference I have seen from when he was 6mo old is that he has more experiences to draw on when he has new encounters, and is physically bigger and slightly more mature and confident. So while he sometimes is still distrusting of new things (like Halloween decorations), he is less spooked (no pun intended) about them than he would've been at 6mo of age and is able to get over them faster.
He is sleeping a little more during the day but from late afternoon on wants to spend all the time outside hunting. Most likely summer heat related.
Luna has developed more & listens better than she did 6 months ago
Since my husband started working from home she has become MUCH more attached to him and is upset when he goes out for even an hour.

Frequent barking through the day.  Pawing at closed doors, barking and expecting the household to rise when she does .  Attention getting- pawing at knitting baskets, pulling out books from book shelves etc to get a response. Through the night, pacing, scratching and panting. Stubborn behaviour in walks.

My other dog passed away within the last six months and I do feel like Carlos was sad for a while. A little less interested in playing and more time just laying around being sleepy but he seems to have bounced back. He also seems more clingy, he already was my little shadow but it's like he always wants me to be touching/petting him.
She has not shown any changes
We have had our 6year old twin grandkids living with us over the past 8 months.  Tank is always ready to fetch run and play.  People are surprised to hear he is 8!

"She would bark for no reason, particularly at night.  This, along with acting confused overall, was reported to the vet  at her last check up. Just moved 5 months ago from a 3-story townhouse to a 2-story home with a yard and nice neighborhood to walk in. She is interested in getting to know her surroundings and has been able to be outside more.
She doesn't like to play with treat puzzle as much as before. Has a harder time completing task. One puzzle requires batting at object which she either can't do or can't remember how to do.
He has always been very needy for affection and it seems like even more lately.
nothing to share Jasper is doing great!
Since giving him his Cosequin, and changing his good he seems perkier.

She has not shown any issues with thinking or information processing. She only runs into things when she gets going to fast and can't stop in time. Being a Newfoundland, they can't stop on a dime, they are much like semi-trucks in their ability to speed up and slow down.

He was having difficulty with stairs.  He fell a few times.  I was concerned that he couldn't do the stairrs.  He is afraid to go down still, but I have retaught him to go up the stairs.  There is a slight turnin the stairs and he gets scared at that pont.  I put my fingers under his harness to let him know I am there to spot him and he seems to be doing fine going up steps now.

No changes, but I want to point out that temperature affects  activity level, so that 6 months ago in July Opie's activity level was depressed during the day due to temperature. She seems to be a little less active now in December, but because she's active throughout the day, overall activity levels are similar. Comparing evening activity levels, she's slightly less active now than 6 months ago.
He seems to have difficulty sometimes finding me. He is always at my side.

His left eye has discharge and I believe he no longer sees well with that eye. I believe that may contribute to some of his changing behaviors.  Since the weather has cooled he is far more active than he was 6 months ago when it was hot
I have not seen any change in Benny from the last six months.
Sleeps later in the morning doesn't get out of bed till noon but plays outside more

No. he doesn't have any of these clinical signs...yet, at least!

temporarily unable to hear for a few days, therefore was less responsive to auditory cues.
My dog is still pretty young (four) and seems very sharp mentally. I haven't noticed any behavioral changes from her recently.

We determined it to be behavioral and tried numerous calming remedies but to no avail.  Now that he's the only canine in the household, he's stopped drinking to excess.  So I don't know if it was ""nervous"" or competitive or what but surprisingly it stopped."

"Marnie is a ""rescue"" (e.g., she was a breeding bitch that could not have any more litters so was of no value to breeder) and was used to being in a small cage 20+ hours a day. Not really.  She is getting more attached to us and asks to be petted more

Dog is gets more walks and is up and about more than he was 6 months ago.  I am now home with him during the day because I work from home most of the time due to COVID-19.  He gets a lot more walks and spends a lot more time outdoors in the yard.

She has been going through a bunch of training and has really calmed down and gotten into a routine so she is less hyper and crazy than she was. She is now a very well-behaved little lady with just the occasional bout of crazyness when she doesn't get a proper amount of exercise.

"So, Laker just turned 5 months today, but I'll try to answer this to the best of my ability. I adopted Laker at 8+ weeks. Since that time, he spends less time sleeping (though, still sleeping about 16 hours per day with overnight plus naps) and he's much more active than he was at 8+weeks of age. He is a quick learn and house training was a breeze with less than 5 ""accidents"" in the house. We went to puppy class, puppy agility class and puppy swim class and he learned new commands/activities with ease. We're still working on walking on the leash without tugging. But when I take him off leash, he comes back on command.  At times, I can see Laker ""sorting things out"" in his head. When he hears barks or other animal noises on the TV his head will pop up and he'll look at the screen trying to 'sort things out'. At other times, he will simply calmly sit and observe me. Oh yes, he gets the zoomies, but I can usually calm him. If things get really crazy he goes into the crate for 3 - 5 minutes and that calms him down. "
She is becoming more and more clingy. Every time we turn around we almost trip over her as she has started following us more and more.
He is much less active in his old age and it has gotten worse recently .
Zola is still so quick to learn new tricks

Not that I can think of at the moment

She's too smart for her own good. I used high value treats to make trades with her when she had something she wasn't supposed to have, like a sock. Now she seeks out things she shouldn't have, brings them and shows them to me, then promptly walks to where her treats are, spits out the item and sits. She looks at the item in the floor, looks at the treats, then looks at me. And will repeat until given a treat or is told no and shooed out of the room.

Aside from the rare time she cannot control her bowels, usually after eating too many treats from neighbors, rabbit poop or other crow dropping outside on walks, or begged for table scraps which she rarely get due to changes in her diet cause her loose stool, Sawyer is about the same. He has slowed down a bit with age, but is still alert and on top of things.  He used to be the top dog (alpha?) but has happily relinquished that spot to my 18 month old English Cocker.

Started relieving her self in house

He studies his leap into the back of the car more than he used to.

He continued this behavior for a few weeks, on and off, then stopped completely. I'm not sure what triggered either the onset or the ending of this behavior. I do know that he's unhappy when I leave him and thrilled when I return, but it seems that's the only time he's been destructive.
He is a bit of an idiot but his cognitive function is perfectly normal for a 4 yr old dog.

While eating...  sometimes he eats whole bowl at once, other times he stands over the bowl and seems entirely not interested.  will lick his food, but takes up to a half hour to eat whole bowl, occasionally not eating at all.  His entire life, he has been fed twice a day and at all food right away.

Since we are home pretty much all the time, I do think he is even more attuned to our moods and habits.  Although we have 5 dogs, he was one of two that stayed home all day on a regular basis, so he is more active these days.

Slightly more responsive to get into the car but often jumps back out right away if the door is not closed- 6 months ago we had to force him, lift him with him often becoming nervous and growling.

She is aging slowly and having more difficulty getting around because she had a bad rear hip.  She sleeps a great deal of the time.  Every once in a while we have to help her up, she struggles to get up on her own, but most of the time can still get up on her own.
As both of us have gone back to work, and Sadie is no longer crating, she recgonizes the behaviors that indicate we are getting ready to leave, and she will go get in bed.
He is happier, more affectionate,  and more eye contact.

Cocco started wandering into neighbors yards to explore more than his usual pattern of exploring within the bounds of our yard and electric fense.  We stopped using his electronic collar after he had his episode of larynx paralysis, but until recently, he continued to stay within our yard.

"My dog has physically aged quite a bit in the past six months, and it seems to surprise her when she can't do the same things or when she gets sore from an activity.  Like when she gets the zoomies and falls down, she gets a look like ""why did that happen?""  "
Maisie gets excited about going outside and acts like she needs to go to the bathroom. Then when she gets outside, she often just stands there and acts as though she doesn't know why she is there.

Nothing at all other than sleeping more

I was in the hospital with surgery and recovery so her decrease in activity is as a result of me being less active and covid.

Scout's activity level hasn't changed much in the past 6 months, he pretty much sleeps most of the day and does get excited for walks.  Outside of that, he is not very active.

My dog is a 5.5 month old puppy.  She is learning every day and her activity level will increase as a matter of getting older.

He's suddenly gotten more anxious/aggressive when witnessing physical OR verbal conflicts between people, and is likely to nip at who he sees as the aggressor. He hadn't bit since he was a puppy. And often, he will even interpret physical affection between two people as aggression and jump to the defense, especially if one person is leaning over the other or if they've fought (even verbally) recently."

Just a couple of months ago he started playing the piano...  Just kidding.   We haven't noticed many changes in the last 6 months with one exception.  We had family in town and needed to send him to the kennel.  For two nights after he returned he would wander around the house in the middle of the night.  From the third night fwd he has been sleeping as usual, but he hadn't ever shown that pacing behavior before. -  Thanks

"He learns or thinks he has learned our routine more and more--expected times to go out...When I am leaving to work vs. working around house (based on clothing/shoe changes I think). No zoomies at night but, still gets more ""active-attention"" needy just before he falls asleep.  Very chew-needy during this time of day.  Can have some stuffed animals now that he mouths but now holds back from opening up and trying to eat. Plops down like he has no bones after his longer (2 mile) evening walk, but ready to go again about ten minutes later.  Seems to get worn out by smells and human interactions equally well as from physical exercise.  Much more calm in meet and greet situations and visitors to house and overall--but still does occasional bursts of running loops and zig zags around yard like a ghost is chasing him. "

Fenris has never been big on being petted -- he mostly wants to retrieve all the time. But he has actually become somewhat more willing to be petted since we got our puppy, so maybe he needs to be reassured that he's still the top dog.

She has definitely developed doggy dementia.  She runs around the yard in the afternoon when I let her out, leaping over walkways and up the stairs.  Unfortunately she frequently misses a step and runs into it.  Her vision is definitely fuzzy - she can see movement but has trouble seeing objects, especially at night.  She also is very hard of hearing.  She'll respond, sort of, when I clap my hands if I'm reasonably close to her.  Her age has been catching up with her for the last year or so.
When we scold him, he now lowers his tail, head and looks for a place to hide. Before he just stood there wagging his tail, not realizing he was in trouble.

Jake's eyes are worse - cataracts.  He refuses to step on the hardwood floors so I have to walk him from living room to kitchen or whenever he wants to cross an area of flooring.  I also have to turn on the lights at night so he can jump off of the bed and walk him into kitchen to drink water. When we walk at dusk he now barks and growls more at people walking their dogs - I don't think he sees them clearly.  He is 13.
Have not seen any changes in his behavior in the last six months.
No. Just his waking habits getting worse and worse.
He's become much more anxious aggressive with other dogs.   It is 100% a fear reaction and not a straight up dominance aggression.

Sailor seems to be slowing down a little, occasionally he'll hit the wall literally, when spinning in excited circles- our vet said he has become a bit far sighted and his depth perception is failing (we notice it most when he has to use a staircase -our home is single level so it's not often) There are times when he doesn't notice that you are very close to him until you touch him and he startles/he seems to not hear you- though honestly I think he often pretends he can't so he can roll in the elk pooh.
Sebastian is almost 18 years old. He sometimes displays a bit of cognitive dysfunction. This usually happens at night especially when he comes to bed. He seems disoriented and agitated and barks.

I think most of his behavioral changes are related to physically aging more than mental aging. He has a harder time moving around as he gets older. His eyesight is not as good as it used to be, so that seems to affect his ability to find food on the floor. He also struggled more with heat this summer and cold this fall than usual.

Parisa is patient with me, she naps, understands single words and appears to communicate in her own special way. When she stares it's at night, when she wakes up, and I've left the room, kinda in a daze and then when I return to bed she stops and goes back to bed. Any time I've gone to the restroom, she stands outside the door in a frozen position staring into space or the floor, then when I leave the room she follows or sometimes she leads for there's a routine����
We notice she is slightly less agile when jumping up to the couch she often sleeps on.

"No changes. We have a 2 1/2 year old Weimaraner who keeps Heidi busy - always wants to play. They challenge each other playfully over chew toys. Sounds rough, but never is. They also ""rough house"" in the yard once a day, playing their version of tag. They do that for 5-15 minutes when Heidi gets tired and they stop"

Coaltrane is the most unusual dog I have ever known. He is very skittish and acts as if he has been abused. But we have never ever abused him. He will sit and stare out the window for hours looking for anything he can chase in the backyard. He wont leave the house and is terrified of the leash. But he is not aggressive in any way. He plays great with other dogs. He is almost dis-interested in food. He will let other dogs join him even push him aside to eat his food. He eats with 2 other dogs. He is just a different kind of dog than I have ever met. I'm 60 now and have had 17 dogs of all breeds and mixes lol.
Sometimes she is reluctant to walk through the door to go into the yard. This happens primarily after dark.

Generally slowing with old age and back injury.  Also does not see so well but he seems a lot happier and less depressed than 6 months ago.  He is very proud of mastering his new step to help him get into the car.
I have not been aware of any changes in Mrawa's behavior over the past six months.

He has had two episodes of vestibular disease and  is less stable on his feet. His hearing is degrading also. But cognitively he is good. Likes to petted, interact with people and go for slow short walks
Other than slight visions and hearing deficits, she is mentally the same.
We had to put Maggie on medicine because she kept fighting with the other female dog in the house.  She has never fought with the male dogs.
She watches and attacks the TV when she sees other animals. I mean all animals. Sometimes even cartoon animals.
He sometimes can be more stubborn.
Max is much more focused in training class.  6 months ago he was more focused on other dogs than me.

Jasper is walked regularly 1x/day at the same time each evening. When he isn't limping too bad, we take him around a larger city block (.5 mile) and when he is limping badly we take him around a smaller city block (.25 mile). We haven't been able to identify why or when he decides this, but every so often he will decide not to walk any further on either of our normal routes. He will stop and physically not move until we turn around and backtrack where we came from. Sometimes this happens just one day and then he's back to walking around the whole block, but there have been times - sometimes 6+ months at a time, when he refuses to go any further than a certain point on the walk that only he has identified. Then we backtrack to get home.
It took 6 months, but our dog has learned to bring in a 5th cookie toy to receive a treat.   Normally this new behavior would have taken much less time.

No changes other than related to Covid changes in our routine.  She has become accustomed to always(underlined) being at my side and has exhibited more empathetic behavior than I have ever known her to do before.

"Sometimes when I hold a piece of food in front of her and say ""sit"" she just stares at me. Usually at those times I have to say ""sit"" a few times in a row. It does not happen so often. Still...Very weird. "
She appears more anxious when I leave her and when I come home she is over the top ecstatic, way more than before

Duke finished his obedience classes right at the beginning of quarantine. I can definitely tell that he misses the mental stimulation of attending a weekly class. I try to continue practicing with him but it's not the same as learning new tricks every week.

Earlier this year when my husband and I had to quarantine from each other for 14 days (staying on separate floors of the house except for meal times when we took turns in the kitchen) Zoe was more unsettled.  The doors to each floor were open to allow her to choose where to be, but she went up and down more frequently, especially at night and also could be found standing somewhere staring into space which was something that she had done often more than a year ago before the tentative diagnosis of cognitive disorder.  We were rarely seeing that behavior after she had been taking the fluoxetine for a few weeks. Near the end of the separation, she settled on staying downstairs and wasn't staring into space, but it started all over again when we moved back together and took more than a week to stop.
She does have some failing eyesight, and is starting to slow down a bit (10 years old).    Also, she has always been very shy, even with us although she has lived with us since age 12 weeks or so.
My dog recognizes people, he's just not great recognizing them from afar. He did forget me when I was gone for a few months, though my scent and sounds were also different temporarily.
He's always displayed some fear aggression, but I think it's gotten somewhat worse. It's only related to certain other dogs, not people.
Nothing to report at this time.

Bella is mostly deaf now; started a year ago and progressed quickly.   Doesn't seem to impact her activity.  She is slightly less active because her Mom is a slacker!  She still runs.  At 14!   She is more demanding.  Expects meals on time if not a bit early.  Expects a treat every time comes into the house.  (Thus, that's reinforced!)  Whiny & barks more (I've been told deaf dogs bark more.)   So in general, she is more rigid about things.  Not quite as chill.

As of now, Finnegan seems to be as sharp as he was as a puppy. ONE time, though,  (recently) while we were playing Red Ball (his holy grail), he became very confused as to where the ball was and seemed to be frantic and disoriented and I could not get his attention. It hasn't happened since, but it was scary at the time.
Much more social and controlled behavior when interacting with newly introduced puppies. Also plays well with kittens recently brought into house and backyard chickens when chickens free range.
Samantha seems to tire more easily than she did 6 months ago.  If we take a 5 mile walk, she  is slower as we near the end of the walk.

He understands so many more words! His understanding is leading to very good behavior. Then again, I was quarantined with him. And my granddaughter.. we were always working with him. He's had lots of attention and lots of speech to listen to! I am still mainly working from home. So his ability to come when I say come, wait, stop, no barking...an amazing advancement

Both of Maerzen's housemates, her mum and grandmum, died in March - April 2020.  We moved house in July 2020 to an area where she sees a lot more dogs.  She adapted incredibly well.  She also did not show any strong behavioral changes in response to the other dogs' death, though I did try to head that off with essential oils and homeopathic medicine.
Finn is less anxious and therefore is better able to process information.

Since Covid, no more dog park or outings to socialize with other people/dogs, Jake has been a little more anxious/focused on me.  I've tried to take him on more solo walks or increase yard/house play time which helps but he's not getting the social/outsiide stimulation he did 6 months ago.

She was frighteden by fireworks this year for the first time ever.  Because of COVID they seemed to start the middle of June and lasted until the midle of July.  Not every night but they did worry her more than ever before.  She compensated by going into an interior room and sleeping under a desk. Other than that I see few changes.  I am home with her all the time now of course and she likes that.
She doesn't like taking walks when it is ho or humid.

I have noticed a slight cognitive decline. But nothing really specific.  He takes longer to orient himself when he wakes up in the morning or from a nap.  Sometimes he doesn't want to go out in the yard, which has not occurred before.

Since he is older, almost 8 months old now, I believe his thinking and information processing has improved just with age. He is in Training at Petsmart and has learned some of the things. Guessing with more age he will get better following commands. He can be stubborn.

She is on behavioral medication for her fear aggression.  She started having mobility issues and was falling constantly more and more.  This led us to the vet and lowering one of her meds as we believed it was not being metaboliZed as well due to her age now.  Her mobility did improve but in turn her anxiety got worse and has increased significantly.  She is due to see the behavior vet at Ohio State for a review the Monday before Thanksgivingl
We have always taken Bo outside on a leash to urinate and defecate.  With in the last few months we sometimes need to carry him back inside when finish as he is unwilling to walk.

I think that he is a little more cautious about jumping into the car. Also, at a recent field training workshop, he did not mark his birds on land (that used to be his signature strength), and he was unable to mark the bird on water - there was some scum and I think (?) he did not see the contrast between the bird and the water. His eyes are definitely cloudy, but his nose and brain are good - he still can follow a track and find his articles and get his cookie rewards. He plays with my other Lab and my son's Lab as if there were no tomorrow and he is the play initiator. He is hungry, tail waggy, and beautiful.
"He started licking his ""anxiety"" spot again if we all leave the house even if the other dog is here. "
Moose seems to be forgetting that she has just gone outside and will ask to go out very soon after her last trip out.

We have gone to rally classes and Timon had learned a lot.  He has gotten his novice rally tittle and is learned more to go on to intermediate.  He is a quick learner, but sometimes he would rather do it his way.
"Nevada is becoming more ""cuddly"" and gets on our bed for pets before going to ""bed"" in the living room with her sister dog.  "
seems to have lost partial hearing

He is a little more forgetful and gets confused a bit more easily.  He doesn't see or hear as well as he use to, thank god my vet told me 5 years ago to teach him hand signals with his commands, they have helped out a lot in his senior years.  He maybe older, but is still the same happy little guy he has always been.

He has developed a problem climbing stairs, started with hesitation and start and stop behavior on our rear stairs to the porch.  Now he wont climb them or the interior stairs to the second floor, but can still climb the front which are less steep.  Doesnt seem to be in pain, but is tentative / uncertain.

After a 2 year lapse of not running Bennie, I was given a dog cart, so about 3-4Xweek, we are out running a mile.  As Bennie is not the oldest dog on the gangline, we are keeping it at a mile until they all get some muscle mass back.  I have noticed that since we have started to run the dogs, they all seem more alert and active....and certainly less bored.

We saw him walk completely around a chair kept in the corner of our bedroom which he has never shown interest in before; he has never paid attention to its presence and seemed as if he was exploring it. He has also jumped down from the arm of the couch in excitement to go outside 3 or 4 times in the last 6 months which was uncharacteristically brave compared to his usual demeanor.
No real change in thought process but seems to be much more clingy, not wanting to be away from us. More separation anxiety.
No changes in the last six months.
His cognition seems to be exactly the same. Physically, he's slowing down just a bit.  More tired after long walks.

He is still young and has been with me a little over 2 years.  The first 20 months, my frequent travel exacerbated his considerable separation anxiety.   We are still building a relationship, and since we are spending so much more time together (pretty much 24/7, since the start of the Covid-19 pandemic), we are more tuned in to each other and learning to communicate better.  My dog is calmer and seems to pay more attention to me and understand what I want from him or what I'm about to do.  So I would say his thinking is improving.
He has been sleeping a little more and sleeping in another room instead of the room I am in.
He has matured into a very well behaved dog and has dropped almost all puppy behaviors like urinating inside and chewing inappropriate things.
He is settling in to his new home.  He was adopted when he was 11years old so went through a period of adjusting to his new home and family.
"he seems to have more self-control, better recall with off-leash walks, and better ""manners"" (sitting or lying down instead of begging for food)"

"He seems to be a bit  more confused and ""out of it"" when he's tired, it should be noticed that he's slowly been losing the vision in his only eye (he had one removed 2 years ago) and his hearing is failing so that could account for some of his bumping into things and getting ""lost"""

since she is partially deaf and has older eyes, she can no longer localize sound so it's hard to determine since her ability to hear is inconsistent.
"Requires more ""activity time"" indoors as I'm SO restricted by COVID being autoimmune. New toys and rotation of games is sometimes a poor substitute for more walks but a must for now."

He often stands in one spot and stares at us as if he is waiting for instructions as to whether to come to us, but even when we call him over, he continues to stand and stare until he decides to move.
No she has the same mentality as she had 6 months ago. She is young and healthy as far as I can tell  I love her

Activity level wise, it's not really fair judgment since six month ago he was still recovering from knee/ACL surgery. Overall behavior wise I would say he is even less tolerant of other (not known to him) dogs approaching him.

He is slowing down... sleeping more... also he has a hard time getting up or down stairs - so he stops at the top and bottom for a bit like he's trying to decide how to manage them.
Dolley often has shaking spells not related to temperature changes.
Not really. Maybe sleeps a little more, but COVID is keeping us all inside more, more sitting, reading, etc. A more passive existence for us all.
Gordon seems to moan or whine more than before when he wants something; we have also started a daily game of hide and seek, or chasing, which has really increased his alertness.
There are times when she seems a bit confused.

"Stella had the chance to travel to an entirely new environment. First, she had to adjust to 12 hours a day in a car. Day 1: Stood or sat up all day. Day 2: Stood or sat up half the time. Day 3: Laid down in 15 minutes. Got a lot smarter. She navigated stairs for the first time. Down and up very cautiously the first night. Ran like a wild dog the second! Got to the Wisconsin Northwoods. Freaked out by every noise and movement for 24 hours. Ran like Rin-Tin-Tin and took charge of her space by Day 2. Tore off after a rabbit into acres of woods, only to return in about 5 minutes with a satisfied ""I'm a real dog"" look on her face. She went pretty much everywhere with me and although alert to her surroundings, she quickly adapted to many different places, noises, smells and people. It was very cool to watch her become comfortable as a companion."
Less tolerant of young children and puppies, they are too noisy or rambunctious for him at times.

"When I adopted Mirth from a rescue where he lived for a year and a half, he had been used to a doggie-door, which I do not have.   Although he had been generally continent in my house for the past two years, he sometimes did not seem to remember to void during a play session/time spent outside.  So there would be a random ""mistake"" inside every couple of months despite Mirth having had ample opportunity outside shortly before the ""mistake"" inside.  It did not seem like intentional marking as it was likely to be a puddle near a door, rather than on a wall or vertical surface. During the past 6 months, the problem has gone away, perhaps because Mirth is now calm and focused enough to think of it when he is romping outside for a prolonged period.   "
I'm not sure if it's related to me working from home since the pandemic, but he's more needy, which translates into whining a lot more than he used to.

"Since my brother adopted a dog he seems to be following behavioral ""commands"" better than he was before the new dog came along.  He has learned that if he excessively/obsessively barks while outside, he will have to come in, so he is controlling how much he barks.  He seems to understand that it is ok to bark but that he shouldn't be going ""nuts"" at people or other dogs while in his own yard.  He very rarely reacts to another dog while on walks and never reacts to people negatively while walking. He seems to be more focused on my  direction than before the new dog came along.  "
does not mind cats but still intensely dislikes all other dogs.
She has started eating non-food items, 8 pompoms the kids were playing with (she threw them up one at a time over 10 days), 2 baby socks (she pooped each out separately).

She has always been a smart cookie, but she definitely seems sharper now. She engages in purposeful deception. he is more obedient and seems to know his commands better, but I attribute that to me being at home since March 2020 due to Covid-19

Amy is getting more verbal (dog talking)  in asking for things.  She understands simple words and acts to show she understands the words.
Emmett knocks on the patio door to be let outside. Emmett has learned the morning routine and anticipates the next activity.
Less interested in wrestling and other play
Peyton has increased hearing and sight loss in the psat 6 months, which inihibits his ability to spot food on the floor and to be aware of where members of the household are.
