She became interested in toys while my daughters dog stayed with us. Runs and chases

Lucy has had behavioral challenges since I adopted her 3 years ago.  She reacts aggressively when encountering other dogs while on a leash, and when other dogs approach the fence when she is outside.      We have worked with several trainers through the years, with gradual improvements.  Due to current public health crisis, we have not had sessions, although previous lessons are still being applied.  Lucy does seem to think before she reacts when encounters some dogs she sees regularly, although she does still act aggressive toward unfamiliar dogs and a black lab with similar difficulties.  She has also become less reactive when she sees other dogs in the vicinity when she is in the yard.

This is hard to say. Our dogs behavior has certainly changed with age (she is almost 15), but her behavior also changes with the seasons.  During warm months she is VERY sluggish and never wants to walk. Now that it is cooler again she has definitely perked up. She is definitely slower / less active compared to last November.  She is definitely more active than she was last May.
She has not exhibited any changes.
" Symptoms of ""sundowners"", she begins in the early evening and continues until bedtime. She paces, pants and is restless. Frequent walks seem to help."

I haven't noticed much change in the last 6 months. Hazel is almost 10 years old and the change she has undergone compared to her first 6 years or so is dramatic, but it is linked to a single event. She used to be extremely driven - running along a loping horse or covering 10+ miles barely dampened her energy. She was destructive if there wasn't an outlet for her energy. She liked to keep to herself - a short pet and some attention for 5 minutes and she'd run off again. She began slowing down in 2017 as my older dog got a tumor and began to deteriorate. He declined steadily and I put him down in September of 2018. As he declined, I chose to spend quality time with him and Hazel got a lot less exercise so we wouldn't have to leave him behind alone which caused him distress. And she settled into it readily. After his death, Hazel's personality changed - she was afraid to run out by herself and was depressed and subdued, while also becoming clingy. Now she wanted to have a lot of contact with me and seeking out frequent petting and touching. After 2 months, I adopted a rescue dog (approx 5 year-old Husky-Great Pyrenees mix). They are attached to each other, but they are not inclined to seek each other out for contact. She is back to being more assertive, running around like her prior self and showing the other dog proper Gopher hunting techniques. But her personality remains needier that she was prior to the old dog's death. I don't think she has noticeable cognitive changes, but she appears to have shifted her focus towards her human since the adult dog she had bonded with so closely is gone (he was about 2.5 years old when I adopted Hazel as a 6 month old).

"At age 11, he is still learning new things. He had surgery and other health issues recently. He has learned to use a ramp to get into the car instead of jumping in. He is more focused on prey animals or balls and less on other dogs than he was 6 months ago.

He apparently started headbutting the food bin because he recognized there is food in it. When caught, he stared blankly at my girlfriend then proceeded to do it again. He likes to headbutt things.
She absolutely LOVES the word outside. She won't stop jumping around at my ankles and try and lead me toward the door after I ask her.

She seems to warm up to my grandchildren much faster and I feel like she makes sure the little ones are safe on the stairs.  She is gentle and sweet to all my grandchildren and loves to play with them.  Once she warms up to them she adores their attention and follows the older (7 and 10 yrs old )ones like a shadow.  She barks at the television at certain sounds but is slower getting better and will settle down quicker.
He seems to be going deaf.  He has a hard time responding to verbal commands.

She's recently become very afraid of the trash truck that lifts the trash dumpsters to dump the trash in. There's a lot of metal banging and it never bothered her before but now she's terrified. She shakes and tries to crawl into my lap. She is about 50 pounds so it's a lot of weight and she doesn't usually want to be in my lap.  I've also noticed that sometimes her teeth chatter. I thought it was because she was cold (a/c blowing on her) but she did it yesterday and it was about 80 degrees in the house so she couldn't have been cold.
Almost 6 months ago, I adopted Eugene (rescue).  Since that time, he has become friendlier to other people, more loving to me, less fearful of his surroundings and more curious about everything.
He was adopted in March at almost 7 years old and it is amazing how he has adapted and really learned and grown as a member of our family
My dog is still a puppy. Not quite six months. Most changes he is experienced are progression into adulthood coupled with training.
She seems to be very needy.  Always touching me whenever I sit or lie down. And she has been having accidents lately.
Seems to have learned to watch people and animals on screens such as TV and face time.

Diva is currently getting warm compresses on her right hind leg.  The only reason I marked the question about walking away is that it's a process she doesn't like.  Interestingly enough, she has become quite clingy in that she will follow me from room to room.  She has been much more vocal about trying to comminate her wants to me.  Not a whiney type of vocalization...more like little chirps.  She's always been very independent, so this is a fairly new behavior...over the last couple of months or so.

She does pace and pant during thunderstorms.  Never does this as an aimless behavior.  At the first sound or feel of thunder (before we even hear it) she paces, tries to turn things over using her paw like a hand, opens cabinets trying to pull things out, turns over trash can (not interested in the trash), turns over food bins.  Will not eat during a thunderstorm.  I have tried kenneling (she tore up the kennel so to avoid hurting herself never used kennel again), thundershirts, sitting with her. Antianxiety meds do absolutely nothing - after storm passes the meds sedate her.
He had some declines 10-11 months ago, but has been stable for many months now.
She's more alert to cues from me.
He did show slight depression when our daughter went back to school, and was over excited when she came home in the afternoon. But that was just for 2 days then he was back to normal.
He went from 2 months old to 8 months old, so he picks things up much more quickly now - everything is easier for him, and he  has developed definite likes and dislikes and preferences.

"Over the last 6 months our dog, Steve, has become increasingly better at brain game puzzles that we have for him involving treats. He has several puzzle boards that ""hide"" treats.  Six months ago it would take him 45 minutes to get all 12 pieces out but now he completes it in less than 5 minutes.  It's amazing."
She has more trouble jumping on to the couch and spends a significant amount of time lying on a thick rug in front of our door as opposed to the hardwood floor.
Ike is doing less happy barking while  hopping backwards when exercising with us on a slow moving 4-wheeler.
No.  He is very alert and happy
No changes to his cognitive skills. Murph is turning 7 this month and seems to be in the prime of his life.  He can still run like the wind and copes well with life as he always has.
He seems to be sometime more clingy and talkative/whining for attention.
I have not observed any changes in his cognitive process in the last 6 months.
Gracie is a young Lab (around 2.5 yrs) and VERY active!
Starting to be more protective of toys and treats from the older 2 dogs.  Sila is 3.5, older dogs are 8.5 and 10.

Due to back problems, we no longer take him on walks as we are afraid he will have another episode (he has IVDD). He also recently ate poop for the first time in as long as I can remember, but it seems to have been an isolated incident.
He seems as sharp as ever, and I hope it continues.
At this point, Daisy seems to be the same as she was a few years ago, just slower in her movements.

Jasper was a basset I adopted from the local pound 5 years ago.  Jasper was older, but sweet.  He startled easily and it turned out he had some deafness.  Jasper was diagnosed with  kidney failure and passed away at the end of April 2020.  The month of March and April while Jasper was failing ,both Penny and Dandy were subdued.  After Jasper passed, Penny slept in Jasper's bed, then Dandy slept in Jasper's bed (Penny is the Leader or Alpha over both Jasper and Dandy).  Neither Penny nor Dandy was playing until Dandy met Bentley. Bentley was a  young, energetic  and friendly dog, we encountered on one of our walks in July.  Dandy and Bentley frolicked in a neighbors front lawn.  It was good to see this spontaneous joy.   Penny has not played since Jasper passed. She slept on Jasper's bed a few more times, even though I moved it out of the bedroom.  This week Dandy got Penny to play a little while they were both on the couch.   Dandy is much more lively and he is helping Penny become more lively again.   Dogs grieve just like humans.  Dandy is a social boy and resilient.  It is touching to see how he is helping Penny through her grief.
She seems to be much less flexible with her  routines/more hypervigilant about reminding me when she thinks it's time to eat or to go to bed. She used to be more of a go-with-the-flow kind of dog.

Bella's hearing appears to be on the decline. She frequently misses the sound of deliveries being made at the front door by UPS & FedEx, where previously, she barked her head off at literally every one.
I'm sure when her profound deafness began, but maybe about a year ago (?). I believe that corresponded with her walks around the house to see and smell what everyone is up to.
A bit more affectionate , because of sheltering in place , loss of a home due to So. Oregon Almeda fire ?
Have only had this rescue puppy for 5 weeks

my dog is 10 going on 11...she is starting to have just a little decline but not much. she is very active daily and also mentally active. she has a big vocabulary and is asked to do tricks and commands which she obliges most of the time. she does seem older though, maybe because she finally is...
I have not observed changes in Ellie's thinking or information processing.

We moved from a large house with a fenced in backyard to a small apartment where she can only mostly be walked on a leash. She hesitates coming into the small apartment.  Once in she behaves the same as she would in the big house but she obviously doesn't like the smaller space. I don't either. I still try to take her off leash to her corner of a public park occasionally.

Libby was once a super bright dog. She had a whole litany of tricks that she loved to perform for visitors. In the past six months, she has lost her ability to do any of them. She was recently diagnosed with dementia on top of Cushing's and diabetes and at the beginning of November (about a month ago), her veterinary internal specialist advised us to stop all of her medications except insulin (i.e. vetoryl, anipryl, MCT oil, dasuquin, and some others that were attempting to treat digestive issues). Since stopping all of the meds, she has been a bit less foggy and has been able to follow some simple commands, like sit, speak, shake, wait, leave it - fairly reliably.
Penny has a cataract in her left eye , this has resulted in her occasionally running into stationary objects and occasionally not recognizing , right away, familiar people and dogs.

Thinking and information processing seem stable.  He is a bit of an anxious dog - so he has always paced.  He did experience what I suspect is a herniated disc - so we are limiting his activity level.
She is obeying better to commands.
No change, but I feel can identify her thinking easier than 6 months ago.

About 3 weeks after we rescued her , she began exhibiting increased reactivity and fear of strangers.  We have been taking her to obedience classes and working with a trainer for about 2 months and she has improved.
Remarkably lucid compared with some other older dogs we've had.

Miss Chiff was scared by a lot. It took her 6 months to come out and get pets from a family member that visited at least once a week. It was her personality. Slow to warm up but loved you when she knew you. Now she is walking out the front door when we are with her she would never do that before meet new people still very wary but if we are with her she will let them pet her. She would run into her hiding cave under the table previously. Definitely come out if her she'll a lot in the last 6 to 12 months.
I think Polly's change in behavior is more due to knee surgery and recovery time than maturation.

"As we grow closer, he protects me more, growling or even quickly yipping, when someone approaches, especially inside.  He is unaccustomed to fast moving or loud folks or dogs and behaves poorly and against his training.  We use the command, ""be nice"" to alert him to oncoming doggies, 'though it's not v effective when indoors or contending with an aggressive or bouncy individual.  Perhaps I say this with each beloved canine, but I cannot imagine, nor do I have to for many years, growing any closer. Yet we persist in this unique repore, the pandemic offering more reasons to go on another walk, or to cuddle or to exchange our unmitigated adoration for one another. "
More barking at passers-by and the mail carrier

I think that she is bored since Covid happened.  She is an active Therapy Dog with no regular place to visit which is why I answered slightly less.  She is also a Crisis Response Canine and has been able to offer Community Support during this time

He has become more irritated (and growls) at my older dog (with whom he has lived for almost 10 years).  I'm not sure how much of this behavior has to do with thinking or information processing, but it has been the only difference that I have noticed in the past 6 months.

"In the last 6 months, I've started Crawford on a daily dose of ""Metacam"".  This has significantly improved his ability to get up and down stairs, and reduced his back leg splaying.  Accordingly, he seems generally happier and more attentive to his surroundings."
After dinner, he will sit and stare at me until I give him some love. Doesn't take much but more consistently now as a nightly routine.
He is more timid about trying new things. He is not as adventurous or willing to put himself in situations he where he isn't sure what will happen.
I have seen no changes. My dog is 10 years old, but as yet I see no real signs that he is aging.
My dog is 10 months old. None of these symptoms apply.

Phoebe's slowing down. She has arthritis in her right shoulder, and it's hard for her to go up and down  stairs, especially right away in the morning.  Over the summer, she enjoyed swimming and retrieving in the lake.  She still likes walking around her yard at home and the cabin.  She is the Golden in Charge, and gets what she wants.
I have only had him for about three months but no changes.
He can't find me in the house, even if I am very near. We know his hearing has greatly decreased, but it seems as if he can't smell me either.

in the last 6 months, the most senior of our dogs passed away.  Since then, Dash has wanted to cuddle with people more, and become a bit more eager to eat at meal time.   He continues to excel at learning new tricks and skills.  I have purchased two toys that challenge dogs to get to hidden treats in the toys.    Dash excels at the simpler of the two toys, mastering a rolling ball that hides treats inside while he has not mastered the puzzle board game where he has to open and move pieces to find treats.
She's more demanding. We always walked them about 7 in the morning. Since covid, she insists on another between 9 and 10, and its  seemingly not related to potty needs.
He has been more independent in the last 6 months to present.
Moved into a new house couple months ago. Appears to have adjusted well with everything.
"Recently she will bark for no apparent reason. Usually just one or two short ""woof""s. "

Maybe it's because we are spending more time at home during the COVID era, but his skill at recalling the toys we have named (each one has a unique name) is higher than in the past.  He problem solves when things are in a place he is having trouble reaching (under the table or chair, etc.)
No.  She has allergies and noticed a big difference (positive) since she has been treated.
Separation ANXIETY is worsening.  We've had to refill her Trazadone for 1st time in 3 years.
Cissy was recently diagnosed with some arthritis, and I think her pain has contributed somewhat to changes in thinking.  I just hurts her to move sometimes.

As we move into Winter outdoor activity is greatly reduced and I think this is depressing for my dog. I only say this because 6 months ago we were going on two to three walks a day and now we are down to one a week, but that is not due to lack of energy or motivation on her part. Purely a laymen's diagnosis, but this is a pretty regular seasonal cycle for her. She lost her lifelong companion (a male collies 2yrs her senior) in January 2019 and I think she is still adjusting to life without him as well.

Rosie has become a runner escaping a car or out a door at any opportunity. She appears to  be running just to run as fast as she can. She always returns home but it appears as though it's something she feels she has to do.  It is frightening when it happens
None!  He's 10 and still acts like he's 2 :)
Everyone is home due to coronavirus so it's difficult to say if that big change is affecting her or we're just more aware or if she's actually changed in 6 months.
I think he may have a little more trouble hearing.

6 months ago she was being taken on longer walks than now and playing outside more, by herself.  She dug in the yard, ate grass, and zoomed.  We have had the grass resodded so have had to restrict her fenced backyard playing. The walks have gotten shorter and less frequent because of COVID.
More fearful of loud noises such as hammering or thunder
No.  He doesn't exhibit any of these cognitive issues.

He will sometimes come to a dead stop while walking and look like he is not quite sure how he got there.  Once we get him to move he seems to figure it out and do his normal routine.  He's also developed some anxiety behaviors like panting and licking after spending most of his life as a very calm dog but I'm not sure that's what you are looking for!
she's the same and still very sharp

Really, I haven't seen changes. Nikki is still very active and her walking in circles is something she has done in the four years she's been  with me. She was a show dog and think this behavior is related to time she spent kenneled. She acts and looks very happy while she's walking in circles--sometimes around me,, as though I were a Maypole! When i exercise her in a nearby field she doesn't walk in circles but runs happily after her ball. I also think her dozing on the couch a lot of the time may be partly age-related, but also partly a habit of patience from her youth.

For two and a half years previous to March 2020, Tommy and I were a pet therapy team. Once a week, we would go to a local library for their Tales for Tails program. Tommy's job was to be petted, brushed, and have stories read to him by the children, a librarian, and/or me as we helped the kids with their reading skills. He's a very social fellow and enjoyed the attention though by the end of the hour, he'd be tired and ready to go home. COVID-19 brought a halt to that. We still frequent the large dog park nearby. Tommy seeks out the children as he makes his rounds, socializing and getting petted. I think he misses children.
He is still pretty sharp and develops behaviors to get what he wants from us.
We adopted another Jindo puppy so I noticed Nova go through changes as she adjusted to him being around.
Misty was a pretty timid dog. Covid did not allow for proper socialization   We are now trying to get out more but people don't come close and that has increased her timid personality.
activity level seems to be slowly dropping as she ages.  She loves the couch, jumping up and down are still possible.
His cognitive thinking has remained the same.
He is losing his hearing.  He is more clingy, wants me to be near to him.  Occasionally he may stumble running up the stairs.
Hearing and sight impaired now.  I am not sure how to tease that out of other cognitive issues.

Our other dog, Pepper (14yrs), passed away 8/5/2020. My husband and I have noticed Holly (15yrs) becoming more interactive with us. She stays out in the living room with us longer in the evenings and also doesn't go to sleep under our bed anymore.  One new thing she started after Pepper died is that she barks now to be let in.  Pepper would be the one to bark. If Holly was outside by herself she would never bark to be let back in. Some of the time, Pepper would let me know that Holly was at the door. If not, Holly would just sit outside the door and wait. We adopted Holly a year and a half after adopting Pepper. Holly was 3 yrs old when we adopted her. Pepper was a year younger.

My dogs behavior as stayed pretty consistent. However he was recently diagnosed with a horrible infection so I missed took it for getting old. Once we got him better the behavior went back to normal. The reason I mentioning this is a systemic infection can mimic aging with the lack of appetite, the disinterest, the sleeping too much etc.
Sometimes he pants for no reason.  It happens sporadically, but not often.  It is different from after being exercised or if he comes inside from the heat of the day.
No, but she's sleeping a lot these days
- she seems to enjoy having her head scratched more - she teases us more by pretending she wants to go out and when we get up to open the door, she tries to play with us.

he tends to decide to move or lay down more quickly.  when he gets up to go from where he is laying to the couch, for instance, he gets up really quick.  same way of laying down.  he used to gently lay down and now it is more of a flop down.  enough it can get loud and surprising.
No changes. Haylie Maye is a consistent and stabile furr kid.

"She seems to be more docile.... this could be because I am home with her all the time due to COVID-19.  We have a Furbo dog camera/treat tosser and a dog door; when I checked on her from work at the office, she was seldom in the house and was out chasing squirrels, etc. Now... she is ""with me"" all the time and seems to be content in her dog bed in the office while I work. "

Dante has become more observant of specific words: walk, carride, car, outside, ball, snack. He has been able to determine when someone is leaving the house and he will follow them to see if he can go for a carride. Dante also looks at the type of shoes we wear to see if we are going somewhere that he can come with. Dante has picked up on when my dad gets coffee in the morning, so Dante refuses to go on a walk with the other dogs until he can go with my dad to get coffee.

We had our first child 6 months ago which changed his routine.  Someone is home every day now and he doesn't get to spend as much time in my lap during the day as he used to like.  We noticed some slight hair loss within the first month of baby's arrival but it stopped.  However, the hair has not grown back but we'll see what happens when his coat changes with the season.  He spent his first 2 years with a family that had 3 kids and perks up around children so it's not new to him, it's just new to our situation.  When he gets stressed he gets diarrhea which is his only tell.  That has not happened.  In the first 2 years we had him he would get diarrhea when we traveled but since our childs birth he has pooped solid while on trips.
A slowing in processing speed when I ask him if he would like to be inside or outside. It can take him a couple of seconds to decide.

Colder weather here in  Arizona only happens a few months out of the year. Cozy plays more and is more active during cold weather months even though she is an inside dog. She has recently become more vocal, including a dog purr when happy and content. I think she picked this up from the other dogs in the household. They have always been vocal.
Increasing (though already great) need to be with me at all times.
Her aggression towards other dogs while out walking has diminished considerably.
My dog, Aryia, does not appear to have any cognitive problems. She has slightly arthritic hips, and I believe she is going deaf.
Since he's maturing he seems more focused and has a longer attention span during training

Zeus has just turned two years old in the last month or so.  Therefore, the only behavioral changes I am seeing is that of a puppy maturing into an adult dog.  He is slightly less active and is slightly more willing to follow commands.  We just had him neutered about a month ago.  As far as I can tell, that has not changed any of his behaviors so far.
He seems slower physically, moves less, more arthritic, but very sweet.  Sleeps a lot.  A little slower on the uptake.

Since living with my parents, in a fenced-in yard, my parents and I have noticed he will bark at things that clearly aren't threats (at least to us). If there is a new tool or piece of equipment in the yard he acts frightened and/or defensive. My mom swears it has to do with his vision and that he has vision problems but the vet has never mentioned anything about that. He has also started to bark a lot more at other animals, people, and cars since we moved here in mid June. This is something he did a little bit of, but not nearly as much when I lived in an apartment before.

Our family moved from NC to TX May 29, 2020. Lady rode in an orthopedic bed for the drive, with stops every so often to stretch. We'd noticed in late 2019 that her back right hip was sometimes bothering her but chalked it up to age (she's at least 10 but a rescue so we're not sure) but we did get her pain meds for the drive down in case it bothered her during the trip. After moving to TX, she had good days and bad days so we took her to a new vet. She has hip dysplasia on the right only and started taking pain meds daily. She has more zoomies on pain meds, has more energy and doesn't seem to exhibit any fuzzy-headedness at this point.
She has progressively gotten more protective and aloof towards new people, but has actually gotten a little friendlier towards new animals.
Ivy is a very reactive dog...squirrels, passing cars, deer, people running, etc.  In the last 6 months she has shown some signs of improvement, but it's going slowly.
Moved from a house with a fenced backyard to not having a fenced backyard

His anxiety has amped up with family home all the time and the daily schedule of family leaving for work being altered. As a result he's a lot more anxious- pacing, barking and is on medication to calm him down a bit and take off the edge.
She tries harder to get my cats to play with her.  This is probably because she met a cat that likes to play.
He is less active because I  am in a cast. Boyze has vision problems at night so can have difficulty recognizing people and pets at night.

She does seem to be reacting more poorly to unknown people, specifically workmen at our lake house. She occasionally has snapped at people, starting about a year ago. They are NOT people that she knows, although they may be people that she met briefly once before. She also has been snapping (or trying to) at runners iand scooter riders if she doesn't know they're coming.

"We got a border collie puppy 6 months ago that ""herds"" Otis so much that he's afraid to get off his couch. He used to go outside in the morning at 7:30am, then at 10:30am, then possibly 2pm but definitely 4pm when I get off work, and before bed at 9:30pm. For several months after getting the puppy he would only go out in the morning and before bed, and sometimes at 4pm with a lot of encouragement. If we put the puppy in her cage, he sometimes will ask to go out at 10:30am and possibly 2pm. We thought he didn't want to move any longer, but when a local dog park opened up recently we found that he's happy to go in and play with the other dogs as long as the puppy is kept away or goes at another time. Otis is far less active than he was a couple years ago, but we realize we need to make opportunities for him to keep moving. He has no problem with other dogs, but when another border collie came to the dog park he had the same exact problem - he froze and wouldn't go anywhere when the dog was ""herding"" him. No idea if he would have been this way earlier in life. He has never been anything like an alpha dog and always eats last."

Marley is becoming blind and deaf. Several times a week, especially when it is dusk or dark, he loses track of us when off leash. When we call him he hears but can't tell what direction we are calling from and can't see us. He becomes disoriented and can panic a d run the wrong way. He therefore now spends a lot less time off leash than he used to.

I believe my dog is blind in his right eye and has limited vision in his left eye. (We have followed all Vet recommendations to save what's left of his vision, but it appears to me all we are doing is fighting a chronic battle against eye infections. Pup, his name is Babouche, is so patient and cooperative with us when we give him his meds. ) It seems to me that this impairment has been progressive over the past two years. With this as background, I address observation of behavioral changes in the past six months.  Babouche now accommodates his blindness by looking for familiar landmarks in our house and in our backyard as his guide for getting from point A to point B and back again. He walks very close to us in unfamiliar territory. He is still brisk and jaunty on a lead, but cautious when free of a leash. He relies heavily on his sense of smell, sniffing everything and the air itself. Late at night he will sometimes cry, that cry of fear which was so rare in past years, and we pet him and talk to him which immediately calms him.

Daisy is less active now than 6 months ago because I am having problems with my arthritis and cannot take her for walks as often as she would like.  Unfortunately she really will only go for walks if I am with her so even my wife has only moderate success in getting her to go for a walk without me.

Ainsley has been extremely consistent in her thinking and behavior. The only noticeable change was when we added another dog to the family. She became more reserved and independent after we got Kinsey.

Eddie is now 12 years old and his health continues to decline progressively. In the past 6 months he has lost a lot of strength in his rear legs and has trouble getting up and down and walking for long stretches.  He can no longer climb stairs at all and in the past 6 months, his ability to go down them has declined as well.  He often wanders in the yard without obvious purpose and sometimes just stands there without moving and doesn't respond to being called as much as he used to. It is hard to tell if some is hearing loss or perhaps also loss of processing. He still recognizes everyone and is always happy to greet old and new people and get love from everyone but he is seems slower on the uptake of processing what is going on in a progressive way.
Lost most of his hearing so he has to see me and I do hand signals to show him what I want him to do
He seems to be more attached to us. He is now 1yr & 8mos.
She has become more affectionate, but also more fearful of cloth and clothing falling - like a coat hanging on the back of a chair, or a dishtowel falling from the handle of the refrigerator.
No. She is healthy and active and engaged. Quite energetic and a real Mommy's girl!

She sleeps a little bit more.  Also, we moved three months ago to a bigger house with a big, quiet backyard where she can sniff around and relax.  Prior to that, and for the 7+ years we've had her, our previous house had a small, granite-paved fenced yard/patio (200 sq ft +/-).  Contrary to sleeping more, she is more playful now than in the previous house.
Nope - he's cognitively intact with no signs of decline.

"Button has learned not to climb gates to get in to harass the goats. But if a goat is near a fence or gate, she will try to ""herd"" it by nipping at it through the fencing or gate wire. We're working on that issue."

"He understands far more casual verbal commands or just being talked to. He's great with intentional commands, those learned through training, But I am referring to just ""talking to the dog, ""and him clearly understanding me."
Mattie is learning new taught behaviors a lot faster now.
My dogs issues are relative to anxiety rather than age related, spinning in circles attempting to bite her tail is entirely anxiousness on her part

Monty has visibly slowed down physically in the last 6 months, at least for vigorous physical activity.  He still walks as much as he always has (about 4 miles a day spread out over three walks) but he is no longer a non-stop tennis ball retriever.  After 5-10 minutes, he's done.  Mentally, he actually seems a bit sharper, at least more canny, than he was a year ago or more.  I think he has just gotten better about knowing how to get what he wants with less physical effort.
Her hearing is starting to fail rapidly to where she will no longer come when called unless it is accompanied by a clap or louder, sharper sound.
Whines more when seeing other dogs on walks. Does no get as much social time with other dogs on walks due to social distancing during Covid

He seems a bit calmer and doesn't chew as much. We have been home more in the last 9 months which we think is why. He tends to have some minor separation anxiety which causes chewing on inappropriate things
Less ability who walk for very long because of her bad back legs
She is slightly more wary of strangers as we've had less visitors during COVID

Lola has become very processive of me and jealous when we bring in foster dogs. Lola has become much more of a bully since we have become foster dog parents. And for some reason she is now arrived of the car rides.  We are working with her on everything.
Asher is more obedient and learning what we expect from him.

She is bored!  For 8 years she has been a busy dog; for 4 years she made frequent visits to hospital patients and staff and hospice patients.  For all 8 years she has made regular school visits as a READ dog.  Until the middle of March she was making at least 9 school visits and 1 assisted living visit every month.  Then it suddenly all ended when schools were closed and this fall we opted not to continue our school visits.  She really misses those kids and being read to by first and second graders 2 or 3 times every week.  When weather is decent we spend an hour each day at our 13 acre dog park, when weather is not so good, she spends 5 hours a day in day care.  She gets out and about some, but nothing like what she has been used to and I am unable to explain the sudden change to her.  She and I both miss our frequent contact with other people, but other than staring out the window and occasional heavy sighs, I have not noticed changes in her thinking or information processing.  She will turn 11 in 5 days.
She has had more difficulty getting onto higher surfaces. We bought her stairs to get on the couch. Took her a while to use the stairs but nw she does it on her own.
No changes. At nine years old she is still as active and engaging as she has been her whole life.
She has become more bossy, demanding to go outside and refusing to go out. We did adopt a dog a year ago and seems this behavior is related to him.

Lizzie was restricted in a cage at a kennel for the first 3 years of her life. I adopted her 16 months ago. She was terrified of cars while on walks and most noises in and outside the house. She was overstimulated on walks. Due to the pandemic, in the last 6 months, Lizzie has been exposed to new experiences outside in a more controlled manner and is able to process new information in a much more calm and relaxed manner.  She presents, overall, with less fear of novel events.
With the pandemic I am working from home.  His stress level seems to be lower.
Seems to be very sharp still at 13 years old

Actually yes-he's figured out a bunch of new strategies for getting at food he's not supposed to. Ever since covid started. I thought at 8 that we were past sone of that stealing and thievery lolol. Seems to coincide with increasing  and longer walks we are ttaking because of quarantine boredom

We started her on a food that requires 15 minutes to soak (in water) prior to feeding. We set the oven timer so it goes off after 15 minutes, and she immediately (same day) began associating that noise with her mealtimes. And she barks at us if we don't move fast enough!

much more active when our other dog comes into heat.

Lexi is fine in her normal environment, but always has reacted to loud noises.  We are social distancing which involves a new, busier environment.  This is our second day in a new house and she does seem more anxious.  Hopefully she is able to adjust.

India has always been reactive to environmental changes / stimuli (kids on bikes, construction cones that weren't there before, etc.). Her threshold distance was always quite big, and we would have to be far away from the things that set her off in order to do any training.  In the last year, I've noticed that her threshold distance has decreased significantly and that the reaction is not as large. A kid on a bike can usually ride by her on the street with only a glare or a bark now when it used to be a full on lunge and bark if I wasn't prepared to help her. I can actually have a conversation with a stranger at a normal distance where this was impossible a year ago.  I think part of this is a decline in vision and hearing, but not all. In some cases she is quite aware of the thing that would have caused the reaction, but as long as it does not interact with her, she seems to tolerate it in her space.

June had a bit of  a readjustment which started about 8 months ago when things shut down.  She had been doing health care visiting once a week and kids were reading to her in a library until then.  So six months ago she was still adjusting to the lack of that kind of activity and seemed rather restless for a few months.  It seems like she is finally accepting her new life without that (she does still get her two walks a day, including an hour off leash in the Boulder Open Space every morning.

Hearing has declined so commands or directives are oft times repeated before compliance. Stella seems to enjoy being brushed or petted more so she is more receptive and quiet when the brush comes out or my hand reaches out to her. Stella has some discharge from her eyes in the morning so when I approach her with a tissue to wipe her eyes she lowers her head just seeing the tissue coming out of the box. What's interesting is that I get packages all the time because I shop online but it's that particular delivery that he always seems to notice and is waiting there for his treat to come out of the bed I just find it interesting that he's figured that out it didn't even click with me The first couple of weeks he's done it but it dawned on me that the only time he ever acts that way is for that delivery

My dog is more active now. I am the new owner. Previously he lived in an apartment, had stairs. Roo now lives in a house in country with dog door to access large yard 24-7. He rarely goes out himself by choice, occasionally. We routinely go out to walk property every 2-3 hours with 2 other small dogs. If raining short time to do business. If nice, walk down by the river and back. or out to barn to do chores. Roo hates rain, (his least favorite thing in the whole world). He has little to no hair coat so chills quickly if wet and cold out. Also does not appreciate coat to help him retain body heat. When seriously raining, not just mist or drizzle he has to wear coat and leash in order to be forced outside for routine outings. I am always with them. This morning sunny, 43 degrees, walked to river, ground wet and muddy with puddles (no dog coats or leashes).  He is wearing no-barking collar during the day, off in evening and all night. Beeps and vibrates if barking continues. He never gets to the vibrate stage. Barking at every sound, phone ringing or using phone to call out or entrance by family member is hugely improved. He may bark 1-2 times but stops immediately on collar beeping. We have a quiet home and he was extremely disruptive and not getting better until collar. He was going to lose his home if not stopped. He is a great little dog and so different from any other dog I have owned (joyful).  So he is thinking to learn new behavior patterns.

We did have a problem with aggression when taking off or putting on an over the head halter. The one time he did bite my husband was when he was upset by a dog we were visiting and we were trying to put him in his crate to go in the car.

For much of the past year, Noodle has been recovering from a medial shoulder instability injury, which he acquired likely doing agility. He has been in a shoulder harness and his activity has been severely restricted.  Since his injury and the start of wearing the harness 24/7, Noodle has been less energetic and less confident overall.  He received shock wave and PRP treatments, and is no longer in obvious discomfort, so my feeling is he is somewhat out of sorts without his usual hobby to engage him. He just appears to feel down, and esp reluctant to wear his harness.  Luckily we are now at the end stages of his rehab, and he can go for longer periods without his harness.  This makes both of us quite relieved :)
We got a second dog about 8 months ago and they get along really well. Delia is playing more and acting younger and sharper.
She does fatigued more easily. She gets distracted and loses interest when we are doing tricks.

He is doing more problem solving. An example when he is on his extended leash and starts to wrap it around and object he now goes back rather that having me unwrap the leash. He does it himself. He has also recognized that the latch on the gate allows it to open and will push it up with his nose when we start out on a walk.
Seems to be hard of hearing.

"He has begun to resist even steps to something he wants to do.  For example, he loves to go outside and initiates a lot of excitement behavior about going, like running and bouncing to the door.  Once there, however, he will resist having his collar put on, and back away.  The action has to be totally voluntary, so I ask him to step forward into it and don't move, until he does. While things have always had to be ""his idea"" this has become more pronounced with the very things he wants to do."

Since covid I've been working from home (March 2020) my dog seems way more attached to me, and much more morose when I leave. Even if other people are home while I'm away he sits in my room and waits for me.

Tucker is a rescue and the changes we have seen in him have been mostly changes he made as he felt more comfortable with us.  He started as a quiet, shy dog about a year old and now is more boisterous, playful, food motivated and barks a lot more at things outside that even we can't see.
Most of the changes in Cookie's behavior are due to hearing loss, which started about six months ago. She follows us around and makes eye contact more frequently.
Mentally she seems the same; physically she's slowing a bit.

He has increased finicky, peculiar eating habits--but always eats. He just appears to need variety, and as we joke, pot to table, cuisine. He's VERY sensitive to any medicine's or supplements we now have to sneak into his bowl.
Much more goal oriented especially as it relates to food More actively engages with us to encourage play

His activity level has increased for two reasons: (1) my husband and I have both been working remotely since March 2020 and take him for a walk at least once a day (sometimes twice) in addition to his having access to the fenced in back yard for as long as he wants to be outside multiple times a day, and (2) our 16 year old dog died in July 2020 and we then adopted a 1 year old pup who Ribeye enjoys running around with in the back yard and playing with in the house

Arya has become obsessed with the front door. She listens for delivery drivers and over-reacts when deliveries are made. She spends more time in the front room than normal. We receive more deliveries because of COVID-19 and I think this is the root cause. We've considered anti-anxiety meds because of this behavior.
He seems more hesitate to go down stairs in the dark. I have bought a motion light so he can see the stair better now.

"It does take her longer to learn a new cue than it would have when she was younger. She needs luring and hand-signal prompts more often. I'm working with vet to try pharmaceutical interventions along with enrichment."
No. His cognitive processes seem fine. He is alert and happy even if he isn't quite as active as he used to be.
Slightly slower - we are guessing his hearing it starting to worse.
He's learning more tricks and is self correcting some of his mistakes

He is better/nicer about telling another dog when they are playing too rough or that he does not like it. We have a small dog park in the apartment complex and he has been playing a lot better with the dogs in there than six months ago in a dog park.
He seems a bit more attached to my youngest granddaughter (2 yrs old), he's more willing to cuddle with and play with her than before.  He normally avoided her.
No changes and during the summer she was very active.
For the first time i noticed her getting up and wandering the house at night.
Zara is slower than in the past. She's deaf so is now relying on hand signals from me to coax her out for a walk or to alert her its meal time.
No cognitive or behavioral changes, only physical changes due to osteoarthritis and partial tear in tarsal tendon.

I have noticed that he falls into a deep sleep more quickly. I have also noticed that he seems to analyze the situation more frequently before reacting - I interpret this as a method of possibly conserving energy.  For example, if I get off the couch and go into the kitchen, Johnny would ALWAYS come with me. Over the last 6 months I have noticed that he will often stay on the couch and watch what I am doing before he decides if he wants to come or not.  This is a much different behavior for him.  He is a little spitfire and has never shown signs of being lazy.
She wants to be left alone, doesn't want to be bothered, becomes annoyed and will walk away.
In the last 6 month Odie had learned new commands.
Digs holes, pants, anxious in car and in vet, overly excited to be with people. She has Atypical Cushings with Hormone surges. Behavior increased by chemical imbalance.
Much happier since moving in with is.
she is more reactive when we accidentally step on/near her

"Nepo has always been what I would call ""highly spirited""....he is strong-willed and highly intelligent...he knows when he is disobeying a command (come, leave it, no)....but his spiritedness, willfulness or lack of impulse control will override his thinking and he will do whatever he chooses.  In the last six months (he is now 3 1/2 years old) I have noticed that he will more often follow a command (come, leave it or no) even when he really doesn't want to...he will let me be in control even though he doesn't want to do what I am asking...he has a look of submission that is a new expression that goes along with obeying me when he would prefer not to."
He has improved with listening and following directions. He is able to anticipate what we will ask him to do much better.
She seems pretty sharp still, it's mostly her body (arthritis) that seems to cause her anxiety/pain.
Just depression from not being walked due to covid.
She's a puppy at 18 months right now.  She has actually become more astute; she is very thoughtful and she's always super energetic and playful!

He has always been anxious, but now with mobility issues, he barks more if left alone in a room.  Since he can't get up by himself any longer, he wears handles and someone helps him up.  He will usually go to the room where one of his people are, but sometimes he goes back to the empty room, lies down and barks again. We tried Reconcile for 3 months, did not seem to be helpful, has been discontinued.
Jack seems to be stable. No signs of any cognitive deficits.
She sometimes doesn't listen when we call to her when wandering around outside. Hard to tell if she's having memory or hearing issues, or is just being an old dog set in her ways.

Ruffles is very aware, loves to play both with people and with her toys.  She has become much more snuggly in the past 6 months, but I am sure that is part of her adjustment to her new home (I have only had her for almost a year).
Lizzie is as sharp as ever.  There are times when I wish she would forget things...
No, it's all about the same.

"Waylon is now approximately 18 months old.  Waylon has become much more confident with his ""place"" in the family.  He has also calmed down a little. He knows where his food is and knows to stay away from the other dog's food (although Rex, our alpha dog, eats from his bowl at times). Waylon happily obliges Trinity.   He also knows when it is bedtime and that he sleeps in our son, Cooper's bed with him."
Mia is only 18 months old. She has learned a lot in the last 6 months. She is more obedient.

"When we don't play with her when she wants to play she lays down with her back to us and pouts. Sometimes she doesn't want to go ""By By in Car"", or sometimes she doesn't want to go for ""Walkies""."
No,  I have not noticed any other changes in my dog's thinking or information processing.
We are at home more due to the pandemic, so he seems more needy and begs for attention more often. He's also a bit more snuggly - will sometimes sleep in the bed with us which he never used to do.
He has become a little less aggressive towards visitors and other pets
Slower sometimes in processing a command. He will either just stare or look at me confused. Doesn't seem to be an issue with his hearing.

She is 19 months old now. I adopted her at 11 months. She had been outside with other dogs her whole life, and had not been socialized. She had no language and was not even housebroken. So, yes, lots of thinking and processing of information.
She has displayed all the cognitive advancements expected for a growing puppy.
He is very social and smart. We spend most of the day with each other.

Sammy was quite agitated and barked excessively at me the first few times cross country skiing with me this season. Will keep working on this if she continues this behavior or stop taking her if it doesn't improve.

I take her to the dog park every evening that I can. This is usually 6 nights a week. She knows that it is getting close to going after dinner, and she will not leave my side. Every move I make, she looks at me and is ready to go.
Yes, Lucas is now about 18 months. Six months ago he still acted like a puppy full of energy. He still acts like a puppy sometimes but he is growing out of the puppy stage

overall anxiety seems better in the last 6 months
"He seems to be having occasional ""flashbacks "" from being abused as a puppy. (Previous home""."

Her attachment to me is getting stronger and not in a healthy way. The following from room to room is worse. If I go out a door, she lays looking at that door until I come back in. When the dogs go outside to go potty in our fenced yard, I cannot go inside and do other things or she won't go. She seems less sociable.  She used to always want to be in the same room with us, but now she will frequently  leave the room and go into our bedroom to sleep on our bed, by herself.  If I enter the room I always get a tail wag...
We have observed Campbell seeming to understand more of our dialogue with her. We think that her understanding of some human vocabulary has increased and see it reflected in her behavior.

we are learning new tricks.  quick learner

I haven't noticed any age related changes in Duncan. In June he was diagnosed with some inflamation around the vestibular nerve on the left side of his face. He has partial facial paralysis on that side. It does not seem to have affected him mentally at all.

Sophie is more consistent in terms of attentiveness and self-control than she was 6 months ago. I attribute this to her age, because she reached 2 years old at about that time: she is now a more mature dog rather than a puppy.

"We actually think she's a bit smarter than before - she's 7 years old but Molly has never gone to the door if the doorbell rings and now she does! We took a Tricks class and she gives high fives when she wants attention now. She did not know this before the class.

Zeke now barks every time he hears the word boat instead of just barking when he sees boats! :)
No changes. She gets better and better at learning our changing behaviors and language. And she's a good problem solver.

Cisco is now 14.8 years old.  He sleeps more now, and seems to have some hearing loss.  Also, his eyes aren't as clear, but he doesn't have cataracts. Seems a bit slower when he gets up from laying down

for ten years we always took the same walk in the AM - lately we have been letting Baby Einstein lead us on his morning walks and he has been exploring our neighborhood - our walks are now usually an hour long and cover 2 to 2 1/2 miles

He's discovered that I actually have two alarms. So, he knows he can get scritches in bed after the first alarm and he gets food and walkies after the second alarm. She seems to be more communicative about what she wants and seems to understand what we are saying more.

At evening, when outdoors is dark - we live rural so a full moon shows light. She must be sure of the outdoor odor before venturing outside.  Six months ago, and for all of her earlier living time, she would moved directly outdoors once leached up for her final 'tinkle' of the night.  It's the hesitation and sniffing the air at the doorway that is a new behavior.  Maybe once a month her nose picks up a scent and she refuses to go out.  Wait 20 minutes and use another doorway, she performs her sniff test and goes out the door.  We are watching this new behavior to see if it grows in intensity over the next months/years.

she was relatively untrained when adopted and has attended several obedience classes and understands what we ask of her much better. She seems to have a harder time seeing things when her hair is long. She remembers some people she hasn't seen in years, but only if they played with her. She used to get very sad when she'd see female golden retrievers (like her mom was) as a puppy.

keep in mind at 17 1/2 she's lost vision in one eye and trouble seeing in the other.  Her hearing is gone or close to. So she does walk into an unopened door occ, but she doesn't see it. "Yes! Within the last 6 months, Mia Tortilla has become much more active in regards to her ""silly"" behavior. This has always existed but has seemed to increase in recent months. This includes her running around/growling with her toys, ""phantom digging"" where she digs into the couch or bed pillows until she's exhausted, and becoming much more vocal when she's confused or wants something/vocally responsive when spoken to (almost ""talking back"" in a playful way). I suspect there are two contributing factors to this change in behavior. The biggest contributing factor, I believe, is a psychological one: my boyfriend moved in with us about 8 months ago, and considering that she has never in her life had another long term ""roommate"" besides me, she was initially subdued by his presence. However, now that she's fallen in love with him and considers him a member of the pack, her silly behaviors have increased alongside her audience size. I believe she's much more confident in her level of derp because she knows she's got a captivated audience that feeds off/responds to it. If there is a second factor to this change in behavior, I believe it is a physiological one: Mia recently had dental surgery where several teeth were removed and it's possible her playful behavior is also a result of experiencing less pain on a daily basis. Either way we love that our 11 year old seems more active, sillier, and happier than ever! "

is becoming more and more accustomed to life outside kennel life.  no longer fearful of, and no longer startles at loud noises, now walks past trucks and buses, now accepts treats and greetings from strangers.

He's been erratic for some time.  I take him for walks (I bike; he walks or runs) twice a day. Some days he walks; some days he runs. Occasionally, he'll just stop and not want to go any further.  Sometimes that seems to be related to the weather (he does NOT like to go for a walk on hot sunny days).  I usually try to adjust my speed to his pace, but sometimes have to circle back to rejoin him.  Other times, he stays right next to me (we're on an isolated, rural road, so I don't put him on a leash).  He can be very different, one walk to the next, even if the weather is similar.  I usually let him decide when to turn around to go home.  Last night, he started running at a typical turn around place--going farther, not turning around (that only lasted about 30 yards, then he was ready to go home.)  We live on a long, dead end road--so these walks are not loops or full of options: it's about a mile out and a mile back, unless he goes off into the fields, which he occasionally does, but usually returns pretty quickly.

Jenny definitely has Canine Cognitive Disorder.  The confusion and walking a circular path through our house has been happening since about May of this year. "My dog has slowed down overall, physically , behaviorally, and psychologically. He takes longer to react to stimuli, will stare into the void more often, hugs walls more to walk, and takes longer to respond to verbal commands even though there are indications his hearing is still strong. Wylie is lucky guy; he has always been curious and very social. With the virus now ~9 months in, Wylie has received even more attention and exercise, all good for his cognition.  He is also off leash for 'squirrel patrol' in the park, hiking trails, or on the beach at least 1-2 Xs/day.   He also likes to wrestle and socialize with the neighbors dogs too.  This is his *favorite time of the day,* when he is interacting, wrestling, socializing, or sprinting and chasing squirrels around trees [even though he has never come close to catching one].   I trust him off leash and he is also lucky because we have a fenced in yard where he is also outside many hours each day.   He greets everyone who walks by the fence and brings people his toys (and tries to get people to play with him).   The extra attention (and time with my work from home) has also increased his autonomy.  He also delights in playing with his Italian Greyhound brother Jesper everyday too--it is a riot to watch an athletic 70 pound dog play and tug of war with a 13 pound Greyhound. continues to be intuitive to our schedule/routine...becoming more stubborn when he doesnt want to do something..or wants ME to do something!

Belle  is sweeter/more  affectionate now (at 14 months old) than she was 6 months ago.

Seems to have more night tremors/convulsions.  Seems to have more of a blank look more often (but still not very frequently).  Is much more hesitant to want to walk in unfamiliar territory.

This has been a very stressful time for Chewy.  He has weathered 2 hurricanes where he was displaced into a hotel room for 3 weeks, then another 4 days.  In between the 2 hurricanes we took him on his first RV adventure.  Since he is a dog of routine, it was very stressful for these 2 1/2 months.  He is now back home, and has gotten back into his regular routine which he has trained us to accept.  Also, I might add that even though we were traveling or outside of his familiar territory, we kept as much as possible his regular routine.  When we got home after Hurricane Laura, our road which we regularly walk and where he runs, were lined with debris, up to 15 feet tall on both sides of the street.  He also adapted well to this change with all of the new smells and places to mark.
She will be 6 in December. I think she sleeps more now than she has in the past.

"Definitely.   He's a lot more aware of his surroundings.  His mind is sharp and he's constantly figuring out how to do something new every week. "He seems to be more independent. He isn't as ""needy"" , he will stay outside on his own for 20-30 mins, where 6 months ago, if I went inside, he needed to come in too. He seems content with sitting outside and just staring into the tree line or up at the birds. "

"I recently had surgery that limited my activity. Prior to that, every night before Chloe retired my wife would walk her and then she would run to the kitchen where I told her to lie down and stay on the floor. I would tell her to ""dance"" on her hind legs and give her a small treat. Then she would lie down again until I commanded, ""Let's go to bed!"" and she would sprint into her crate, where I would give her another piece of biscuit and close the door of the crate. As I recuperated, my wife would take over the last part of the process, but now I am able to do it again. For the first several days, Chloe was confused, first didn't leave the kitchen, then would go to the bedroom and jump into our bed (where she is allowed when prompted), and then go to her crate when prompted a second or third time. After a few nights, she seemed to relearn her original behavior and sprint to her own bed. Other than that, have not noticed any changes over the past 6 months and much longer. At 10.5 years, still energetic and responsive."

Not really.   Bernie has slowed down considerably in his old age (he's 12), but is still healthy, still runs after squirrels in the yard, barks at leaves blowing in front of the house (LOL), etc.   He is just slower and calmer.

I purchased expensive canned dog food to mix with her kibble, and now she will eat on her own. "About 10 months ago we got a 1-year-old Labradoodle. This has provided her with opportunities to socialize with another dog on an ongoing basis. Since we live in the country, this means she now has a ""peer"" to spend time with while running around outside in the woods.  She is still mostly a solitary dog (always has been independent) but she now has periods of time most days when she is playing with and socializing with our other dog.   In terms of changes in thinking, it's clear she is paying attention to the amount of attention he gets and asks for similar attention. For example, when he's being brushed or groomed, she will come and stand nearby to wait her turn to be brushed or clipped, too. Prior to his arrival, she was never brushed or groomed in this way because her fur doesn't require that type of maintenance.  This is a consistent behavior now for her that we have to give her a brief brushing and pretend to clip her hair if he gets this treatment.  Another example of changes in thinking is that when it's feeding time, in order for the Labradoodle to be allowed to eat, he has to sit and wait for a hand signal that tells him he can eat. Lately, she now does the same thing even though this has never been required of her. Prior to his arrival, she was free fed. Since his arrival, she is on his twice a day feeding schedule and has now adopted the behavior that she waits to be fed until we give her permission to eat."

"We go to an off leash dog park every morning.      He was excellent at remembering where he dropped his toy in the 5 acre park and would go retrieve, with command ""go get your toy"".   He has just a little bit more trouble finding it now, although is still remarkable most of the time."

Reflections of light, or light spots from a beam, can instantly distract him from everything else and he goes wild trying to chase it down.    Mark is aware that if I turn on the ceiling fan or use the fan remote, that it causes the ceiling fan to turn on. So when he sees me reach for the switch or remote, he looks up at the fan. In order to keep him we had to do some extensive training so he wouldn't kill our cats. We took him to a trainer who used a mild shock collar on him (this is the only thing we've ever used this training method for), and even if I hid the collar remote behind my back so he couldn't see me use it, he knew it was me. If he was going for the cat and he felt the shock, he would turn and stare at me, everytime. He's basically fine with cats now, but you can tell he'd love to go after them if he thought it was a good idea, although strange cats should not come into our yard.
