Saoirse has learned to contain excitement about squirrels while on a lead, barking at neighbors is of shorter duration, she has expanded into the new yard space learning to keep senses open to potential squirrels in yard or walking the fence rails and is clearly enjoying the cooler weather by being more active.  Her pattern indoors is to be in any room I'm in.

"Edwinna had some lymph node swelling, lethargy and pain this past summer, for about a week. The vets were not able to make a diagnosis, but it resolved when treated with steroids.  One of the things I told them on my first visit was that she ""just wasn't herself"" - which for Edwinna means always ready for anything - first pictures of her as a puppy show her with this slightly mischievous look on her face and she still looks like that to this day, if she feels good.  She did not on those days.  I have also referred to Edwinna over her life as ""Joy Incarnate"" - the only time that dog is ever unhappy is if you say something negative to her.  And then she is just crushed.  But otherwise, she is a very happy dog.  Which I guess I just mention for benchmarking purposes -"
She is better at doing a sequence of activities without stopping (sit, wave, run through the tunnel, push the ball, catch, etc.)

In the past 3 months or so, Tulio has begun to go to the basement of the house alone and bark constantly until someone brings hi back upstairs to be with us. If we block the stairs he will then go to a back bedroom and bark until someone comes for him.  In the past 3 months, Tulio insists on being outside on a lead chain in the yard for extended periods. He will often stay out until after dark and curl up in a ball in the garden. It is like the cold air makes him feel better. When I go out to bring him inside he sometimes struggles to stand up and get moving again. However, he is still very eager to exercise and go for long walks and trail walks, so I don't think he is physically incapable.
He seems much more eager to stay right next to me as much as possible.  I think this is more because I'm home nearly all the time now.

Jackson seems to be terrified of small children, including babies. He barks incessantly at them, the only time he lets them touch him is if they are not afraid and just walk up and do it without him realizing it is about to happen.  He does not seem aggressive but afraid. whatever causes this had to have happened before we got him at 4 months of age.
He's more stubborn and will try to cross the street without being directed to (as from before).

She has become more anxious, whining often to get attention, and crying when either me or my partner walks away/leaves. She has also been acting strangely recently in that she is more alert and nervous, and has weird facial expressions we haven't seen before.

"I have noticed that she is not good at sleeping by herself downstairs any longer. If she sleeps in her bed upstairs next to me, she doesn't bark at night [or have as many dreams where she is howling]. However, if she sleeps downstairs, she sometimes has a ""bad"" dream and, rarely, urinates her downstairs bed. "
Her lifelong canine died.  She spend a few weeks looking out for her but has settled down and now spends more time hanging with humans.

She has fallen out of her dinnertime pattern and now starts begging one or two hours earlier than we normally feed her. I'm sure it could just be due to daylight savings ending for us humans, but she usually adapts much faster than she has this time.
She whines more at night. She wants food all the time, even if she just ate.
He's growlier. Less tolerant of the younger dogs intruding into his space.

"Jackson is experiencing some age related hip challenges, but nothing that won't keep him off the couch, bed or walk.  He readily recognizes his ""girlfriends"" being the receptionist at the vet, my step daughter and my daughter.  He is still the friendly, sweet, goofy boy."

"She's getting smarter in that she recognizes the word ""supper"" and immediately gets up or comes to me, knowing she'll get fed. She also knows if she hears me getting plastic bags at certain times of the day that it's time for a walk."
I haven't had her for six months
No changes, more activity due to working from home now, more walks
Daisy has matured.  She still is a crazy bity girl who is obsessed with her ball and playing fetch.  She become more dependable during potty training.  She is now willing to let children pet her.
She learns words much more quickly now, her desire to please is much more focused, her response to reward is much quicker
He seems a bit more sexually preoccupied at times
He eats more quickly, probably due to a change from 90% dry food to 90% wet food, both with 10% ground (cooked) chicken mixed in.

He has stopped waking me up by sniffing my face and rather sits and stares and me until I wake up which is an interesting change. He has learned to wait for me to walk out of the bedroom first in the morning rather than him going first because he is avoiding me shutting the door on him ;) Sneaky and clever! He has increased refusal to get in the car to go places which he displays by laying down on the garage floor and rolling over then while squinting his eyes. He is clearly communicating he does not want to go yet other days he cannot wait to get into the car. I'm not sure the antecedents yet to this behavior.
I think he has been needier since we've been home more because of the pandemic. Sometimes he needs to go outside when I am on a Zoom call.
In July I got a 9 month old Clumber Spaniel puppy and this has drastically Alice's attitude and activity level.  She is having the time of her life.  Not bad for a a dog who will be 9 on Nov. 18.

Teddie had a really hard time with the COVID lock down in March.  He was used to going places with me daily, going on new walks and meeting people daily.  With the lockdown, neighbors were home all the time and let their dogs roam off leash.  Everyone was out walking their dogs and riding bikes.  Teddie became reactive to dogs, bikes, and some people.  We had to stop taking him for rides in the car.  He has been just on our property since March.  I'm working with a trainer to help him and he is now on Prozac and CBD oil to help with the reactivity.  It seems he became depressed with the change in routine.  He's doing better but still not back to where he was Pre-COVID.  He is now back to playing with toys and eating regularly which he stopped doing in March.

He has a harder time finding people and things due to the progression of his visual loss (glaucoma and detached retinas in both eyes). He also seems to be having hearing problems, not responding as quickly to verbal commands or calling his name.
more possessive of his favorite toy.
Nothing has changed. She's intelligent and still learning new things.

"He does seem slightly ""dottier"", but only slightly. For instance, walking right past the open car door when going on an adventure, though he quickly realizes his mistake, backtracks, and jumps in."
Since our dog park has been closed off and on, he hasn't gone to play with other dogs as much, so at times he seems bored and wants to go for walks around the neighborhood more often.
She was a puppy 6 months ago, so her learning is improving.  She wanders & walks in circles because she's looking for a new spot to sit & just looking around the house.  She is no couch potato!
he has always been vocal, but has become more so.

no; we were given Tempo by my friend in 2016, after one of our Golden Retriever's died; that is why the medical records began in 2016  Tempo has slowed down JUST a bit- he turned  8 9/20/20.-- not wanting to jump into the back seat of my SUV every time & sometimes having trouble jumoing off our high bed.
he bit my hand once when I tried to feed our other dog a treat.  he cut my thumb fairly badly. he's never cut me before

She stays in the house much more often. I have 4 dogs and she used to stay outside with the other two dogs who love the outdoors, but lately she comes in and lays by me along with my other couch potatoe

My dog is on Prozac for separation anxiety and generalized anxiety and in the last 6 months we've raised his dose.  He was having some difficulty in staying focused and being able to relax (he needed constant supervision and had to be entertained and wasn't able to relax enough for naps, and his separation anxiety training was at a stalemate, we couldn't get past the 1 minute mark after 6 months of training).  Now he acts much more like a neuro-typical dog.  He still has some anxiety, but he's able to focus better, he makes better choices, and he can rest rather than constantly be on the go.
I have not noticed any changes.

6 months ago, he was 9 months old, and now he is 1 year 3 months. As you would expect in a growing dog, he has matured over the last 6 months. Now he, is calmer, and listens better than he did 6 months ago.
No. She just gets sore from arthritis.
She responds to high value treats better.  Fewer episodes of red zoning.
not as playful; likes more napping, but everything seems to come in spurts; sometimes he'll STILL do ZOOMIES (he's 6 1/2)
I am not aware of any changes.
As he just turned two years old last month, over the last six (6) months I've noticed greater ability to process information and make more confident independent decisions.

Hammy has always been a dreamer and will stare at the sky. Now sometimes he wanders around without purpose that I can see but he's never fanfic about it. We have food, beds, and water all over the house so who am I to wonder what he's thinking or not. As long as he is happy, no problem.

Ryder is still a puppy at 18 months, so he is still very eager to learn new commands and try new and different experiences like riding in the car, visiting our canine neighbors, etc. Unfortunately, he remains a fierce watch dog, warning us loudly of every leaf that blows across the front yard, every delivery truck that passes, every neighbor who walks by. We're hoping he will learn to be more discriminating about who/what triggers his barking.

"She's more observant. She follows us everywhere; bathroom, outside, in the car with no apprehension. Brigid is ready to stay in  ""place"" in the evening meaning she'll lay on her dog bed comfortably. 6 months ago she needed to be told repeated. "

Echo has more self control now and seems to be much more sensitive to how her companion dog and her two humans act and what they are asking of her rather than barging ahead with whatever she feels like doing. She never rushes toward her food before checking with us or the other dog to assess whether it's OK.  She's not a sneaky eater, although she is a sneaky toy-grabber and we can watch her strategizing to distract Pixel in order to create an opportunity to grab a toy from her. She's learning to howl with us. She stands quietly when it's time to get re-leashed after a dog park experience. She's picked up on reading us if it looks as though an outing is imminent.
His neuter calmed his Napoleon complex and he's accepted his ranking in our home pack as #2.
His hearing doesn't seem to be as good as it used to.

Because of Covid, my husband is working from home and Moose LOVES having him around so much. My husband takes him everywhere and I'm afraid Moose will be very sad when/if my husband ever returns to the office.

Since he has been on a vet-controlled diet, he's much more attentive to food, dropped, being eaten by others, etc. He also is much more adept at finding the odd container with tony bits of food remnants, disappearing with its, and enjoying his stolen delight.
She might be developing a hearing problem.

Because of the pandemic, with my husband working from home, it is rare for Noli to be left alone. She has become very attached to my husband, although she still sleeps with me and reacts with joy when I come home from work. I still work 5 days a week.
having more difficulty getting up onto the couch than she used to
No he is doing just great!
Rutherford seems to grave a routine. about 4 months ago he began asking for a walk right after his dinner. Where before he was content having it at anytime before his bed.
More focused when working sheep for longer periods of time. More confident when sheep turns on her.

He creates games either for himself or to get us engaged. For example he takes a ball to the top of the stairs and pushes it to roll down. He either retrieves it himself or waits for someone to toss it back up the stairs.

I adopted a puppy a few weeks ago.  I also adopted another dog about 8 months ago.  he's actually able to relax more, but is more active because the other 2 have a better matched energy style. I had never heard him growl until Olive was adopted, but she's all up in his face, too
No real changes in the past 6 months
There have been no distinguishable changes in the past six months.

About 1 1/2 month ago Ginger found that escaping outside my fence is a lot of fun.  I have a 12 acre fenced in yard - but outside the fence is where the bunnies go when she is in hot pursuit.  She does stick around so its easy to get her back in - then onto fixing the place she escaped.  She is very inventive and have no preconceived notions about what is proper.  Its a lot of fun as long as I'm in somewhat control...  One of my other dogs does not stick around so I'm happy she is the inventive one.
N/A I've only had him for about 4 months
Seldom leaves the house to investigate strange noises; she lets the other dogs do that and she barks from inside the house.
He seems to wake up suddenly and look around as if confused more often than 6 months ago.
He doesn't play as much as he used too.
He just had his front leg amputated. I'm very sure that the pacing is pain-related. I do not believe he is having cognitive issues.

He has a favorite pillow that he will suck on and go to sleep.  However the other day there were 5 soup bones that he had worked on and they were all over the family room.  I walked into the room and he had placed all the bones on the pillow!!???
No - it's been the same. She gets two walks a day averaging 1.5-4 miles a day / every day when weather allows. She doesn't sleep all day.
We got a couple of puppies and that has actually stimulated him more.  He appears a little more active and engages with the puppies.
I think the biggest changes with Chancellor are more physical than mental - I think he's got arthritis, and I think his eyesight is diminished.

"My dog had a much more active lifestyle when we lived in Austin, but given the time frame (going on a decade since the move), it's hard to know whether that's age or the amount of time away from daily socialized play. We did go to the sprawling dog park here for him to swim and play at least once a week, but between me getting a much smaller car, and the pandemic, that's dropped to zero. In a nutshell, he gets 95% less socialization then he ""grew up"" with, and that any dog should get every day, and I think it's been very bad for him."
Only that she seems to sleep more during the day. And she tires a little more easily when we take her for a run.

Honey has developed selective hearing. She frequently (but not always) has difficulty hearing us call her, and has become markedly less responsive to commands. She lost her companion in the spring, and we adopted a much larger, younger male dog in July. Both have been stressor for her. She does get more walk time now, though, and her stamina has increased.

"I got her as a rescue 6 months ago, so had no ""baseline"" for her cognition or activities.  She has definitely found her space and awareness of her surroundings, and has mellowed a bit (she was really mellow when I got her).  "
He seems a little more calm and able to pay attention to us or be distracted from things now.
7 1/2 years old.  Seems to be slowing down very slightly in energy and stamina.  Again, very slightly.
She is more alert to things like squirrels, barks at unfamiliar objects has decreased a bit, and has become more reluctant to do things she would rather not do such as kennel up at night.
His reflexes are not as fast and his smell ability is really a lot less.
"She is only three years old, so she has been steadily ""calming down"" from a more puppyish, hyperactive level of behavior."

She has learned she has to sit before I turn on the elevator. She now does this unprompted. She comes in, sits, and then we press the button. She must stay in the elevator (not move) till she is told it is ok. I will leave her in it, walk out as a test. She stays even as the motion light makes the elevator go dark.

Bing recognizes names of my friends. If they have a dog, gets excited.  All his toys have names and when asked to get the Toy by name, gets right toy.  Bing has been supportive of our older dog in hospice. Barks to let me know if something is wrong with Boofy.  At night he lays close to her.  Displays high level of empathy and compassion.
She is more affectionate, but it is most likely because she is trying to compete with our other dog, who is extremely affectionate (while Chrome has always been a bit more aloof)

Had seemed confused at times.  Vet began supplementing with 0.6 mg Thyro-tabs (synthroid?) for weakness and probable neural demyelination, cognitive functioning has improved somewhat.  In fact, he has learned to go in his crate when I point to its open door (it's where he eats and sleeps), without my having to give a command/request.  Sometimes he just doesn't want to, but it appears to be a choice now.

Most behavior has been pretty consistent over years. An exception is peeing in the house within the past year, which is very infrequent - he did it a few times, went months without, did it again a few times within a few weeks, long dry spell, so to speak, then a couple more incidents. Puzzling. Other than the time or two it happened during thunderstorms, haven't seen an obvious reason. More noticeable is just a physical slowing down. He still goes on long hikes, but he doesn't range as far and is less enthusiastic about higher exertion (hills, faster pace) or challenging conditions (loose rock, slick winter slopes).  I slow down runs now when he's along, and I've stopped taking him along for bike rides. Still, many people, including his vet, remark that he's in good shape for his age.

She is the same, actually she is better at knowing when is tune to play and when is rest time. She is a border collie... and rest time was very hard for her. We have a better schedule going now, as she is very active.

Oslo's appetite seems to be amplified over the past 6 months, possibly due to a health condition we're in the midst of trying to figure out. So he's exceptionally food motivated and very intense about doing his usual range of tricks in order to get treats. Without the obvious food incentive, however, he seems to be demonstrating slowed down cognitive activity. He definitely sleeps much more intensely now.
"Tovah has been training with the Dog Wizard. She now goes to her ""place"" when someone comes near the house or anther animal is outside.  She is following commands better that before training."

Chance is 3 yrs and 3 months old.  I adopted him when he was 10 months old.  He had been neglected, physically abused.  He was not house trained.  He was fearful of everyone and everything.  With time, love, patience and training, he became and is a wonderful pet still in the prime of his life.  I do know that if he lives to an old age, he will probably exhibit a lot of the behaviors in this survey because my border collie mix dog who lived to a month shy of 16 years did indeed exhibit a lot of these behaviors and it was heartbreaking to go through that period of her life with her.
Nothing new in the last 6 months.
I foolishly started giving him pieces of food while I was eating and now he begs whenever I get food out for myself.
She has learned the names of many of her toys, and brings the appropriate one when asked
I have not noticed any thinking or information processing changes in the last 6 months.
Sometimes has difficulty catching his treat in his mouth which May indicate a change in eyesight or depth perception.

He's pretty much the same. We had 2 good size earthquakes a week ago. He did not become nauseated by them nor reacted to them. We had a large earthquake 2 years ago with aftershocks that were very traumatic for him and many animals. He reacted to earthquakes and loud noises by becoming nauseated and drooling up until this summer.
Frederika is very active and sharp. The only signs of aging she has is cataracts and teeth having to be removed. She's is very strong and healthy.
His hearing has diminished so I find he uses vision and smell senses to accommodate.

Can't hear more of the time. Very hard to wake her up. Ripping up paper and other mild negative behavious she does now, but never did as a younger dog. Barks when we leave her now. Never did before. Very cooperative when younger.  Now quite stubborn and determined to do things her way,
Nope. She is just as active, crazy and velcro like as she has always been.
no change in the last 6 months

Sparky's field of view seems to have diminished because of his cataracts so that has taken a bit of his ability to key off of visual information thus impacting his thinking/actions/responses a bit.  His hearing has also diminished so he no longer can hear folks come into the house.  Once he sees his favorite people though he is all over & greeting them.
We've been training using a positive reward , cognitive based approach. She's having to think about and choose what is appropriate all the time. We can see her thinking
See's that I home more often. When I leave for periods of time and come back it's even harder for him to leave my side.

He became blind by SARDS a year ago and has degenerated continuously since then from a happy frisky senior dog to a depressed and confused one. He even seems to have trouble finding his way around the most familiar places and it is a struggle to get him to do anything, even going out to relieve himself. He may be partially deaf as well.
No changes, but she's still relatively young and still acts like a puppy for the most part.
Activity level is slightly less due to owner's choice-trying to ensure a healthy recovery from pancreatitis diagnosed 3 months ago.  Information & thought processing remains the same as always.
"It seems she has more ""active"" dreams, where her legs are in motion, and she's quietly yelping during sleep. Almost every day."

Lately he barks at the front door for no reason.  Since he is hard of hearing, it could be that he doesn't recognize sounds.  Or, it's possible that he hears us talking and thinks the sound is coming from outdoors.  Or, it's possible that he's getting a bit loopy.

Kilroy shows slightly more anxiety with sounds (especially Apple iPhone alert!)  He is also less inclined to go to school in the morning (he is a therapy dog and was visiting almost daily before COVID.)
We haven't noticed and concerning behaviors. He is a young, happy, active dog.
She seems happier because we are always around and she is not alone.

Six months ago he was getting ready for second CCL surgery (one on each back leg) of the year.  He is almost back physically to pre-surgery--able to do two mile walks in the park.  Of course, the change has been more physical than mental.  I have not noticed any thought or information processing changes in that time.
"We added an anti anxiety pill in October to see if she showed less worry when her ""dad"". Our son hasn't seen her in a couple days. Seems like she's the same. Maybe more relaxed. "

No, Piper is pretty social with familiar people and dogs.  When she first came to me in 2015, she was quite withdrawn, but became progressively more social over the next few years and is now well socialized.  It was very interesting and inspiring to see the gains that could be made by an older dog.

We don't know why but he seems to bark even louder and aggressive when he sees people walk by (he is inside looking out the window) or people walking their dog/dogs, delivery man, etc. Just as excitable or even more so when familiar people come into the house. Takes longer to settle down. We are thinking  about contacting a trainer. It could feel more so for us because of the pandemic? Just can't figure it out, but I know he's still puppy like for his breed even at two years old.
She seems to want to stay with me more. In the same room even when the rest of the pack is elsewhere

He likes bed time more and is happy to snuggle up with us or go in his crate of his own volition.  He will go in his crate and appears to sulk if he's not getting enough attention.  (He is a bit needy as a Havenese)

Zoe is now learning how to trick her sister the same way her sister tricks her. They will both now distract each other with a toy to get the other away from their ultimate goal (usually pets from mom and dad or a favorite bone).

Just a note about the amount of time spent active - as a result of COVID, Jackson is going to his doggy day care far less frequently than he used to. We have tried to increase the length of our near daily walks to adjust.

he is as smart (and shrewd) as ever. the only thing i notice that is different is that he asserts himself more/is a bit more stubborn, but at this point, i just go with his flow and follow his lead, as i want him to be happy...and i know my time with him is limited.
Bridget is maturing and easier to work with.

He used to turn to know exactly when we would reach our house at the end of his walks and would turn down the driveway. Now he does not, and sometimes tries to go into the neighbor's house. He also used to have to be the first one in the door and would run through it. Now we have to encourage him to go in and he will stop in the doorway.
"She has started ""guarding"" the house more. While friendly she's very vocal when anyone comes to the door. "

"She seems to take more time orienting or ""thinking"" before making decisions on where to go or what to do...like a pause. It's like a dementia type of behavior...where am I...oh, yea..that's where I was going/what I was doing...."

Early morning walks (first of the day) for her to pee/poop and to get some exercise for both her and us, generally walking thru our neighborhood.  Originally K.LEE wanted to go for walks in the early morning.  Now she expects to be let out into our fenced back yard for early morning pee/poop.  When shown her leash which she knows it's for going out for a walk, she heads for one of the bedrooms and has to be coaxed out (hand signals) so she can be leashed up and taken for a walk and a bathroom break.  She will walk about a block in the neighborhood, peeing wherever she gets a hit (marking some other dog's spot), pooping once (her general bowel movement amount) and then turning back towards her home.  During the day, we take K.LEE on a walk (1.5 to 2.0 miles) both on and off-leash (wooded area) in our neighborhood.  Once or twice a week she may indicate that she does not want to go for a walk by again going into a bedroom and lying down when she sees her leash, recognizing that we are going for a walk with her.  We may leave her in the house or take her out with us.  If she comes with us, she seems to enjoy the walk and all the smells she encounters and potentially marks.  We think she must have a 2 gallon bladder for all the peeing she does. :)
None, she's very alert and smart and ready for any kind of activity.

She's only 14 weeks old. I  wish there was an option in the responses to say, she didn't even exist 6 months ago. You are including people with puppies and there is no baseline for 6 months ago in some of these cases.

She seems to be doing really well.  We moved a few months ago, and she settled in quickly to our new home, knows when we're headed to one of our favorite dog parks, etc...
i think Tilly might be starting to loose her hearing a little. I noticed she can still obey verbal commands, but only when i am facing her.

My dog's sister was his companion from 2 yrs old until she died in Feb.  At first my dog seemed lethargic and sad but lately he has begun to play with me again and has played with his favorite toy again

A bit more aware, as we got a new puppy after our other older dog passed. Maybe not really thinking or processing, but just more watchful of the puppy and keeping an eye on him that he wouldn't do for our older dog that passed.

Not really. She is still somewhat leash reactive. I've been trying to distract her with treats when other dogs come our way. She is fine with dogs she has gotten to know, but unpredictable with new dogs, especially those also on leash.
She is a young dog who is an hunting dog.  In the last six months she has gotten notably better.

Just today, we took Peewee to the vet where he was diagnosed with Horner's syndrome. I know it is not thinking or information processing but it might be affecting his thinking or information processing. He also seems to need more companionship in the evening.

Buddy has started to experience hearing loss this year, so we are still at the point where we are trying to assess what is attributable to this and what might be caused by other factors.   Regardless of whether he's not hearing us or just ignoring us, he has developed a bit of a more stubborn streak lately - for instance when we go for a walk - if we aren't taking the route that he prefers, he just stops and stands there, and will pull against his lead.  He's rarely done this in the past.
He had a little difficulty with our isolation. He wants to interact with any dog he sees on our walks, and I now hesitate to let him do hellos because of COVID.
"As a terrier, he is a very active and curious dog.  If anything, he seems to have ""mellowed"" in his behavior and is somewhat more purposeful in his curiousity and his relationships with people."

Rooster seems to think before doing mischievios thing like if hes going to steal the cats food he will go into the kitchen stop look back at us myself and the cat as if to see if we are going to stop or say something before continuing to the cats food.
Rosie was diagnosed with anxiety disorder in the last three months so her thought and information processing is improving now that she is on prozac to help her calm down and think rationally.
He learned that when we spell the word foot he is going to get a pigs foot as a treat. So now we say Snort Snort.
She hasn't experienced any changes. She has wanted to go on walks more because we are home more during pandemic. She barks at us and leads us to the leash basket every evening, more than she used to.
She seems to be reverting back to puppy behaviors and does not always respond to her name.
She sometimes bumps her nose on furniture or doorway but our vet reports her vision and hearing are still quite good.

My dog has become MORE much affectionate with me. He really thinks he's a lapdog now. He is also much more protective over me with other dogs. I can't pet them or he'll become aggressive. He's also much more prone to bark back at other dogs on our walks around the neighborhood. He used to ignore dogs who barked from behind fences, or walk up to the fence and just stare. Now, he barks back. I'm sure part of it is all the quarantine time we've been spending together.

She seems to have become less time aware than before. It used to be that she'd cry to wake me up at 5:34 every morning and now she sometimes doesn't cry until 6. Same with our bedtime. Used to be she'd take herself to bed at a specific time and now she doesn't.  She's also more forgetful of our routines. Used to be that I'd feed her and then feed myself and give her some of it and then she'd go outside and I'd usually come out shortly after to give her a treat or play. Now if I take too long between feeding her and feeding myself she'll wander outside and just wait there looking at the door for me to come out like she's forgotten that I haven't eaten yet and is just waiting for the step where I come out to see her.
He seems cognitively intact. The problem is arthritic/joint issues and probable pain
We have seen no changes in MacDougals activity level.

Not related to information or thinking, but comment on increased activity.  Kasai lost his main companion (14 yr old Lab x Pit Bull, spayed female) in February, 2020, and the second dog (12 yr old Min Pin, neutered male) died in July, 2020.  Approximately three weeks ago, we adopted a 3 year old spayed female Husky x German Shepard.  Kasai's attitude and activity have markedly improved.
His activity has been slightly less as we moved recently and he doesn't always want to walk when one human remains at home.

I rescued Sophie 7 years ago from a shelter in Kentucky and until recently she never barked.  This summer she finally began barking and growling when she sees someone she doesn't know approach the house.  I'm glad to see her doing this.  I feel she is finally comfortable and secure enough to know she won't get punished for barking.

She is sleeping much more. Most of her recognition issues stem from her blindness. She barks much less unless she hears something and does recognize if I have been around another dog.  Her smell and ears are excellent. She seems to be slowing down more rapidly in the last 6 months.

Ellie seems to have been traumatized by her human dad picking her up about five months ago. Since that time, she tends to purposely walk away from him unless he has food to share with her. She has cataracts and get Vision is impacted so she gets very skittish when you approach her.
Only that we are doing some new training to get her to stay on her bed during meals, and with the help of verbal clues and an ultrasonic remote, she's making good progress.

Swen certainly has entered into a canine dementia phase that comes and goes. He was a very sharp and alert service dog and while he has sort of rebooted mentally on occasion it is interesting that his Service dog training is such a physical part of his being that he still blocks me in to keep me from falling and stuff. He still tries to stay with me but he is what he is.

Due to Covid pandemic and having to be home all the time she is a lot less active than pre-covid when she used to attend doggie daycare 3-4 times a week. Additionally, she now exhibits stress if left alone, whereas in the past this never occurred.
Ridley's information processing has greatly IMPROVED--probably a combination of age, going from 18 mo to 2yo, and formal training--off leash-follows commands now.

Covid has being hard. I'm concerned with my dog catching Covid from other dogs or people and passing it to us. There's so many unknowns when it comes to this virus. Before the pandemic hit, I had Pegasus in puppy social class every Saturday. He loved to play. I was also taking the time to walk him and was taking service dog training classes. Then I had to home school 4 kids and we had to isolate our family. The trainings stopped and I'm still concerned with taking Pegasus out for walks. We started going out again when the kids went back to school in August. It was great, then Covid cases started increasing again and then I read an article on how people that walk their dogs are like 70% chances on catching Covid. That scare us again and we stopped the walks again. We have a big yard, so he does get plenty of exercise daily, but his lack of dog socializing is affecting him. I wish there was no Covid and I can take him to doggie parks. He barks at the neighboring dogs when then walk by the house. I know he wishes to play. He is starting to bark at the kids and neighbors that pass by too. I used to take him to the bus stop and all the neighbors and kids will let him and he loved it. None of the neighbors have touch him since March. But he gets plenty of love from our family of 6, but I wish he could socialize more. I can't wait for Covid to be over. By the way, I contacted the animal clinic and gave them all you guys info and ask them to forward the info, but it's up to them whether they want to share the info. Sorry.
he has learned to sit but not stay and we are working on returning with fetch
Just becoming more of a bum. Doesn't want to play as much. Still excitable, but aware of his limitations. Stumbles sometimes running.

Pearl went through tests in July to determine why she has never put on weight and to see if malabsorption and/or a food allergy was to blame for her behavior issues (chronic vomiting and diarrhea, urinating inside for 18 months and reactivity towards dogs and some people). The tests didn't point to anything specific, but we switched her to a prescription diet. She is now nearly at an ideal weight, and her behaviors are slightly better. Most notably, urinating indoors has stopped.

"She's a Golden - so she's got ""quirks"". She's afraid of the weirdest things like brooms and blowing leaves - and when the neighbor uses an air compressor she won't go outside. On the other hand, when I use a chain saw we have to put her inside because she'll put her nose right up to it - even if it's on. Same thing with the circular saw. And when she gets on a bed, she needs to be ""invited"" off (you'd think it was the opposite and she should be invited on the bed, but she hops right up like it's hers). So if I leave the room with her on the bed, she stands up and cries and cries and cries - for a while - like she can't get off herself, until I go back in the room and tell her its OK to get off the bed, then she jumps right off."
No doesn't seem to be any changes
She still acts like a puppy!

Celine has seemed more calm in evenings for the last 6 months. Previously she seemed more more excited by all stimuli in the evenings. We suspect this may be due to having more people home during the day due to COVID.
Sometimes she opts for selective listening. I had to drag out her beep collar (used occasionally now) as a reminder.

She is more nervous about loud noises such as thunder or gunshots. She is more dependent on my husband and seems to need to know where he is and want to follow him around. She is friendly with strangers when we are with her but is shy and nervous around men she does not know even when we are standing with them.
He doesn't go to his toy box every day like he used to. Also he becomes nervous when our phones receive notifications and will leave the room. Totally a new behavior
